<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A0352 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">RUDOLPH</ENAMEX> -OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-02</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">RUDOLPH</ENAMEX> -OBIT-NYT
(<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ala.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX> ATTN)
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ARTHUR RUDOLPH</ENAMEX>, DEVELOPER OF SATURN 5 ROCKET, AT 89
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">WOLFGANG SAXON</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Arthur Rudolph</ENAMEX>, the developer of the giant Saturn 5 rocket that
launched a crew of American astronauts on the first manned flight
to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">moon</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1969</TIMEX>, died <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> after he lapsed into a coma at his
home in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hamburg</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>. He was 89.
<p>
   He left the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1984</TIMEX> and moved back to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>
after the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice Department</ENAMEX> accused him of ``working thousands of
slave laborers to death'' while director of the German factory that
produced the V-2 rocket in World War II. He denied the accusation.
<p>
   His death was reported in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Huntsville</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ala.</ENAMEX>, by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hugh McInnish</ENAMEX>, a
friend and retired military specialist who said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> died in an
ambulance on the way to a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hamburg</ENAMEX> hospital.
<p>
   He was one of 118 Nazi rocket engineers secretly brought to the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> after the war. The scientists included <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wernher von
Braun</ENAMEX>, the father of the American rocket programs.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> was a key figure in the Apollo Project at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Marshall
Space Flight Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Huntsville</ENAMEX>, one of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s principal
installations. A member of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">von Braun</ENAMEX>'s team, he was the project
manager for the Saturn, a vital and complex component of Apollo.
<p>
   As project manager, the sheer size of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">moon</ENAMEX> rocket was the
source of his nightmares during its development and construction.
``It was all harder than I ever expected,'' he told an interviewer
in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1969</TIMEX>. ``Since it is so large and has so many components, you get
more people involved, and that makes it difficult. You have to get
them all to sing from the same sheet of music. My task has been as
choir director.''
<p>
   Besides a few top colleagues from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, the project involved
some 100,000 people and several thousand industrial contractors who
designed, built and tested rocket parts and the Saturn 5 itself.
The cost was <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$15 billion</NUMEX> by then for the 15 rockets on order.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Huntsville</ENAMEX> Saturn team got the green light in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early 1962</TIMEX> and
found that putting the enormous machine together proved one of the
toughest engineering and manufacturing feats ever.
<p>
   ``You want a valve that doesn't leak and you try everything
possible to develop one,'' he said. ``But the real world provides
you with a leaky valve. You have to determine how much leaking you
can tolerate.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX>'s association with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">von Braun</ENAMEX> started in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Peenemuende</ENAMEX>,
where scientists made the V-1 and V-2 rockets for the German war
machine.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Von Braun</ENAMEX> also was a target of accusations about his past but
countered that he was a scientist dedicated to rockets and space
flight and nothing else.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> first joined forces with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">von Braun</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1934</TIMEX> and
remembered igniting his early rockets with lighted cigarettes.
<p>
   At the time of his entry into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> was
described by the American military government in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX> as an
``ardent Nazi'' but he was not classified as a war criminal. But
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army</ENAMEX> documents from <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two years later</TIMEX> showed that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> had indeed
been classified as a war criminal by West German and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
officials.
<p>
   These documents surfaced when the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Office of Special
Investigations</ENAMEX> was formed in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice Department</ENAMEX> to investigate
war crimes. The office conducted an investigation and interviewed
survivors of forced labor at the V-2 factory.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Fred Sher</ENAMEX>, the director of special investigations, said this
evidence was presented to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> and he signed a document agreeing
to relinquish his <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> citizenship. In return the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice
Department</ENAMEX> agreed not to pursue his case in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice Department</ENAMEX> handed the information over to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">West
Germany</ENAMEX>, but in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1987</TIMEX> the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bonn</ENAMEX> government ruled that there was
insufficient evidence to justify trying <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX>. Feeling himself
vindicated, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX> began trying to regain his American citizenship
and return to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Some present and former employees at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Marshall Space Flight
Center</ENAMEX> and elsewhere at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> supported him, saying <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph</ENAMEX>'s
contribution to the American space program never received the
proper credit.
<p>
   He is survived by his wife, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Martha</ENAMEX>, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hamburg</ENAMEX>; and a daughter,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marianne Rudolph</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Jose</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>
</TEXT>
