<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1595 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-03</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-SHUTDOWN-HNS
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> BEGINS RECALLING EMPLOYEES FOR SHUTTLE LAUNCH
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> began recalling several hundred furloughed
federal employees back to their posts at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX>
without pay on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, so the agency can proceed with plans to
launch the shuttle Endeavour on a mission to retrieve a Japanese
science satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Shuttle managers planned to convene <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Kennedy
Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX> to assess preparations to launch Endeavour
and an international crew of six on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 11</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``Right now, shuttle program managers are in the process of
exempting additional employees who are necessary for the
preparation and conduct of the mission,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Carr</ENAMEX>, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX>'s chief spokesman at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The precise number of employees being recalled was unavailable.
But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Carr</ENAMEX> said the agency was following a plan similar to one
imposed during a five-day furlough in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX> that coincided with
a shuttle mission to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s Mir space station.
<p>
   About 900 of the nearly 3,500 federal workers at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson</ENAMEX>
continued to work in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX>.
<p>
   When the most recent furlough began <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Dec. 15</TIMEX>, the space agency
fully exempted about 50 <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson</ENAMEX> workers, primarily for management
and security. Another 1,200 were exempted to work on an
``as-needed'' basis to keep <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> shuttle flight and space
station development plans on schedule.
<p>
   The space agency has successfully demonstrated to the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>
administration that long delays in either program could cost more
to recover from than to continue.
<p>
   Among the issues that shuttle managers will likely assess
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> is the status of funding for the large contractor work
force required to launch and fly Endeavour.
<p>
   A spokeswoman for the 4,000 workers employed under the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell
Space Operations Co.</ENAMEX> shuttle contract in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>
that the contractor has not furloughed any workers and forecasts
adequate funding through <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-03-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2018EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
