<DOCID> nyt960110.0604 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A8352 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-10</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> READIES ENDEAVOUR FOR <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">EARLY MORNING</TIMEX> LAUNCH
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CAPE CANAVERAL</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Working in chilly temperatures <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> ground crews readied the space shuttle Endeavour for
launch on a Japanese satellite retrieval mission.
<p>
   Endeavour, with an international crew of six, was set to blast
off from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">4:18 a.m. EST</TIMEX>, the
start of a 49-minute launching period. The <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine-day</TIMEX> shuttle flight
was to be the 12th launched in darkness.
<p>
   Forecasters offered a favorable weather outlook, as dozens of
technicians and engineers undertook the most hazardous portion of
the long countdown  &MD;  the pumping of explosive, supercold hydrogen
and oxygen propellants into Endeavour's 15-story fuel tank.
<p>
   The lone concern among mission managers was that temperatures in
the mid-40s, high humidity and light winds might permit the
unwanted formation of ice on the outside of the tank, in which a
half-million gallons of fuel are stored, much of it at temperatures
of 400 degrees below zero.
<p>
   ``If the winds abate somewhat, there is a concern that ice will
accrete on the tank, at least that it will at least be potentially
an issue,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ed Priselac</ENAMEX>, shuttle weather officer for the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX>. Should the ice shake
loose on launch, it could damage the orbiter.
<p>
   Once aloft, Endeavour commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Duffy</ENAMEX>, pilot <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brent Jett</ENAMEX>,
flight engineer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Winston Scott</ENAMEX> and mission specialists <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leroy Chiao</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Barry</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Koichi Wakata</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> will pursue the orbiting Space
Flyer Unit, an experiment-laden satellite launched by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 18</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The shuttle crew plans to snare the spacecraft with the
shuttle's robot arm <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Saturday</TIMEX> as the two spacecraft circle the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> at an altitude of just under 300 miles.
<p>
   Once berthed in Endeavour's cargo bay, the fliers will turn
their attention to the mission's other objectives. These include
the deployment and retrieval of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-owned spacecraft called
Spartan, which carries a half-dozen experiments.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chiao</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Barry</ENAMEX> have prepared for a pair of near
seven-hour spacewalks in which they plan to test hand tools,
equipment and spacesuit garb that will be required for the assembly
and maintenance of the planned international space station.
<p>
   The astronauts also plan three dozen medical, biotechnology and
engineering experiments, including an evaluation of how well a
half-dozen nursing rats can feed 60 baby rodents in a
self-contained enclosure that is being prepared for future shuttle
and space station use.
<p>
   ``This is an ambitious mission,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bryan Austin</ENAMEX>, the
venture's lead flight director. ``For the most part, every day will
hold a little something different for us.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-10-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2056EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
