<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960112.0403 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A0415 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-12</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
SHUTTLE DODGES <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AIR FORCE</ENAMEX> SATELLITE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Astronauts aboard the space shuttle Endeavour were
forced to dodge a derelict <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, as they sped
toward a rendezvous with the Japanese science spacecraft they plan
to retrieve and return to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   A small maneuver by shuttle commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Duffy</ENAMEX> and pilot
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brent Jett</ENAMEX> about two hours before the shuttle and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX>
satellite intersected allowed the two crafts to miss one another by
more than five miles. Without the maneuver, the two spacecraft
would have passed within eight-tenths of a mile of one another.
<p>
   ``It wasn't any big deal to us,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Duffy</ENAMEX> who told the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cable
News Network</ENAMEX> he and his colleagues were unable to see the 370-pound
satellite.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX> identified the
interloper as a Miniature Sensor Technology Integration satellite
launched into a polar orbit in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 1994</TIMEX> by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX>. The
launch was for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ballistic Missile Defense Organization</ENAMEX>, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>'s successor to the Strategic Defense Initiative or ``Star
Wars'' program.
<p>
   Experimenters lost contact with the satellite in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September 1994</TIMEX>
after a series of successful experiments with its cameras and other
sensors for missile tracking.
<p>
   ``We track an awful lot of things in space,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Bantle</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s mission operations directorate representative for the
shuttle flight.
<p>
   ``Occasionally, probably several times a flight, we are looking
very closely at a specific object, because it may be in
conjunction. Most of them track out of our concern.''
<p>
   According to a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Research Council</ENAMEX> report compiled <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
year</TIMEX>, more than 10,000 man-made objects larger than a softball and
tens of millions of smaller objects circle the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>, posing a
potential hazard to spacecraft. The largest objects are monitored
with radar and optical tracking devices by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S.
Space Command</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colorado</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Endeavour's astronauts are circling <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> at just under 300
miles, about 100 miles higher than on a typical mission, a factor
in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>'s near encounter. At a lower altitude, larger objects are
more likely to be pulled into <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere and burn up,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bantle</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Meanwhile, the shuttle crew closed rapidly on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s Space
Flyer Unit, the four-ton scientific satellite the astronauts plan
to retrieve <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Saturday</TIMEX>. The astronauts were more than 13,000
miles from the spacecraft when they lifted off <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Duffy</ENAMEX> was to maneuver Endeavour within 35 feet of the Space
Flyer Unit as the two spacecraft raced around <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> at nearly
18,000 miles per hour just before <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">4:30 a.m. EST</TIMEX>, allowing Japanese
astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Koichi Wakata</ENAMEX> to snare it with the shuttle's 50-foot-long
robot arm. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wakata</ENAMEX> was to berth the spacecraft in Endeavour's cargo
bay so it can be returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The Space Flyer Unit was developed by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s space community as
a reusable automated scientific satellite. It was launched from
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> for the first time on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 18</TIMEX> with nearly a dozen
experiments, including a small <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> astronomical observatory.
</TEXT>
