BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ASTRONAUTS EVALUATE TOOLS ON SPACEWALK
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Endeavour astronauts <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leroy Chiao</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Barry</ENAMEX> walked
in space for <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">six hours</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, evaluating tools and procedures for
the assembly and maintenance of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-led international space
station.
<p>
   ``Unbelievable, absolutely beautiful,'' gushed <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chiao</ENAMEX>, a
35-year-old chemical engineer, as he floated 192 miles over
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Australia</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">South Pacific</ENAMEX> while secured to Endeavour's
payload bay by a safety tether.
<p>
   ``The view is incredible,'' agreed <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Barry</ENAMEX>, a 42-year-old
physician-engineer. ``There is no other word for it, the colors are
so spectacular.''
<p>
   The two first-time spacewalkers tackled a range of tasks
simulating those that will be required to assemble the sprawling
station complex beginning in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1997</TIMEX>. Despite their rookie
status, the pair adapted quickly to their new environment; their
activities were an hour ahead of schedule at one point.
<p>
   The first of their tasks involved the conversion of the
shuttle's 50-foot-long robot arm into a high-tech cherry picker  &MD;  a
towering mobile work platform that could quickly move a
spacewalking astronaut and a variety of tools to far-flung work
sites. Similar mechanical devices are planned for the space
station.
<p>
   The second task required <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chiao</ENAMEX>, his feet planted on the mobile
work platform, and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Barry</ENAMEX>, tethered to the side of Endeavour's
payload bay, to install an 18-foot-long conduit across an expanse
of the ship's cargo hold. Similar apparatus on the space station
will enclose utility lines.
<p>
   Using hand tools, the two men practiced installing several kinds
of power and fluid cables and evaluated the ease with which several
types of fasteners could be connected and disconnected.
<p>
   ``The lessons we are learning here will be folded directly into
station design, so we can make sure it is a workable and mature
facility,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Daryl Schuck</ENAMEX>, who supervised the excursion from
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission Control</ENAMEX> at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Working closely with the spacewalkers were Endeavour pilot <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brent
Jett</ENAMEX> and Japanese astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Koichi Wakata</ENAMEX>, who operated the robot
arm. Astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Winston Scott</ENAMEX> is scheduled to join <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chiao</ENAMEX> on a second
spacewalk <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Wednesday</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott</ENAMEX> will test several spacesuit
improvements intended to permit work in conditions where
temperatures can be lower than 100 degrees below zero.
<p>
   The six-man shuttle crew plans to retrieve <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10 million</NUMEX>
Spartan science satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>. The spacecraft was deployed
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two days</TIMEX> of experiments.
<p>
   One of Endeavour's orbital cooling systems shut down abruptly
during <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>'s spacewalk. It was the third time since liftoff that
astronauts have had trouble with the flash evaporation system,
which is used intermittently with other cooling systems to
dissipate heat generated by sunlight and the shuttle's electronics.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Bantle</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> mission operations director, said engineers
believe a buildup of ice has clogged the system's plumbing. Some
shuttle electronics were turned off and other measures were taken
to prevent the problem from interfering with <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>'s activities.
<p>
   However, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bantle</ENAMEX> would not rule out the possibility that the
mission could be cut short if the system is not repaired.
<p>
   The shuttle is scheduled to land <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Saturday</TIMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
