<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ASTRONAUTS GRAB SATELLITE, PREPARE FOR SECOND SPACEWALK
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Space shuttle Endeavour astronauts snared their second
orbiting satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> and prepared for their second spacewalk
to test equipment for future assembly of an international space
station.
<p>
   Japanese astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Koichi Wakata</ENAMEX>, the shuttle crew's prime robot
arm operator, grabbed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10 million</NUMEX> Spartan science satellite
at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">4:47 a.m. EST</TIMEX> following a flawless rendezvous that placed the
two spacecraft side by side, 190 miles above the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pacific Ocean</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Koichi</ENAMEX> is two for two,'' Endeavour commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Duffy</ENAMEX>, who
flew the rendezvous with pilot <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brent Jett</ENAMEX>, told <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission Control</ENAMEX> at
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Early Saturday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wakata</ENAMEX> used the arm to grab the Space Flyer
Unit, a Japanese-launched science satellite circling nearly 300
miles above <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The 2,600-pound Spartan contained four experiments, each
intended to help spacecraft engineers develop materials and
electronics components for lower-weight satellites. The findings
will be studied after Endeavour lands.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Late Tuesday</TIMEX>, astronauts <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Winston Scott</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leroy Chiao</ENAMEX> were to
don bulky spacesuits for a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">six-hour</TIMEX> excursion into the shuttle's
open payload bay.
<p>
   During the spacewalk, which was to begin at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">11:56 p.m. EST</TIMEX>,
mission planners hoped to expose the two men to temperatures
averaging 100 degrees below zero, similar to those astronauts will
face during space station assembly, by turning the cargo bay away
from the sun and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s surface.
<p>
   The objective was to determine how well the improved garb will
keep the astronauts warm.
<p>
   The two also planned to assemble a portable work platform,
assess hand tools and evaluate the ease with which they can connect
and disconnect a variety of fasteners that are slated for use in
station construction.
<p>
   Meanwhile, shuttle managers on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> continued efforts to free
one of Endeavour's cooling systems of an ice jam, a problem that
has the potential to curtail the flight.
<p>
   Once the second spacewalk was under way, ground controllers
planned to raise the air pressure in the shuttle's crew cabin. The
higher pressure will permit them to flush the shuttle's iced flash
evaporator system with warm Freon. Engineers believe several
flushes will free the ice, as it has when similar problems arose on
past missions.
<p>
   ``I wouldn't say it couldn't happen,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Bantle</ENAMEX>, the mission
operations director, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> of a potential flight
curtailment. ``But now, we're very confident this process will
clear the ice.''
<p>
   Endeavour's <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine-day</TIMEX> mission is scheduled to end <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Saturday</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
