<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-18</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ASTRONAUTS PREPARE FOR TRIP HOME
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Their <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine-day</TIMEX> mission nearly complete, the Endeavour
astronauts slowed their work pace <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, enjoying a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">half-day</TIMEX> of
free time and preparing the shuttle for its return to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The six-man crew is scheduled to make a rare landing in darkness
at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:42 a.m. EST</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Forecasters expect a cold front to move through <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX>, leaving
clear, dry conditions.
<p>
   ``The weather looks real good,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> flight director <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff
Bantle</ENAMEX>, who will supervise the landing operation from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission
Control</ENAMEX> at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX> engineers touted
an experiment aboard Endeavour called the shuttle laser altimeter.
The low-power laser mounted in the payload bay has been fired at
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s surface more than 2.5 million times since Endeavour
blasted off.
<p>
   By recording the reflected signal, scientists at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Goddard
Space Flight Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenbelt</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Md.</ENAMEX>, have been able to measure
the elevation of a wide range of surface features, including the
volcano <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mauna Kea</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hawaii</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mount Everest</ENAMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Himalayas</ENAMEX>, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Red Sea</ENAMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Middle East</ENAMEX> and towering treetops in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Laos</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Each pulse of the laser produces an invisible splash of energy
about the size of a football field on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s surface, said
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Garvin</ENAMEX>, the project's science team leader.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Garvin</ENAMEX> said engineers hope to use the findings from the
experiment to develop a permanently orbiting instrument that could
be used to monitor changes in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s environment.
<p>
   Since blasting off <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 11</TIMEX>, the six-man shuttle crew has
retrieved a 300-mile-high Japanese science spacecraft called the
Space Flyer Unit, deployed and retrieved an experiment-laden <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>
satellite and conducted two long spacewalks.
<p>
   According to Japanese astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Koichi Wakata</ENAMEX>, the Endeavour
crew's robot arm operator, the flight has been a model of
international cooperation between his country and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United
States</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``I think international cooperation is the most important thing
in proceeding into the future frontier of space,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wakata</ENAMEX> told a
gathering of schoolchildren in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Johannesburg</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">South Africa</ENAMEX>, who
questioned the astronauts with the help of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United States
Information Agency</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The Japanese are <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s international space station partners
along with the space agencies of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
