<STORYID cat=f pri=u> A7669 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-SATELLITE-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-19</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SATELLITE-TV-NYT
CABLE COMPANIES PART WAYS ON STRATEGY FOR SATELLITE TV
(bl)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">EDMUND L. ANDREWS</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX> 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner Inc.</ENAMEX>, the
nation's two biggest cable television operators, have parted ways
in what had been a joint effort to launch satellite services that
beam as many as 150 channels of television directly to individual
homes.
<p>
   With the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Communications Commission</ENAMEX> scheduled to auction
off two valuable satellite licenses <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX>
announced <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> that it would be a bidder in competition with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI
Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> and perhaps several other companies.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX>' longtime partner in the satellite
television business, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar Partners</ENAMEX>, announced that it would
not be a bidder and had instead agreed to buy a separate and
somewhat less sophisticated and less powerful satellite.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX>, based in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bala-Cynwyd</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pa.</ENAMEX>, is a consortium owned by
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comcast Corporation</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Continental Cablevision</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Using an old pair of satellites that need to be replaced,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> has signed up nearly 1 million subscribers who receive
service on 36-inch-wide satellite dishes.
<p>
   The top provider of ``direct broadcast'' service is <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>, a
unit of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Communications</ENAMEX>, which uses high-powered satellites
to beam more than 100 channels of programming to pizza-sized
satellite antennas that can fit on a windowsill. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> has
slightly more than one million subscribers. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Communications</ENAMEX>
is a subsidiary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   Executives close to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> consortium said that
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner</ENAMEX> had disagreed about the wisdom
of bidding on licenses for high-powered satellite service, and that
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner</ENAMEX> executives believed it would be cheaper and more
practical to use a less ambitious technology for at least <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a few
years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   But the upshot of the rift is yet another bewildering media
alliance, in which companies are both rivals and partners at the
same time.
<p>
   If <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> wins a license <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>, it will be
poised to compete with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> or to supply satellite capacity to
some other new direct-broadcast rival.
<p>
   That would only further complicate the relationship Between
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-communications</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner</ENAMEX>. Because the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Denver</ENAMEX> company
owns a big stake of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Turner Broadcasting System</ENAMEX>, which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner</ENAMEX>
wants to buy, it could soon become a big shareholder in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time
Warner</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   On top of all that, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> recently formed an
alliance with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> to begin a
satellite-delivered sports television service. But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> is
also aligned with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>, which will bid against <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Executives at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> said they had no intention of
leaving the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> consortium. But if <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> wins
one of the new satellite licenses, it would have the capacity to
compete head-to-head with its old partners.
<p>
   It remains unclear whether that is the company's goal, and
executives at the company refused to discuss their plans in any
form.
<p>
   Meanwhile, several big telephone companies said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> that they
would not participate in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>'s auction. Among those declining
to bid on the new licenses are <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T Corp.</ENAMEX> and at least six of the
regional Bell companies  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nynex Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bell Atlantic</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwestern
Bell</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pacific Telesis Group</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ameritech</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US West</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> has long said it would be a bidder and would start the
bidding at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$175 million</NUMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> has teamed up with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> in a
broad media alliance, though the two companies have not said what
kind of services they plan to offer over the new system if they win
the bidding.
<p>
   The auction <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> is the result of a tangled legal and
regulatory battle that began more than a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year ago</TIMEX> when the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>
blocked <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar Partners</ENAMEX> from acquiring one of the last available
licenses for a direct-to-home broadcast satellite that could serve
the entire continental <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> had been planning to buy the license from a small
company that got it for free years ago and had never used it. But
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> decided that the company had waited too long to act on its
license and would be getting an undeserved windfall. So it refused
to allow the deal to go through and instead set up the auction that
will take place <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> is challenging the auction in court, and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Court of
Appeals</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> will hear oral arguments in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James L. Gray</ENAMEX>, chief executive of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar Partners</ENAMEX>, said
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> that his group had decided that bidding on a high-powered
license would be too expensive for the time being.
<p>
   ``To pursue high power didn't make sense,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gray</ENAMEX> said in an
interview. ``We had a need to move on. We felt we didn't want to
wait around for something as uncertain as this.''
<p>
   A person close to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner</ENAMEX> confirmed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> that it had run
into strong disagreements with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX>. The
high-powered satellites that would be operational with the new
licenses being auctioned off can reach smaller and less obtrusive
antennas about 18 inches in diameter.
<p>
   The medium-powered satellites used by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> currently
require antennas about 36 inches in diameter, though the new
satellite will allow slightly smaller antennas.
</TEXT>
