<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A1720 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>-AUCTION-UPDATE4-B </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-24</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0684 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>-AUCTION-UPDATE4-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>'S <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$332 MLN</NUMEX> BID LEADS ROUND 9 OF <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> AUCTION (UPDATE4)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Liza McDonald</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Rewrites top with update on the ninth round of bidding. Updates
share prices in the ninth paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 24</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI Communications Corp.</ENAMEX> led
the bidding in the ninth round of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Communications
Commission</ENAMEX>'s auction of a nationwide direct broadcast satellite
license with an offer of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$332 million</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar DBS Corp.</ENAMEX>, the other two
bidders in the auction, didn't bid in the latest round. Auction
rules provide for the use of five waivers for each of the three
bidders. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> took one of its waivers for the ninth round, while
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar</ENAMEX> was given a bye for making the highest bid in the eighth
round -- <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$313.3 million</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>, the nation's No. 2 long-distance phone company, plans to
develop its satellite service with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> if
it wins the license.
<p>
   The auction's tenth round has already begun. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> has put the
minimum bid for that round at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$348.6 million</NUMEX>, <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">five percent</NUMEX> higher
than the previous round's highest bid.
<p>
   The DBS license provides the rights to satellite perches for the
delivery of video and high-speed data transmissions that can be
picked up by 18-inch dishes. This kind of wireless capability could
allow phone companies and cable-TV providers to provide wireless
communications and data and video services throughout the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   The DBS license, one of only three that reach the entire
continental <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>, went on the block at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> auction
site at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">9:30 a.m. EST</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The commission will auction a second license, considered less
valuable because it reaches mostly just the western half of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> after the conclusion of the first auction. Only <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar</ENAMEX> have applied to bid on this license.
<p>
   In the opening round <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> had the highest bid at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$201
million</NUMEX> followed by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>'s <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$175.2 million</NUMEX> opening bid. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar</ENAMEX>, a
division of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar Communications Corp.</ENAMEX>, weighed in with a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$125
million</NUMEX> bid.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> shares were up 1/2 at 27 7/8 in <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX> trading. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>
shares were down 1/8 at 20 3/8. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar</ENAMEX> shares were up 3/8 at 24
3/8.
<p>
   The auction will continue until two of the bidders drop out,
which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> officials expect to happen sometime <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``The American consumer will be the real winner of this
auction,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott Blake Harris</ENAMEX>, chief of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>'s
international bureau. ``It will lead to the prompt introduction of
new DBS competitors and additional DBS service.''
<p>
   Still, most other companies considered potential bidders
--including all seven Baby Bell telephone operating companies,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sprint Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T Corp.</ENAMEX> -- didn't participate in the sale,
shrinking the field.
<p>
   Indeed, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T</ENAMEX> may have found a less risky, and quicker, way to
get into the business. The telecommunications giant announced
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> an agreement with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GM Hughes Electronic Corp.</ENAMEX> to market and
distribute <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> digital TV programming.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> said before the auction that it would consider using the
license to provide digital TV programming, similar to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>'
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> made a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2 billion</NUMEX> investment in <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s
international media company <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX> and plans several joint
ventures. The first, a sports pager service, was launched <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
October</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Customers can buy <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>'s 18-inch disks at an electronics
retailer, attach the disks to their homes and get as many as 150
channels of movies, sports and other programs.
<p>
   ``If <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> can get into the (media) game via satellite as a
competitive response, I think they should do it,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Craig
Ellis</ENAMEX>, an analyst with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Wheat First Butcher Singer</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The three bidders for the nationwide license had to pay <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10
million</NUMEX> in application fees, while the application charge was <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2
million</NUMEX> for the second slot.
<p>
   The down payments aren't counted against the final bid, and are
returned to bidders that don't win a license unless a bidder
engages in improper bidding, such as pulling out after making a
high bid.
</TEXT>
