<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A2238 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tab-z> BC-TV-SAT-DISHES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-24</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-TV-SAT-DISHES-NYTSF
LITTLE DISHES, BIG CHOICES: SO YOU WANT 150 TV CHANNELS?
(This ``separate-buy'' financial/lifestyle story is from the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Dec.
'95-Jan. '96</TIMEX> issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article,
it must be purchased  the rate is not prohibitive  from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York
Times</ENAMEX> sales representative <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CONNIE WHITE</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas City</ENAMEX> at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-444-0267, or fax her at 310-822-1444.)
(PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed  into the ``l''
lifestyle news and ``f'' financial news files.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MONICA CORCORAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Worth Magazine</ENAMEX>
(Distributed by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times Special Features</ENAMEX>)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">A few months ago</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ted Sturman</ENAMEX> invested in the future to buy back
a piece of his past.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sturman</ENAMEX>, a psychology professor at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">University of Southern
Maine</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Portland</ENAMEX>, sorely missed the sports teams of his native
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ohio</ENAMEX>  &MD;  so much so that he laid out nearly <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$700</NUMEX> for a satellite-TV
system that offers him the sports channels shown to the
Clevelanders back home.
<p>
   ``Now, I can watch an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Indians</ENAMEX> game at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> or settle down with
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cleveland Browns</ENAMEX> on a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>,'' says <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sturman</ENAMEX>, who's lived in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Portland</ENAMEX> for just over a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year</TIMEX>. ``I see local commercials from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ohio</ENAMEX>
that bring me back to my childhood.''
<p>
   The system <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sturman</ENAMEX> bought, however, hardly harkens back to the
Volkswagen-size satellite dishes of yore. The new satellite-TV
systems are more like Hot Wheels cars: smaller, sleeker, and soon
to be very affordable.
<p>
   Although not quite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two years</TIMEX> old, small-dish satellites setups
are already found in almost 2 million American households.
<p>
   Until the birth of these compact systems, a satellite-TV dish
spanned ten feet and cost around <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2,000</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Today</TIMEX>, a system requires an investment of just <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$200</NUMEX>, nestles
inconspicuously on the roof of a home or apartment building, and
delivers exclusive programming. And with newcomers joining the
satellite market soon, prices are expected to drop and choices to
multiply.
<p>
   ``Once the competition heats up, they'll probably start giving
the hardware away just to get eyeballs,'' says <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Scott</ENAMEX>, editor
of Satellite TV Week.
<p>
   For now, though, two small-dish satellite systems are available:
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RCA</ENAMEX> Digital Satellite System, which offers two programming
choices  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USSB</ENAMEX>  &MD;  and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RCA</ENAMEX> dish costs <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$550 to $1,000</NUMEX> (depending on the model) plus
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$199</NUMEX> for installation; <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> leases its dish for an up-front
payment of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$200</NUMEX>, including installation.
<p>
   But before beaming into space, know that network broadcasting is
not always included, meaning no ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Seinfeld</ENAMEX>'' or ``X-Files'' unless
the viewer gets a basic cable hookup (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10 to $25</NUMEX> per month plus
installation) or adds an antenna to get the local network
affiliates.
<p>
   Or the satellite company will zap you a network signal from a
distant city for a nominal fee.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>, which runs <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$29.95</NUMEX> a month, boasts a 65-network channel
menu similar to cable's (CNN, CNBC, etc.), 29 audio-only channels,
and 7 movie channels.
<p>
   And sports zealots take note: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> offers an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NFL</ENAMEX> package
(choose any of 13 games <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">every Sunday</TIMEX> for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$139</NUMEX>), an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NBA</ENAMEX> package (all
700 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">regular-season</TIMEX> games for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$149</NUMEX>), and an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NHL</ENAMEX> package (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$99</NUMEX> for the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">whole season</TIMEX>).
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last year</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> offered its Major League Baseball package for
free, but <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next year</TIMEX>'s edition will carry a price tag that has yet
to be announced.
<p>
   For premium channels, you need to add <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USSB</ENAMEX> to the mix. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USSB</ENAMEX>
carries 21 programming options for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$34.95</NUMEX> a month, including five
HBO, three Showtime, three Cinemax, and two Movie Channel channels.
<p>
   With <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX>, which for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$45</NUMEX> a month offers 90 channels, in
addition to the standard cable lineup, you can click from 16
regional sports networks to movie channels that show only westerns
or mysteries.
<p>
   There are also three HBO and two Cinemax channels airing
different shows, thanks to feeds from different time zones.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX> also offers season-long sports packages similar to those
on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   New providers are coming: In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-December</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AlphaStar</ENAMEX> launched
programming, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">EchoStar</ENAMEX> will debut in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``Unlike cable, the satellite industry is wide open to
competition,'' says <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott</ENAMEX>. ``There will be better prices and wider
variety as new companies emerge.'' After all, there's plenty of
room in space.
 &LR; 
</TEXT>
