<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CANADA</ENAMEX>-TV-TAX-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-31</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CANADA</ENAMEX>-TV-TAX-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CANADA</ENAMEX> STUDY URGES NEW TV CONSUMER TAX TO FUND STATE-OWNED <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William J. Willitts</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ottawa</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 31</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- State-owned <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canadian Broadcasting
Corp.</ENAMEX> should be financed through a tax on cable TV and
direct-to-home satellite services, rather than the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">C$1 billion</NUMEX>
(<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">US$727 million</NUMEX>) in federal grants it currently relies on, a
Canadian government report said.
<p>
   Former <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX> chairman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pierre Juneau</ENAMEX>, head of the panel that wrote
the report, said he was recommending ``significant changes'' for
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">50-year</TIMEX> old radio and television service that broadcasts
nationwide in both English and French.
<p>
   In order to avoid ``deep and damaging cuts,'' the committee
recommended a new <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">7.5 percent</NUMEX> ``Communications Distribution Tax''
to be applied to all cable and direct-to-home satellite services.
<p>
   The tax would be phased in over a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">five-year</TIMEX> period beginning
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this spring</TIMEX> and would ``free more than <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">C$800 million</NUMEX> a year either
for deficit-reduction ... or high-priority spending initiatives.''
<p>
   There was no immediate reaction from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rogers Communications Inc.</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX>'s largest cable television supplier, nor from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Toronto</ENAMEX>-based
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ExpressVu</ENAMEX>, which will soon launch its direct-to-home satellite TV
service. Canadian cable distributors, though, earlier criticized
the idea of new consumer taxes.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Juneau</ENAMEX>, who headed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX> for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE"><TIMEX TYPE="DATE">seven years</TIMEX> through <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1989</TIMEX></TIMEX>, was
commissioned <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last spring</TIMEX> by Prime Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jean Chretien</ENAMEX> after
deficit-cutting efforts looked likely to erode the broadcaster's
financing.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late November</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX> said it would lay off as many as 1,000
people by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late March</TIMEX> as it prepares to get by with <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">C$227 million
less</NUMEX> in government grants <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The new financing scheme would be made available for a
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">seven-year</TIMEX> period, at which time the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Radio Canada</ENAMEX>, the
sister French service, would have to present a new corporate
spending plan.
<p>
   ``To cushion the introduction of the levy somewhat for
consumers,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Juneau</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Newsworld</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RDI</ENAMEX>, the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">24-hour</TIMEX> cable
French- and English-language news services, should drop their
monthly subscriber fees that range up to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">C$0.90</NUMEX> a month.
<p>
   ``In no way would this restrict <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">parliament</ENAMEX>'s authority to change
the level of funding to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX>, but it would remove the
requirement for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Parliament</ENAMEX> to appropriate funds <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">every year</TIMEX>,'' the
report said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX> President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Perrin Beatty</ENAMEX> said existing funding plans would
cut an additional <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">C$350 million</NUMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBC</ENAMEX>'s budget by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 31,
1998</TIMEX>, from its current <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">C$1.065 billion</NUMEX> annual budget. The cuts are
part of Finance Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Paul Martin</ENAMEX>'s plan to reduce the budget
deficit to <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2 percent</NUMEX> of gross domestic product, from its present
level of <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">5 percent</NUMEX>.
</TEXT>
