<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A9598 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-RESEARCH-SHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-31</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-RESEARCH-SHIP-BOS
NEW RESEARCH SHIP FOR DEEP SEA EXPLORATIOIN READY
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">RICHARD SALTUS</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   A new ``mother ship'' to carry the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institute</ENAMEX>'s manned submersible, Alvin, and deep-diving robot
explorers is scheduled to be launched <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moss Point</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miss.</ENAMEX>, where the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$50 million</NUMEX> state-of-the-art ship was built.
<p>
   The 274-foot research vessel Atlantis will replace Atlantis II,
a smaller ship being retired after <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">33 years</TIMEX> of service for the
institute and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Navy</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   When work on its systems is completed in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1997</TIMEX>, the new Atlantis
will be among the most sophisticated oceanographic research ships
in the world. It has four times the on-board laboratory space of
Atlantis II, can carry more scientists, and has twice the endurance
at sea.
<p>
   ``This is a great event for us,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Pittenger</ENAMEX>,
associate director of marine operations for the institute, in a
telephone interview <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>. ``We just took a tour, and the ship
is absolutely magnificent,'' he said.
<p>
   Following the traditional christening with champagne, shipyard
workers plan to to send the 274-foot research vessel down greased
skids in a spectacular sideways launch, splashing it into a bayou
where it will rock back and forth before coming to rest upright.
<p>
   The ship's electronic systems and other equipment remain to be
installed during the ``fitting out'' period, scheduled to end with
delivery of Atlantis by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 15, 1997</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pittenger</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Equipped for general oceanographic research and to support
undersea exploration, Atlantis will serve as mother ship for Alvin,
the first deep-diving submarine, which was commissioned in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1964</TIMEX> and
has made more than 3,000 scientific dives. Also based aboard
Atlantis will be the JASON/Medea system of remotely controlled
undersea craft that can reach <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">98 percent</NUMEX> of the world's ocean
floor.
<p>
   The ship will also be home to the institute's new Autonomous
Benthic Explorer, a robot craft that can remain on the ocean floor
for as long as a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year</TIMEX> to observe marine life or monitor sunken
submarines or other potential sources of pollution.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Navy</ENAMEX> financed construction of Atlantis and, although it
will be operated under a charter agreement by the private,
nonprofit oceanographic institution, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> has the right to use
the ship and its submersible craft in the event of national
security emergencies.
<p>
   Atlantis is the third of four vessels being built for the
academic ocean research community.
</TEXT>
