<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A9664 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">RUSSIA</ENAMEX>-SPACE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-31</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">RUSSIA</ENAMEX>-SPACE-HNS
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> TABULATING COST OF SPACE STATION CONCESSIONS TO <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">RUSSIA</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> is weeks away from totaling the costs of a
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> administration decision to shoulder some of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s
financial burden for the planned international space station, a top
space agency official said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wil Trafton</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s acting spaceflight chief and space station
program director, also said the Russians have been warned they risk
expulsion from the project, if their financial and political
difficulties cause more upheaval. The decision to lighten <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s
responsibilities was made to keep the project on schedule.
<p>
   ``This can't go on,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Trafton</ENAMEX> said at a news briefing. ``We have
made it clear we are simply going to be unable to help them, if a
problem of this magnitude should arise in the future.''
<p>
   Assembly of the global outpost is to begin in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November 1997</TIMEX> and
conclude in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-2002</TIMEX>. Crucial early Russian components will provide
guidance and living space for three occupants by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">spring of
1998</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> are also involved in the project.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Late last year</TIMEX>, the Russians proposed a major design change that
would incorporate their <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10-year</TIMEX>-old Mir space station into the new
facility, a strategy intended to save them money and avoid the
political problems associated with decommissioning the venerable
outpost in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early 1998</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Earlier this week</TIMEX>, Vice President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Al Gore</ENAMEX> announced the
provisions of a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> counteroffer intended to keep the assembly
plans for the new international station on schedule, yet help the
Russians keep operating Mir until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the turn of the century</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> will increase from seven to at least nine the number of
shuttle flights it plans to Mir in order to ferry the food, water,
clothing and other supplies required to keep the Russian station
operating for an additional <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   In addition, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> shuttle will transport a Russian electrical
power generator to the new international space station in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1999</TIMEX>,
lowering from four to one the number of unmanned Russian rocket
launches required to loft the apparatus needed to power research
activities.
<p>
   The Russians also will likely lower the number of habitable
research modules they plan to contribute to the new station or
substitute less expensive components, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Trafton</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``There is no question there is an additional cost involved
here,'' he said. ``We still have our budget analysts out working
the numbers. We will probably have that number in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the next two to
three weeks</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Trafton</ENAMEX> hinted that the true cost may take much longer to
assess, at least until after a series of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX> meetings between
Russian and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> space experts in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX> to negotiate the full
range of requirements dictated by the concessions.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last year</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX>
flew two of seven planned docking missions to Mir scheduled through
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1997</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> is investing about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4 billion</NUMEX> on the missions. That
total includes a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$400 million</NUMEX> payment to the Russians for use of
Mir by a handful of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> astronauts for research and some hardware
for the new space station.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gore</ENAMEX>'s offer extends the number of shuttle flights to nine
through <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1998</TIMEX>.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> has agreed to discuss the possibility of flying more
than the nine missions to Mir, extending the program into <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1999</TIMEX>.
<p>
   So far, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Trafton</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> has identified only a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$124 million</NUMEX>
cost for the addition of one shuttle visit to Mir, a figure that
could triple or quadruple if <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. General Accounting Office</ENAMEX> figures
are substituted.
<p>
   By the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX> meeting, negotiators will have assessed new cargo
preparation costs and additional experiment preparation expenses.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> has asked the Russians to modify the interior of their Soyuz
crew capsules to accommodate larger <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> astronauts, an expense
that may be weighed against the new <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> costs.
<p>
   The three-person Soyuz capsules will serve as lifeboats for
crews stationed aboard the international space station during its
assembly.
</TEXT>
