<DOCID> nyt960205.0556 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A4248 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=sci-z> BC-ASTEROID-PROBE-SCI-2N </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-05</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0822 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-ASTEROID-PROBE-SCI-2NDTAKE-NYT
UNDATED: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Planetary Society</ENAMEX>.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The plan for an orbital mission to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eros</ENAMEX> has been aggressively
promoted by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Daniel S. Goldin</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s Administrator for nearly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">four
years</TIMEX> and a champion of doing things smaller, cheaper, better,
faster, as he puts it. The flight is the inaugural mission of the
Discovery Program, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> initiative for small planetary missions
with a maximum <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">three-year</TIMEX> development time and a maximum cost of
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$150 million</NUMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eros</ENAMEX> probe is known officially as NEAR, for Near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>
Asteroid Rendezvous. It is scheduled for liftoff on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 16</TIMEX> from
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cape Canaveral</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX> The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jet Propulsion Laboratory</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pasadena</ENAMEX> is
to navigate the craft on its journey of more than a billion miles
through space, as the laboratory has done for all of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s
deep-space missions.
<p>
   The voyage to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eros</ENAMEX> is complex because the asteroid orbits the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sun</ENAMEX> at an angle 10.8 degrees off that of the disklike plane that
the planets whirl through, loping down many millions of miles below
that horizontal layer in its rush through the solar system. The
probe, to achieve the rendezvous, must match this unconventional
orbit.
<p>
   After its launching, the spacecraft is to swing out far past the
orbit of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX>, passing by the large asteroid <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mathilde</ENAMEX> on this leg
of the journey and possibly photographing it, and then come
barreling back toward <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> for a close flyby in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January 1998</TIMEX>. At
this point flight controllers will use the planet's gravity to
increase the probe's speed and change its orbital plane to match
that of the prime target.
<p>
   Final maneuvers are to begin in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January 1999</TIMEX>. As the spacecraft
approaches <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eros</ENAMEX>, it will begin firing a large rocket engine to slow
itself down and match the asteroid's speed, making its first close
encounter in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February 1999</TIMEX> at a distance of about 300 miles.
<p>
   If no dangerous satellites are discovered that would hamper a
closer approach, the probe will slowly be maneuvered toward the
asteroid until in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 1999</TIMEX> it reaches its optimal orbit for
scientific study of 20 to 30 miles high. The detailed observations
are to last until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the end of the millennium</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The main scientific aims of the mission are to measure the
asteroid's size, shape, volume, mass, gravity field, spin state,
surface composition, geology, morphology, texture, mass
distribution and magnetic field. To do so, the probe carries a
camera, a gamma-ray spectrometer, a near-infrared spectrograph, a
magnetometer and a laser range finder, among other instruments.
<p>
   Scientists believe that clues to the nature of the early solar
system are preserved on small bodies like asteroids. In contrast,
the cosmic records of large, planetary bodies have been altered or
destroyed over the ages by the traumas of planetary evolution. In
particular, near-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> asteroids are thought to hold clues to the
nature of the building blocks of the inner planets, including
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   In addition to raw scientific insights, the mission to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eros</ENAMEX> is
seen as possibly yielding a flock of findings that may help
humankind wrestle with the possibility of killer rocks descending
on the planet from space. First, a better understanding of
asteroids would aid predictions of how the rocky bodies would
interact with the atmosphere and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> upon fiery impact. Second,
it would aid possible safeguards.
<p>
   ``The more knowledgeable one is about these objects,'' said Dr.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clark R. Chapman</ENAMEX>, a senior scientist at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Planetary Science
Institute</ENAMEX>, based in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tucson</ENAMEX>, and a member of the mission team, ``the
more we can figure what we'd have to do to move them or otherwise
get out of harm's way.''
<p>
   In recent years, scientists have speculated about using bombs or
rocket engines to nudge threatening asteroids out of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s path
or to destroy them.
<p>
   Scientists are closely watching the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eros</ENAMEX> mission not only for
its insights but as a critical test of the space agency's new
small-is-beautiful philosophy, which is sometimes viewed
skeptically by a generation of experts that relied on large budgets
to push the glory days of planetary exploration to the dim edges of
the solar system and beyond.
<p>
   ``These things are being touted as a whole new way of producing
science cheaply,'' said Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joseph A. Burns</ENAMEX>, an astronomer at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cornell University</ENAMEX> who is a past chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Committee on
Planetary and Lunar Exploration</ENAMEX> at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Academy of
Sciences</ENAMEX>, a private group that advises the government. ``But it's
not clear that the science return per <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">dollar</NUMEX> is going to be there.
It's an experiment.''
<p>
   But the chief scientist of the rendezvous mission, Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrew F.
Cheng</ENAMEX>, an astrophysicist at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johns Hopkins University</ENAMEX>, said no
corners had been cut to develop the spacecraft, which relies on
many more miniaturized components and innovative materials than did
past probes.
<p>
   ``It's a full-science mission in the grand old tradition,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Cheng</ENAMEX> said. ``But it doesn't bust the budget.''
</TEXT>
