BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ASAHI</ENAMEX>-SHUTTLE (GENERAL)
FOR RELEASE: <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">FRI., FEB. 9, 1996</TIMEX>
BAD WEATHER GROUNDS SHUTTLE LAUNCH
C.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Asahi News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TOKYO</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s first test launch of its space shuttle prototype
didn't get off the ground in the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX> of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 9</TIMEX> because of rain.
It was the third time the launch has been postponed.
<p>
   The Hyflex shuttle/glider was scheduled to make a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">15-minute</TIMEX>
unmanned flight from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tanegashima Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kagoshima
Prefecture</ENAMEX>, beginning at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">7 a.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   Officials rescheduled the test for <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">7 a.m.</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 11</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Hyflex was supposed to shoot up through the atmosphere on its
Japanese-made J-1 booster rocket, then fall back down without
orbiting <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>. It has been programmed to land in the sea around
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ogasawara Islands</ENAMEX> 1,000 kilometers south of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tokyo</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The flight was to test the craft's ability to withstand the
extreme heat of reentering the atmosphere.
<p>
   Like the American space shuttle, the Japanese prototype is
covered with a special material made of carbon designed to
withstand temperatures of up to 1,500 degrees. The unpowered craft
is much smaller than the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> space shuttle. It is designed to
gather data on how to design more sophisticated craft.
<p>
   The launch was postponed on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 1</TIMEX> because of a functional
problem and again on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 7</TIMEX> because of unstable weather around the
landing area.
<p>
   Officials said the J-1 rocket is not able to withstand wet
weather.
<p>
   The repeated postponements caused alarm among officials at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Space Development Agency</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>, the Japanese version of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>, because <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">one day</TIMEX> of delay costs <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">30 million yen</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$286,000</NUMEX>). The
sum includes personnel costs.
<p>
   Fine weather was forecast for the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tanegashima</ENAMEX> area on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 11</TIMEX>.
However, it is expected to be stormy around the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ogasawara</ENAMEX> region.
<p>
   Hyflex is the first experimental craft in jA919M'' &QC; 5U%1
9*9599A !UQQ1''!Q &QC; U1IIejQI%1M'' &QC; 
95J9QI9Q% &QC; 91A QQ% &QC; 99''+$<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U7ited States</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX> plan to complete
the space station by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2002</TIMEX>.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 10</TIMEX>, another small rocket is scheduled to be launched
from the town of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Uchinoura</ENAMEX>, also in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kagoshima Prefecture</ENAMEX>, which
means the Hyflex cannot go aloft until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 11</TIMEX> at the earliest.
</TEXT>
