<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A5598 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">COMSAT</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">INTELSAT</ENAMEX>-CORRE </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-15</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0896 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">COMSAT</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">INTELSAT</ENAMEX>-CORRECT-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">COMSAT</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> AGENCIES PROPOSE <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">INTELSAT</ENAMEX> RESTRUCTURING (CORRECT)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Liza McDonald</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Adds comment from <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gerard Klauer</ENAMEX> analyst; corrects consortium
membership to 136 in 2nd paragraph; rewrites paragraph 6; corrects
company name in paragraph 8 to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX>.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bethesda</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Maryland</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 15</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat Corp.</ENAMEX> and the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government proposed a restructuring of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> that would
include a sale to the public of a portion of the international
telecommunications and broadcast satellite operator.
<p>
   The proposal, which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> says may be challenged by others in
the 136-nation consortium that owns <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>, is unrelated to the
loss <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX> of a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$204 million</NUMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> satellite in a failed
launch attempt in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Instead, it reflects massive competitive changes that have taken
place in the satellite business -- particularly for the
long-distance telephone services -- in recent years, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX>
officials said.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> was derived <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">30 years ago</TIMEX> to provide service in a
monopoly environment,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Mattingly</ENAMEX>, vice president and
general manager for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat World Systems</ENAMEX>. ``There's no longer a
monopoly environment.''
<p>
   Competition from private satellite communications providers like
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenwich</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Connecticut</ENAMEX> based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> and fiber optic
telecommunications carriers ``is growing like gangbusters,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mattingly</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   That cuts into the business <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> provides
to companies like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI Communications Corp.</ENAMEX>, which
use their satellites to route their overseas calls.
<p>
   For <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX>, which owns <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">19 percent</NUMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>, the preferred
solution is to divide <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> into two separate entities. One
would have public shareholders, like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX>, and would be
structured to compete in the satellite ``markets of the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">90's</TIMEX> and
beyond,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mattingly</ENAMEX> said. The remainder of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> would remain a
cooperative intergovernmental organization that would continue to
provide basic public network services.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Today</TIMEX>'s proposal could take years to be put in place. Even so,
shares of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> jumped 2 7/8 to close <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> at a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">52-week</TIMEX> high of
25 3/8. The total of 1.6 million shares was almost seven times its
average daily volume for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last six months</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> plans to present the proposal to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>'s board of
governors in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mattingly</ENAMEX> said. If it wins approval from the
governors at its <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 1997</TIMEX> meeting, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> would like to see it
implemented ``shortly thereafter,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mattingly</ENAMEX> said. An offering
could then take place at the earliest about a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year later</TIMEX>, he said.
<p>
   Still, ``there will be competing proposals'' from some of the
other 135 <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> members, he said. ``We expect there to be a
couple of alternative approaches. What we have is not the end but
the beginning,'' he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> were both created in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early 1960s</TIMEX> when
satellites were first developed to carry telephone calls and
broadcast signals. No <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government funds are invested in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX>,
the company says, but reflective of its original sponsorship, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> president names three of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX>'s 15 board members.
<p>
   In addition to its investment in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> also owns the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Denver Nuggets</ENAMEX> team in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Basketball Association</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   For now, though, the focus is how to handle the big changes
under way in how long-distance providers like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI
Communications Corp.</ENAMEX> route their calls overseas.
<p>
   Long distance phone companies have largely replaced their use of
satellites with fiber optic lines, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles DiSanza</ENAMEX>, analyst at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Gerard Klauer Mattison</ENAMEX>. ``With all the fiber capacity, and with
renewed satellite competition, the industry is pretty much wide
open.'' Still, he said, ``you still need satellites to get places
where the lines aren't. When a call needs to go to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Nigeria</ENAMEX>, it goes
via satellite.'' Other industry officials question why governments
should provide that service. ``The industry has changed so much
that it has become questionable to have a government-sponsored
entity performing these functions,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael Alpert</ENAMEX>, former
senior officer at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> who now is president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Alpert and
Associates</ENAMEX>, a communications consulting firm in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>'s assets, including satellites, would be divided almost
evenly between the existing organization and the new company,
according to the plan developed by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> in conjunction with a
task force of government officials from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State</ENAMEX>
and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> departments and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Communications Commission</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Initially, the existing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> company would own all of the
stock of the new company, though the proposal calls for <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">60 percent</NUMEX>
of the stock to be sold to investors within a year of the new
company's creation, with an additional <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">20 percent</NUMEX> in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next two
years</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bethesda</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Maryland</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mattingly</ENAMEX> said the sale of stock would be undertaken globally.
No underwriters have yet been suggested, he said.
<p>
   The proceeds from the public stock sales would be used to reduce
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>'s debt and improve its ability to provide global
communications, as well as provide working capital for the new
company.
<p>
   The new company would be publicly funded and free to purse other
market opportunities worldwide on a fully commercial and
competitive basis, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comsat</ENAMEX> said.
</TEXT>
