<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-21</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
SHUTTLE MISSION TO PULL EUROPEAN SPACE EFFORT INTO SPOTLIGHT
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CAPE CANAVERAL</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>'s budding human space program is
poised to step into the spotlight with the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, Italian astronauts <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Maurizio Cheli</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Umberto
Guidoni</ENAMEX> are set to join veteran Swiss astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Claude Nicollier</ENAMEX>
and four Americans aboard the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> shuttle Columbia to blast off on
a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two-week</TIMEX> mission.
<p>
   When the shuttle settles into orbit, there will be 12 astronauts
circling the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>  &MD;  the seven-person Columbia crew, four Russians
and German <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Thomas Reiter</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Two Russians and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reiter</ENAMEX> are aboard the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">decade</TIMEX>-old Mir space
station. Two Russians are on a Soyuz capsule launched from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Central
Asia</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Wednesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Columbia is to blast off from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> during
a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2 1/2 hour</TIMEX> period that begins at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">3:18 p.m. EST</TIMEX>. Ideal weather
conditions were forecast.
<p>
   The shuttle crew plans experiments with a small Italian
satellite they will unreel to a distance of nearly 13 miles on a
thin tether. They hope to show that the tether will generate an
electrical current as it whips through the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s magnetic field.
<p>
   ``<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tomorrow</TIMEX>, 12 astronauts will be together in orbit  &MD;  four
Americans, four Russians and four Europeans,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jean-Jaques Dordain</ENAMEX>
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>. ``As you can see, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX>
is fully dedicated to manned space flight.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dordain</ENAMEX>, director of strategy, planning and international policy
for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX>, called the mission ``a new step toward the international
space station where the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX> but also
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> will work as partners, paving the way toward the
international exploration missions of the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">21st century</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   Assembly of the station is to begin in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1997</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Few would argue that the 14-nation <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX> is near
parity with the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> or <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX> in terms of space
exploration. But as the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next few weeks</TIMEX> may demonstrate, the
consortium plans to make significant gains by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of the
millennium</TIMEX>, building on the experiences of its senior partners and
setting its own goals.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX> watched from the sidelines in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1961</TIMEX>, when the former
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Soviet Union</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> lofted the first humans into
space. Later, Europeans watched as the two superpowers spent
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">billions</NUMEX> competing to explore the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">moon</ENAMEX>, loft space stations and
develop space shuttles.
<p>
   When Columbia lifts off, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Cheli</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Guidoni</ENAMEX> will become the 23rd
and 24th Europeans to fly in space, compared to the 218 Americans
and 84 Russians who have flown. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nicollier</ENAMEX> has flown twice
previously aboard the shuttle.
<p>
   In the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1970s</TIMEX>, he became the first <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX> astronaut to train
with the astronaut corps of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   When <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reiter</ENAMEX> returns to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> with two Russians on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 29</TIMEX>, he
will have accumulated <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">179 continuous days</TIMEX> in space, well below the
Russian record but far exceeding the American record of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">115 days</TIMEX>
established <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX> by former <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Norm Thagard</ENAMEX> aboard
Mir.
<p>
   While flying as guest researchers aboard the spacecraft of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>, the Europeans have been tentative about
investing in their own space programs, often heatedly debating
whether they could afford it.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX> developed the bus-sized Spacelab module that functions as
the laboratory in the cargo bay of the space shuttle.
<p>
   However, it was only <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last October</TIMEX> that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX> ministers cemented
their commitment to proceed with the development of a similar
module for the planned international space station. Their lab will
join those contributed by the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX> for
long-term research in space.
<p>
   The Europeans also are planning an automated cargo module for
the space station and considering whether to develop a crew
transfer vehicle, their first spacecraft capable of launching
humans into orbit. Both would be launched by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 rocket, a
powerful rocket the Europeans are developing initially for
commercial payloads.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-21-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1952EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
