<DOCID> nyt960222.0634 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A3265 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-22</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
COLUMBIA REACHES ORBIT SAFELY AFTER ENGINE SCARE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CAPE CANAVERAL</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The space shuttle Columbia thundered
safely into <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> orbit <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> with a multinational crew and an
Italian satellite, though two cockpit displays falsely signaled an
engine problem after liftoff.
<p>
   The shuttle soared from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">3:18 p.m.
EST</TIMEX>, rising through hazy skies on an easterly course and settling
into a planned 184-mile-high orbit.
<p>
   The seven astronauts are prepared for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two weeks</TIMEX> in orbit. On
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> they will unreel a 1,500-pound, tethered satellite to a
distance of nearly 13 miles from Columbia on a matchstick-thin
cord.
<p>
   During <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two days</TIMEX> of experiments, they hope to demonstrate that
the copper wire wrapped in high-strength synthetic insulation will
generate electricity as the two spacecraft whip through <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s
ionosphere and magnetic field.
<p>
   The same experiment faltered during a mission in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX>, with the
satellite becoming stuck 850 feet from the shuttle during
deployment.
<p>
   Columbia's three main engines ignited precisely on schedule
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, but within a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">few seconds</TIMEX> an amber ``alert'' light flashed
in front of commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrew Allen</ENAMEX> and pilot <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott Horowitz</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX>
informed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission Control</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX> that the left engine chamber
pressure was far lower than the <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">100 percent to 104 percent</NUMEX> it was
supposed to register.
<p>
   ``We've got a gauge showing <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">45 percent</NUMEX> on the left,'' radioed
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Had the reading been accurate, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Horowitz</ENAMEX> would have
faced a possible launch abort with an emergency landing at the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> or, perhaps, on emergency strips in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Africa</ENAMEX> or
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Spain</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``Columbia, we're showing good engines, good commands on all
three channels,'' responded <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Blaine Hammond</ENAMEX>, the shuttle crew's
liaison in the control center.
<p>
   Similar readings at the launch control center at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy</ENAMEX> also
showed the engines were working properly.
<p>
   ``Obviously, we will have to pore over the data,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Loren
Shriver</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s mission management team chairman and a former
shuttle commander, told reporters later. ``But all the responses,
all the performances of the mission were right on the money.''
<p>
   Through the ascent, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX> told controllers later, the left
engine chamber pressure reading in the cockpit indicated a
consistent deficiency of <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">60 percent</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shriver</ENAMEX> said engineers believe there may have been a problem in
the link between the shuttle's bank of general-purpose computers
and the left engine's computer.
<p>
   Columbia was graced with a smooth countdown and near-perfect
launch weather.
<p>
   ``From my crew, `arrivederchi, adieu, auf wideersehen and
adios,''' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX> radioed the launch control team moments before
liftoff.
<p>
   The seven-man crew includes two Italians and a Swiss astronaut.
<p>
   A German astronaut and four Russian cosmonauts were also in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> orbit aboard a Russian Soyuz capsule and the Mir space
station <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> orbit was populated for the first time by
four Americans, four Europeans and four Russians.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1997</TIMEX>, all three nations plan to join the Japanese and
Canadians in the assembly of a new global space station.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX>'s crew includes flight engineer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Maurizio Cheli</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Italy</ENAMEX>,
payload commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Franklin Chang-Diaz</ENAMEX>, mission specialist <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff
Hoffman</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Claude Nicollier</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Switzerland</ENAMEX> and payload specialist
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Umberto Guidoni</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Italy</ENAMEX> as well as <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Horowitz</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chang-Diaz</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hoffman</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nicollier</ENAMEX> all flew on the first
tethered mission in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX>. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Italian Space Agency</ENAMEX> have invested nearly
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$450 million</NUMEX> to develop and prepare the tether system for the two
test flights.
<p>
   Once the tethered satellite experiment is completed, the shuttle
astronauts will join teams of ground researchers for a series of
physics and biotechnology experiments. Researchers believe the work
could improve the production of computer chips and metal alloys as
well as aid the eventual development of antiviral drugs.
</TEXT>
