<STORYID cat=i pri=u> A4388 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FRANCE</ENAMEX>-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-23</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FRANCE</ENAMEX>-MILITARY-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CHIRAC</ENAMEX> REAPS GLORY, AND GRUMBLING, ON FRENCH DEFENSE CUTBACKS
(HLW)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CRAIG R. WHITNEY</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">PARIS</ENAMEX>  &MD;  President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jacques Chirac</ENAMEX>, denounced around the world
only <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a month ago</TIMEX> for conducting underground nuclear weapons tests
in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pacific</ENAMEX>, reaped praise on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> for his decision to phase
out the land-based third of the French nuclear deterrent and to
stop all further production of weapons-grade fissionable material.
<p>
   But his plan to abolish conscription and to shrink the uniformed
military from 500,000 to 350,000 in an all-volunteer force <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">six
years from now</TIMEX> met with mixed reactions, inside and outside the
ranks.
<p>
   In a television interview on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX> said the
underground tests had proved that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> could rely on submarine-
and air-launched missiles for its nuclear deterrent from now on and
do away with all ground-launched ones.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX> said that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> was the first nuclear power to renounce
production of more fissile material to make nuclear warheads, and
that it would close down the plant at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pierrelatte</ENAMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Rhone
Valley</ENAMEX> that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> established in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early 1960s</TIMEX>, over the
objections of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> and other nuclear powers, to
produce enriched uranium.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX> also plans to close the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">South Pacific</ENAMEX> sites where the
last six tests were conducted.
<p>
   By phasing out 18 land-based medium-range missiles in
southeastern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year and next</TIMEX> and dismantling 15
short-range missile launchers stored in eastern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> that had
long been a thorn in the side of relations with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX>
took more tarnish off his image.
<p>
   Though he acknowledged that Chancellor <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Helmut Kohl</ENAMEX> would
probably regret the withdrawal of some of the 19,000 French troops
still stationed in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX> pledged to preserve the French
commitment to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Eurocorps</ENAMEX>, a 50,000-man multinational unit that
both <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX> regard as the core of a strengthened
European defense. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kohl</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> expressed support for the French
decisions.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NATO</ENAMEX> diplomats said that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX>'s strategy was in line with the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NATO</ENAMEX> alliance's moves in recent years to shift from big, heavily
armed units designed to repel a Soviet invasion toward smaller,
more mobile forces that could be sent quickly to trouble spots like
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   In the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next century</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX> told a gathering of 500 senior
French officers and members of the enlisted ranks at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Military
School</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX>'s nuclear deterrent would rest on
four new strategic missile submarines plus an undetermined number
of supersonic air-launched cruise missiles.
<p>
   Defense officials said that by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2015</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">army</ENAMEX> would consist of
136,000 soldiers, 100,000 fewer than <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, with a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> of 45,500,
nearly 20,000 fewer, and an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">air force</ENAMEX> of 63,000 which would be
25,000 fewer.
<p>
   ``I expect unflinching commitment from you to this task of
reconsolidating our armed forces,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chirac</ENAMEX> told his troops. He
called for a national debate on doing away with conscription  &MD;  and
got one immediately.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jean-Marie Le Pen</ENAMEX>, the leader of the extreme-right <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Front</ENAMEX>, welcomed the end of the draft but not the shrunken military.
<p>
   And the communist-affiliated <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Confederation of Labor</ENAMEX>
warned: ``Tens of thousands of jobs are threatened, contrary to the
deliberately reassuring statements of the president.''
</TEXT>
