<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A4453 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-23</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ASTRONAUTS STRUGGLE WITH COMPUTER PROBLEMS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Columbia's astronauts prepared to unspool an Italian
tethered satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> for a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two-day</TIMEX> test but fell <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">several hours</TIMEX>
behind schedule because of difficulties with computers needed to
control the experiment.
<p>
   Space agency officials, however, were hopeful the shuttle crew
would not have to delay deployment of the 1,500-pound satellite,
beginning shortly before <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">4 p.m. EST</TIMEX>. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> The near <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">six-hour</TIMEX>
operation would separate Columbia and the satellite on a
shoe-lace-thin, 13-mile-long cord.
<p>
   ``I'm at this point enthusiastic,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nobie Stone</ENAMEX>, chief
mission scientist for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX>. ``I think we can solve the problems and go on with
the deployment mission as we had planned.''
<p>
   A team of Italian and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> researchers expect to demonstrate
that the long tether will generate an electrical current as the
crafts race through <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s ionosphere and magnetic field at
velocities of five miles per second.
<p>
   The computer trouble, which could hinder the crew's ability to
safely maneuver the satellite away from Columbia, caused the seven
astronauts to fall <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">three hours</TIMEX> behind their timeline as they worked
around the clock in shifts. If the slide continues, mission
managers could postpone deployment until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The 12,000 pounds of gear required for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two-day</TIMEX> flight test
relies on the interactions of 18 computers.
<p>
   During checks <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, a critical payload bay computer started,
faltered and restarted itself, interrupting the flow of commands
and science data it routes between the tether's complex deploy
mechanism, satellite experiment equipment and astronaut control
panels and displays.
<p>
   Additionally, a laptop computer used by the astronauts to
display data operated too sluggishly to be useful, and a sensor on
the deployer that clocks the speed and length of the tether
provided bad readings.
<p>
   Working with engineers on the ground, the astronauts operated
the payload processor in a backup mode that seemed to function
reliably and replaced the sluggish laptop and cabling with a spare.
But the sensor error, which indicated several yards of tether
deployment when there was none, proved more mysterious.
<p>
   ``These things happen to you sometimes,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lee Briscoe</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s
mission operations director, said of the problems with equipment
that worked on the ground during pre-launch tests.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> and Italian space agencies attempted the same tethered
satellite experiment in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX> aboard the shuttle Atlantis, with
disappointing results. The deployer mechanism snagged on a safety
bolt, and the satellite never made it more than 850 feet from the
shuttle.
<p>
   Four of Columbia's astronauts flew on the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX> mission,
including <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andy Allen</ENAMEX>, the mission commander. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Early Friday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX>
took a call from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> Administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Goldin</ENAMEX>, who offered words
of encouragement and caution.
<p>
   ``Clearly, I want success, but the fact of the matter is, we
have to understand when you go into space, there is always a
risk,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Goldin</ENAMEX> told <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX>. ``Safety is going to be the first
priority in operating the tether, right?''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Allen</ENAMEX> responded, ``There is no doubt in our minds we will be
able to keep the orbiter safe and the crew safe. That is the utmost
of our priorities.''
<p>
   Researchers believe tether systems could be used to generate
electrical power aboard a space station, maneuver spacecraft into
higher or lower orbits without rocket propulsion and lower probes
into regions of the atmosphere that cannot be studied with
conventional aircraft or satellites.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, propulsion system experts said they believe Columbia
may have experienced a pair of unrelated scares <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, when the
astronauts blasted off. Moments into their ascent, a caution light
lit on a cockpit panel, and the gauge for the left main rocket
engine indicated it was significantly underpowered, a condition
that could have prompted an emergency landing.
<p>
   As it turned out, the propulsion system performed normally. Some
shuttle engineers believe Columbia's primary computers and a second
computer on the shuttle engines may have been slightly out of sync
in the relay of commands and responses, triggering the amber
caution light.
<p>
   But they may not know until Columbia returns to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> why the
cockpit gauge erroneously indicated at the same time that the left
engine was underpowered.
</TEXT>
