<STORYID cat=e pri=u> A5207 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-TV-SPY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-25</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-TV-SPY-REVIEW-NYT
`SPY IN THE SKY': HOW SPY PLANE DELAYED ARMS CONTROL
(EDS: Broadcast details appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> area. Check local listings.)
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">WALTER GOODMAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Remember <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis Gary Powers</ENAMEX>? He became an incident in the cold
war on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 1, 1960</TIMEX>, when his plane, the supersecret U-2, was shot
down over the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Soviet Union</ENAMEX>. ``Spy in the Sky'' finds unexpected
ironies in the story of what he was doing up there.
<p>
   As explained here, President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dwight D. Eisenhower</ENAMEX> ordered the
building of a new spy plane because he doubted <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> estimates
of Soviet bomber strength. ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eisenhower</ENAMEX> never really trusted the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX>,'' says <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Donald Welzenbach</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CIA</ENAMEX> historian. ``He always
thought they overstated their case.'' The new plane, the U-2, would
have the mission of confirming or rebutting the dire estimates.
<p>
   Building a craft that could fly high enough to evade Soviet
defenses was a considerable challenge. Much of <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">hourlong</TIMEX> program is
given to details of how that was accomplished.
<p>
   Not only could the lightweight U-2 fly high and travel far, but
it could also bring back excellent pictures, which in fact proved
that the Soviets did not have nearly the number of bombers the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air
Force</ENAMEX> had assumed: the bomber gap didn't exist.
<p>
   So from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">America</ENAMEX>'s point of view, the U-2 was a peacekeeper,
making it unnecessary for the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> to build more planes
than it needed, and thus holding down the arms race. Unfortunately,
the Soviets, who spotted the first U-2 to go over their territory
but were unable to get at it, did not see things that way. They
were waiting for a chance to shoot one down.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Powers</ENAMEX>' mission was particularly chancy. In search of missile
bases, he had to fly thousands of miles across the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Soviet Union</ENAMEX> in
a straight line, which made him more vulnerable to Soviet
interception. As <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Welzenbach</ENAMEX> puts it, ``If you fly in a straight
line long enough, they're going to get you.''
<p>
   The fact that the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Powers</ENAMEX> U-2 was caught working on that favorite
Soviet holiday, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May Day</TIMEX>, added insult to injury at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kremlin</ENAMEX> just
as a big-power summit meeting approached. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nikita S. Khrushchev</ENAMEX>
denounced the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>, and the narrator adds, ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eisenhower</ENAMEX>'s
hopes for a test-ban treaty and for detente were shattered.''
<p>
   The program, an offering from ``The American Experience'' on
PBS, ends by noting that on the day that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Powers</ENAMEX> was sentenced to <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10
years</TIMEX> in prison (he would serve <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">17 months</TIMEX>), the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CIA</ENAMEX> received film
from its new spy satellite, which covered more territory than all
the U-2 flights put together.
<p>
   It showed that the supposed missile gap was no more real than
the supposed bomber gap. But the plane that had served to slow the
arms race had also delayed the move toward more peaceful relations.
<p>
   BROADCAST DETAILS:
<p>
   ``The American Experience: Spy in the Sky''
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> on PBS
<p>
   (Channel 13, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">9</TIMEX>)
<p>
   Produced, directed and written by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Linda Garmon</ENAMEX>; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beth Tierney</ENAMEX>,
associate producer; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Lattanzi</ENAMEX>, film editor; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sheldon Mirowitz</ENAMEX>,
music. Narrated by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Roy Scheider</ENAMEX>. For ``The American Experience'':
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Judy Crichton</ENAMEX>, executive producer; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Margaret Drain</ENAMEX>, senior producer;
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David McCullough</ENAMEX>, host. ``The American Experience'' is a production
of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WGBH Boston</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-25-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1848EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
