<DOCID> nyt960227.0647 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A7794 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-27</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
MYSTERY SURROUNDING LOST SATELLITE THICKENS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> ground control teams stablished periodic radio
contact with the lost tethered satellite on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>, finding to
their surprise that its computer was dormant and its fuel tank
empty.
<p>
   Controllers successfully commanded the 1,500-pound satellite
into a ``safe'' mode  &MD;  a form of electronic hibernation  &MD;  moments
after the spacecraft and the more than 12 miles of shoe lace-thin
tether attached to it broke free of the shuttle Columbia on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>.
<p>
   When they lost contact 30 minutes after the snap, the computer
was on, the fuel tank filled with more than 90 pounds of nitrogen
gas and the valves that secure the propellant tank closed.
<p>
   The satellite's computer software was specifically compiled in
such a way that it could not command the opening and closing of the
fuel valves.
<p>
   Now, ground teams acknowledge, there are at least two mysteries
 &MD;  why the long tether snapped and how the satellite could have been
so radically altered.
<p>
   The space agency said its formal investigation into the
satellite loss will include the possibility of a connection between
all the events.
<p>
   ``It's a very interesting puzzle,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tony LaVoie</ENAMEX>, the
satellite system's chief engineer. ``We're collecting data now on
the satellite and going over other data we have. We don't have all
the answers right now.'' About the only thing experts are willing
to rule out is extraterrestrial intervention.
<p>
   The purpose of the unusual experiment was to determine if long
space tethers could be controlled to generate an electrical current
while speeding through <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s ionosphere and magnetic field.
<p>
   Researchers said they saw more than the expected voltage across
the tether, a voltage surge on one satellite instrument and
high-energy electrons around the spacecraft before the break. The
current flow, however, had been intentionally interrupted by ground
commands several minutes before the break.
<p>
   Contact with the renegade satellite was first re-established
through the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Electronic Signal Test Laboratory</ENAMEX> at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson Space
Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>. It sent commands that re-awakened the
spacecraft's scientific gear for electrical measurements and
reactivated gyroscopes for stability. All of that was possible
without the computer, which was on, when contact was lost <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The satellite and the mass of fabric tether suspended from it
are circling <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> in an egg-shaped orbit with high and low
altitudes of 254 and 195 miles. The satellite is expected to fall
and re-enter <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere within <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">20 to 30 days</TIMEX>, burning up
before it reaches the ground.
<p>
   ``I can't emphasize enough that the satellite and the tether is
a very unstable system,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Tracy</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> flight dynamics
officer following its movements.
<p>
   Its instability and mysterious behavior aside, the spacecraft
may get more attention before its suicide plunge. Some people on
the ground should be able to see it.
<p>
   One of the commands transmitted to the satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> turned
on a set of flashing lights.
<p>
   ``It will be an absolutely awesome sight,'' astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff
Hoffman</ENAMEX> said of the opportunities to see the satellite from the
ground in parts of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Northern Hemisphere</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>. ``It will be
the only time for ... people to see something in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> orbit that
is more than a point of light. They will see a line moving through
the sky.''
<p>
   Columbia commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andy Allen</ENAMEX> and his six-man crew could pass
within 60 to 70 miles of the spacecraft <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Friday</TIMEX>, perhaps close
enough for them to get another look.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-27-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2100EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960229.0636 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A0329 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-29</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ELECTRON GUNS FIRED AT TETHERED SATELLITE IN ENERGY WAVE
EXPERIMENT
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The shuttle Columbia's astronauts fired electron guns
at the wandering Italian tethered satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> as part of a
last-ditch experiment in electrodynamics.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Overnight</TIMEX>, the seven shuttle astronauts expected to close within
50 miles of the half-ton satellite and the thousands of feet of
tether massed around it  &MD;  the closest they will come before
Columbia's scheduled landing <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The tether linking the shuttle to the satellite broke <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>, flinging the smaller spacecraft into a much higher,
elliptical orbit.
<p>
   Columbia was to cross behind and below the satellite.
<p>
   Hours before the close approach, the astronauts periodically
fired the shuttle's electron guns into space in a range of
frequencies, so researchers could determine whether the pulses were
generating waves of energy and magnetism that could be detected by
the satellite's instruments.
<p>
   So far, the satellite has recorded waves generated by Columbia's
electron guns at a separation of more than 300 miles, said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nobie Stone</ENAMEX>, the project's chief scientist.
<p>
   More shuttle pulses were planned during the fly-by to help
experts determine which electron gun frequencies were most
successful at generating the waves.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stone</ENAMEX> was hopeful the satellite's fading batteries would hold
out long enough to relay the results to the network of ground
stations hastily assembled after the tether break.
<p>
   Meanwhile, most of the shuttle crew's efforts were redirected
toward the mission's second major objective, research efforts to
exploit the weightlessness of space for the production of better
medicines, metal alloys and semiconductors.
<p>
   Among the experiments is a project proposed by Columbia
astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Franklin Chang-Diaz</ENAMEX> to grow crystals of tripanothione
reductase, an enzyme involved in the spread of Chagas' disease.
<p>
   The disease, for which there is now no effective treatment, is
transmitted by a nocturnal insect and afflicts thousands of Central
and South Americans. It affects the muscles, including the heart,
and eventually causes death.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Larry Delucas</ENAMEX>, the project's principal investigator, said
researchers hope to grow large, pure crystals of the enzyme aboard
the shuttle.
<p>
   Special X-ray techniques will be employed after the shuttle
returns to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> in a bid to develop a map of the enzyme's
molecular structure in unprecedented detail.
<p>
   An experiment team then plans to test natural extracts as
potential treatments for the disease. They would act by inhibiting
the enzyme and thus interrupting the life cycle of the parasite.
<p>
   ``It's a wonderful story,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Delucas</ENAMEX>. ``This is ... an area
where drug companies really don't want to work, because there is
not a lot of money in it for them.''
<p>
   Also <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, Columbia commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andy Allen</ENAMEX> assisted
ground-based researchers with a series of combustion tests in which
silicon rubber and several types of insulated electrical wire were
ignited. The project is intended to assist engineers with the
development of a smoke detection system for the planned
international space station.
<p>
   At <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">mid-day</TIMEX>, Columbia crewman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Hoffman</ENAMEX> became the first
astronaut to log <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1,000 hours</TIMEX> of flight aboard a space shuttle.
<p>
   ``It sure has been fun getting here,'' said the veteran of five
missions and several space walks.
</TEXT>
