<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-01</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
CONTACT LOST WITH TETHERED SATELLITE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> lost contact with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Italy</ENAMEX>'s now powerless tethered
satellite on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, just hours after the Columbia astronauts
managed to spot and photograph the gleaming spacecraft and the
miles of reflective cord suspended below.
<p>
   Final signals from the runaway spacecraft reached <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> stations
at about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">6 a.m.</TIMEX> On a successive orbit over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> ground sites, the
satellite did not respond to electronic queries.
<p>
   Officials at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX>
expect the satellite to plunge into <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere in about <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two
weeks</TIMEX>, burning up before reaching the ground.
<p>
   ``The satellite is dead at this point,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nobie
Stone</ENAMEX>, the chief scientist for the project.
<p>
   Its battery power lasted longer than expected, permitting
researchers to communicate with the spacecraft during a close
approach <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``It's like the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Energizer</ENAMEX> bunny. It just kept on going,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stone</ENAMEX>
said.
<p>
   More than a dozen miles of fabric tether linking the half-ton
spacecraft to the shuttle snapped <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>. The satellite was
flung into a higher orbit, and plans for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two days</TIMEX> of linked
experiments in electromagnetism were interrupted after only <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">a few
hours</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Late Thursday</TIMEX>, the two spacecraft crossed within 53 miles of one
another. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> determined <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this week</TIMEX> it would have required
too much propellant for the shuttle to attempt an impromptu
rendezvous or retrieval.
<p>
   Nonetheless, the shuttle's communications gear was in contact
with the spacecraft for about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">50 minutes</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The shuttle crew was moved by the eery beauty of the spacecraft
and surprised to find the tether hanging down from the satellite
rather than tangled around it.
<p>
   ``It was beautiful. It was like a comet,'' Columbia crewman
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Umberto Guidoni</ENAMEX>, a guest researcher from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Italian Space Agency</ENAMEX>,
told an Italian television interviewer on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>, we've got contact. It's beautiful,'' Columbia
astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Franklin Chang-Diaz</ENAMEX> told <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission Control</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson Space
Center</ENAMEX>, when the two spacecraft were separated by 93 miles. ``We
can see the tether.''
<p>
   ``The tether looked completely straight,'' astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff
Hoffman</ENAMEX> reported minutes later. ``I did not see anything above the
satellite.''
<p>
   The astronauts' first observation of the satellite occurred in
darkness and revealed only a bright light, when the two spacecraft
were 175 miles apart.
<p>
   Columbia's planned <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">14-day</TIMEX> flight is scheduled to end <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early
Thursday</TIMEX>, though mission managers are considering the possibility
of a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">one-day</TIMEX> extension.
<p>
   As tethered satellite activities waned <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="week">during the week</TIMEX>, the
seven-man shuttle crew has been working around the clock in shifts
on 10 major laboratory experiments. The efforts are directed at
improving production techniques for metal alloys, semiconductors
and medicines for the treatment of viral diseases, cancer and
disorders of the immune system.
<p>
   The astronauts are also conducting experiments in combustion as
part of an effort to develop a fire detection system for the
planned international space station.
</TEXT>
