<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A5709 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-05</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> PROBING SINGED O-RINGS, PROCEEDING WITH MIR MISSION PLANS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> is proceeding with plans for a shuttle mission to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s Mir space station <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">later this month</TIMEX>, even though engineers
are investigating singe marks on O-ring seals in rocket boosters
used to launch Columbia on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 22</TIMEX>, officials said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Atlantis is to blast off on a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine-day</TIMEX> mission to Mir on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March
21</TIMEX>. Its crew includes veteran astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shannon Lucid</ENAMEX>, who will
remain aboard the Russian outpost until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">August</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Shuttle managers are to meet <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> for a major review of
mission plans before confirming their launch plans.
<p>
   One propulsion expert, who serves on an independent <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> safety
panel, said Columbia's O-ring problem may stem from assembly rather
than a more serious design flaw, such as the one that triggered the
fatal <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1986</TIMEX> Challenger accident.
<p>
   ``My immediate suspicion would be there was something different
in the manufacturing or assembly (of Columbia's boosters),'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Seymour Himmel</ENAMEX>, a member of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aerospace Safety Advisory Panel</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The 15-story booster motors are comprised of four major
segments, a nozzle assembly and nose cap, all bolted together at
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX> prior to launching.
<p>
   ``It's a job that requires a bit of experience and skill, and
I'd be suspicious when I find two of these things and wonder if
something happened with a tool that wasn't quite right or a
procedure that wasn't followed precisely,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Himmel</ENAMEX> said of the
singed O-rings.
<p>
   After Columbia's reusable booster motors were recovered from the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX> and taken apart, engineers found singe marks on
O-rings taken from the case-to-nozzle joint of both the left and
right solid-fuel rockets.
<p>
   The singed rubber O-rings were not designed to act as a thermal
or pressure barrier. Instead, their purpose is to keep adhesive
from getting to primary and backup pressure seals during assembly.
<p>
   While shuttle engineers have found similar damage to ``wiper''
O-rings nine previous times since the Challenger tragedy,
Columbia's was the first case with multiple burn damage in two
boosters from the same launch.
<p>
   ``That in itself is something I'd call a different situation.
Therefore, it's a reason to require deep investigation,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Himmel</ENAMEX>, a former propulsion engineer for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics
and Space Administration</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   He said, however, that it is reasonable for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> to search for
an explanation while preparing Atlantis for launch.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last summer</TIMEX>, singe marks were found on a different O-ring
component in the nozzles taken from two back-to-back shuttle
missions. Engineers traced the cause to a subtle change in assembly
techniques and delayed a third shuttle flight for more than a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">month</TIMEX>
while repairs were made.
<p>
   Meanwhile, Columbia's crew caught another fleeting glimpse of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Italy</ENAMEX>'s runaway tethered satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>, as the two spacecraft
crossed paths high over the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pacific Ocean</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The shuttle crew managed a similar observation of the Italian
satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late last week</TIMEX>. The satellite and more than 12 miles of
tether linking it to Columbia snapped on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 25</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Columbia's <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">15-day</TIMEX> research flight is scheduled to end <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early
Friday</TIMEX>, though mission managers might consider extending the flight
until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
