<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 6</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> stocks fell for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a second
day</TIMEX> after <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> announced plans for new missile tests near the
island starting <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``People are still reacting to this <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Grace Lee</ENAMEX>, a
fund manager with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jardine Fleming Taiwan Investment Trust
Management</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX>. ``It's mostly small investors that didn't
hear the news until after the market closed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   The main index of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Taiwan Stock Exchange</ENAMEX> fell as much as
117.38 points, or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2.45 percent</NUMEX>, to 4675.36. The index of electronic
shares declined as much as <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">3.8 percent</NUMEX>, the biggest fall among all
industries.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Winbond Electronics Corp.</ENAMEX>, a computer memory chip maker, fell as
much as its <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">7 percent</NUMEX> daily limit of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">NT$4.00</NUMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">NT$57.50</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s official <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Xinhua News Agency</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX> the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">People's
Liberation Army</ENAMEX> will conduct missile tests in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION" MIN="China">east and south
China seas</ENAMEX> in areas north and south of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 8-15</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> will test-fire missiles into an area as close as 12 miles
from northeastern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Broadcasting Corp.</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>
said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s main stock index plunged about <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">20 percent</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">between July
12 and August 14 last year</TIMEX> in connection with two sets of military
tests and war games. The main index lost <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">27 percent</NUMEX> for all of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
year</TIMEX>, and has declined another <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">6 percent</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX> amid increased
military tension with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>.
-- <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Russell Flannery</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Hung</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX> (8862) 517-2512
