<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NEWS-CORP</ENAMEX>-SATELLI </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-07</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0820 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NEWS-CORP</ENAMEX>-SATELLITES-UPDATE3-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NEWS CORP.</ENAMEX> TO PAY <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LORAL</ENAMEX> <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$400 MLN</NUMEX> FOR 2 SATELLITES (UPDATE3)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Morrison</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Adds <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>'s alternatives in eighth paragraph, final stock
prices.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 7</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI Communications Corp.</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> said they will pay <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX> more than <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$400 million</NUMEX> to
build two satellites for a direct television broadcasting venture.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> said it will launch the first satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late next year</TIMEX> and
the second in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1998</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> said it expects to offer satellite
television in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of 1997</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> contract raises the stakes in negotiations between
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> Chairman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX>
President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Malone</ENAMEX> on having the cable-TV giant join the
venture. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> owns two satellites it's not using
after the company lost a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX> auction for satellite broadcast
licenses to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> satellites provide the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> venture with new
leverage in the negotiations, analysts said. ``Any tactic they can
use to get <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> to work with them would make sense
because they want to get the satellites up as quick as they can,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Connie Luecke</ENAMEX>, analyst at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Duff &AMP; Phelps Corp.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> has that ace in the hole: Its satellites can
be launched <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> satellites are almost ready and could be launched in
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">fall</TIMEX>,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Susan Mayer</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> senior vice president for
ventures and alliances. ``If it were possible to negotiate a deal
with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Malone</ENAMEX>, then we could use one or more of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> satellites
and deploy the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> satellites elsewhere in the global system.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> venture isn't the only option for
entering the high-powered satellite television market. ``We're
looking at several different ways to enter the market,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>
spokeswoman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LaRae Marsik</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The nation's largest cable operator owns part of the satellites
controlled by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar Communications Corp.</ENAMEX> and is a partner in
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar Partners</ENAMEX>, a satellite cable venture between six cable
companies. It could use one or both as a base for a satellite
television business.
<p>
   Satellite Business News, a trade magazine, reported that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> is
negotiating to sell its two satellites to Canadian satellite
company <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Telesat Canada</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> would then lease back 27 to 28
transponders for television transmission.
<p>
   The venture companies and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> are eager to get
rolling in the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5 billion</NUMEX> satellite TV business, which is expected
to expand by <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">70 percent</NUMEX> annually from 5.5 million subscribers
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, according to Sky Report, a trade publication.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>, the leading satellite broadcast company, started in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October 1994</TIMEX> as a way for rural residents to receive cable-like
programming by satellite and quickly became popular in urban areas
too.
<p>
   Direct broadcast is received by 18-inch satellite dishes, which
have become one of the fastest-growing consumer electronics
products. Subscribers typically pay about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$30</NUMEX> a month to get as
many as 175 channels of movies, sports and other programs.
<p>
   Consumers sign up for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> service in consumer electronics
stores when they buy the dish and receiver box needed to get the
programs on their television. The 18-inch dish and receiver cost
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$600 to $900</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Information Television</ENAMEX>, an affiliate of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg
Business News</ENAMEX>, broadcasts on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX> won the rights to operate a nationwide broadcast
satellite by bidding <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$682.6 million</NUMEX> in a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Communications
Commission</ENAMEX> auction. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> said at the time that they
intended to offer a package of video, audio, information and
entertainment services to businesses and consumers in all 50 states
and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Puerto Rico</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``The signing of this (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX>) contract puts <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX>
right on target in our plans to bring a unique blend of new
high-powered, digital satellite services to all our customers,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bert Roberts</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> chairman and chief executive, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> will go head-to-head with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T Corp.</ENAMEX>, which plans to buy as
much as <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">30 percent</NUMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV Inc.</ENAMEX> satellite service operated
by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Electronic Corp.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   The No. 1 long-distance company in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX> said it plans to
begin marketing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX> by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">midsummer</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T</ENAMEX> said it would have taken at least <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two years</TIMEX> to enter the
market if it started from scratch. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T</ENAMEX> also saved paying more than
a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">billion dollars</NUMEX> to bid for satellite licenses at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> auction.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> is the nation's No. 2 long-distance
company. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> owns <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Star TV</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fox Broadcasting Co.</ENAMEX>, and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">20th Century Fox</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> shares closed unchanged at 29 7/8. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX>
shares, which trade as American Depositary Receipts in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>,
fell 1/4 to 22 3/4. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> shares fell 1/8 to 46 3/4.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications</ENAMEX> shares slipped 1/16 to 20 9/16.
</TEXT>
