<STORYID cat=i pri=u> A8306 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-07</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-BOS
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> DENOUNCES CHINESE ROCKET FIRINGS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">PAUL QUINN-JUDGE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> fired surface-to-surface missiles off the
coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, drawing a swift denunciation from the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> of the ``provocative and restless'' action.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> denounced the firings minutes after <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>
reported that Chinese naval forces off the coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> had
fired two missiles, one to the north of the island, another to the
southwest.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> described the firings as tests. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>
called them intimidation.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> had urged against the missile firings,
describing them as ``destabilizing'' and warning that although
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> claimed not to be aiming at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, the accuracy of the
missiles was open to question.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> intelligence sources said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> that the missile firings
are part of a series of Chinese maneuvers that have included 500
sorties by Chinese combat aircraft <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="last Friday">since last Friday</TIMEX> and a large
amphibious assault exercise around <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Haitan island</ENAMEX>, due west of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s northern tip.
<p>
   The missile tests are the most recent in a series of disputes
and disagreements that have in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the past few days</TIMEX> opened up deep
fissures in the carefully maintained facade of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> relations.
<p>
   They follow harsh exchanges between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> over
human rights, persistent <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> warnings that missile tests were
irresponsible and renewed expressions of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> unhappiness with
Chinese arms sales to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pakistan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Few analysts believe <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> has either the capacity or the desire
to invade <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, but no one doubts that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> could inflict
serious damage on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s economy with a campaign of long-term,
low-grade military pressure.
<p>
   The missile firings and other menacing military activity come
just two weeks before general elections in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> maintains
that the elections  &MD;  whose multiparty nature is probably an
embarrassment to Communist-ruled <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>  &MD;  are a sign that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>
is proceeding apace with its plans to declare its total
independence from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>. Since Nationalist Chinese forces retreated
to the island in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1949</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> has insisted that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> is simply a
temporarily province area that, like <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Macao</ENAMEX>, will soon
return to mainland rule.
<p>
   Analysts in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> have suggested that the tests are a
tactic devised to engineer the greatest possible destabilization of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> while incurring the least possible risk for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>. The
mere expectation of tests has affected the Taiwanese stock market,
they said.
<p>
   One Chinese missile landing on Taiwanese territory, even without
any human casualties, could ``crash the market,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stanley Roth</ENAMEX>
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Institute for Peace</ENAMEX>. ``This could be a very clever
scenario.''
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Earlier Thursday</TIMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" MIN="Foreign Ministry">Chinese Foreign Ministry</ENAMEX> spokesman rejected
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> expressions of concern about the impending tests. ``<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> will
never accept the representations and protests from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> side on
this issue,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shen Guofeng</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shen</ENAMEX> also told the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> to keep its views on human
rights in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> to itself. A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Department</ENAMEX> report <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> had
complained of a growing number of human rights abuses in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>. The
Chinese spokesman shrugged these off. ``The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> does not
have the right to make irresponsible remarks on the internal
affairs of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> or any other country,'' he said.
<p>
   In <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, as a senior Chinese national security official
arrived for meetings with his counterparts, administration
officials again voiced concern about <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s arms transfers to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pakistan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The latest exchange of verbal blows underlines the difficulties
facing <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> policy makers in their dealings with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> is gradually turning into a major power, one whose economy
is expected to outstrip <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the early decades of the next
century</TIMEX>. The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> is <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s third largest investor, with
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$26 billion</NUMEX> in the country  &MD;  coming ironically, just after <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong
Kong</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> wants good relations with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>, but
admits it has no idea which path <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> will take  &MD;  a recognizable
form of democracy, a strengthening of its present authoritarian
regime, or something in between.
<p>
   At the moment, with its still secretive leadership involved in
their own version of elections, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> is showing its uncompromising
face to the world. The pivotal and preeminent figure in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s
post-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mao</ENAMEX> economic moderninzation, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Deng Xiaoping</ENAMEX>, is quietly dying.
<p>
   Other top leaders are maneuvering to take over. None has the
power to secure it without a struggle. And none of the claimants,
analysts here say, wants to be seen as weak in the face of
perceived insubordination by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> or disapproval from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-07-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2034EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960307.0733 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=u> A8358 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>-ART-2NDT </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-07</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0479 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIPEI</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>: uncivilized, barbarian.''
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, even before any missiles were fired, many banks
were experiencing heavy buying of American dollars, according to
local newspaper reports. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bank of Taiwan</ENAMEX>, according to The China
News, doubled its weekly purchases of American dollars and several
banks placed limits on their purchase.
<p>
   The New Taiwan dollar was hit hard by heavy selling and lost
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">three cents</NUMEX>, a further fall prevented only by the intervention of
the island's <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Central Bank</ENAMEX>. The stock market, which was rocked
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this week</TIMEX>, recovered strongly on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, with government
buying largely contributing to the markets strength.
<p>
   Despite pleas for calm, rumors coursed through the capital. The
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Institute</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, the private non-government agency
that serves as the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> embassy here, denied repeated rumors that
it was preparing for the evacuation of American citizens.
<p>
   Gold dealers were reporting that the sale of gold bars, a
traditional haven for Chinese in times of trouble, were running <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">20
to 30 percent</NUMEX> above normal.
<p>
   In <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> was ``deeply disturbed,'' said
its spokesman, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael D. McCurry</ENAMEX>. He said the national security
adviser, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anthony Lake</ENAMEX>, would meet on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> with his Chinese
counterpart, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Liu Huaqiu</ENAMEX>, a vice foreign minister, to talk over the
sharply elevated tensions in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan Strait</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Hours after the tests, Secretary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Warren Christopher</ENAMEX>
sought to ``get a dialogue going'' over dinner with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Liu</ENAMEX>, who was on
a private visit to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>. But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lui</ENAMEX>, like other Chinese
diplomats, was not listening very closely on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> to American
concerns about human rights, trade deficits, copyright violations
and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>'s sales of missiles and nuclear-weapons technology.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Liu</ENAMEX> wanted most of all to air <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s grievances over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>,
officials said. Chinese officials openly expressed fury on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>
over democratic elections to be held in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two weeks</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> and the
refusal of Taiwanese leaders to discuss reunification with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>.
They also lashed out at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Department</ENAMEX>'s criticism on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>'s human rights record, and restated their
anger at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>' decision <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX> to grant a visa to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s president, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lee Teng-hui</ENAMEX>, so he could attend a reunion at
his alma mater, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cornell University</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last June</TIMEX>.
<p>
   A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Department</ENAMEX> official stressed that the missile tests were
not acts of war or terror. As long as the missiles keep falling in
the target areas, and do not strike <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, the tests are no more
than political theater  &MD;  ``but a little too close to the edge of
the stage,'' he said.
<p>
   ``The view here is that these tests, while clearly meant to make
a political impact, do not constitute an economic blockade, or an
attempt to mess <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> up commercially or economically,'' he said.
</TEXT>
