<PREAMBLE>
BC-DEFENSE-WINNERS-BLOOM
DEFENSE COMPANIES PROFIT MACHINES EVEN AS MILITARY BUDGET FALLS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jenell Wallace</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
(Not for publication until <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">6 a.m.</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 4</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> defense companies are
winners these days, even as military spending shrinks.
<p>
   The nation's airplane and weapons makers turned big profits in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1995</TIMEX>, boosting returns for investors as well. No. 2 defense
contractor <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas Corp.</ENAMEX>, for example, reported operating
profit of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$905 million</NUMEX> in its military business, up <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">28 percent</NUMEX> from
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">previous year</TIMEX>. Its stock rose <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">94 percent</NUMEX>.
<p>
   The gains reflect a shift in the way <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX> designs
and builds products. Take the upgraded F/A-18 Hornet, a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>
strike fighter that will cost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$89 billion</NUMEX> -- the single most
expensive program planned by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> -- if the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> buys 1,000
of the planes over <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two decades</TIMEX>. Its nose barrel is made with one
piece of sheet metal rather than 90 as required for its
predecessor, saving <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$3,746</NUMEX> per aircraft and eliminating a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">20-day</TIMEX>
cycle for subassembly.
<p>
   ``The industry is just simply working smarter,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard
Bitzinger</ENAMEX>, defense industry analyst at the nonprofit <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessments</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Add to that mergers and acquisitions in the defense industry
that have helped cut costs -- at the price of firing 1.33 million
workers <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">between 1987 and 1995</TIMEX> -- and defense companies are sitting
pretty. This is evident in the <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">66 percent</NUMEX> gain posted by the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Standard &AMP; Poor's</ENAMEX> aerospace and defense index since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 3, 1995</TIMEX>.
The broader market as represented by the S&AMP;P 500 rose <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX>.
<p>
   The defense industry ``has become enormously profitable over the
course of the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last four years</TIMEX>,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BT Securities</ENAMEX> analyst
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wolfgang Demisch</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Part of the profit growth stems from sheer size as companies
merge or acquire particular products to dominate certain types of
defense work. As a result, President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Clinton</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">fiscal 1997</TIMEX>
military budget request allocates roughly <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">25 percent</NUMEX> of the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$73.6
billion</NUMEX> in it for weapons to just five contractors.
<p>
   Consider No. 1 contractor <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX>, one of the
principal military aircraft manufacturers along with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell
Douglas</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northrop Grumman Corp.</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bethesda</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Maryland</ENAMEX>-based
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX> -- created in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1995</TIMEX> when then-No. 2 <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Corp.</ENAMEX>
acquired No. 3 <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Martin Marietta Corp.</ENAMEX> -- plans to bolster its
defense electronics business by acquiring <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX> for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$9.1
billion</NUMEX>.
<p>
   Under <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s request, funding for just two <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> programs,
the multiple launch rocket system and a tactical missile system,
would amount to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$225 million</NUMEX>. These programs would boost government
revenue at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>, in addition to the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4.46 billion</NUMEX>
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> seeks for its major programs such as the F-16 fighter.
<p>
   ``As companies merge, the defense industrial base is getting
more profitable,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bitzinger</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Electronics Corp.</ENAMEX>, a unit of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX>, is
another case study in contractor dominance: It makes systems for
virtually every <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> military plane. Profit in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>'s aerospace
and defense segment <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX> rose to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$688 million</NUMEX> from <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$664
million</NUMEX>, even as revenue slipped to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5.95 billion</NUMEX> from <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$6.02
billion</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> makes radar for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX>'s F-15, FA-18 and AV-8
Harrier fighters, for example, as well as systems for the Bradley
Fighting Vehicle, an armored vehicle smaller than a tank
manufactured by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Defense LP</ENAMEX>, a partnership of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Harsco Corp.</ENAMEX>
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FMC Corp.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   In addition, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> is involved in anything to do with missile
defense, said a defense industry official close to the budget
process.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> proposes <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$133.2 million</NUMEX> for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> satellite
communications system and <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$187.2 million</NUMEX> for 170 Advanced Medium
Range Air to Air Missiles (AAMRAMs), along with funding for other
programs at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX>-based contractor.
<p>
   The president's proposal for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.3 billion</NUMEX> for eight of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell
Douglas</ENAMEX>'s C-17 military transport plane illustrates another change
in the defense industry: willingness to rethink the way it builds
weapons.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX>, the C-17 program was months behind schedule, about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1
billion</NUMEX> over budget, and plagued by software, avionics and wing
problems. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX> and the government, which kept revising
production specifications and performance requirements, shared
blame. The C-17s future was in jeopardy.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX> responded by paying closer attention to costs.
Employees devised a different way to use scaffolding in building
the plane, a simple change that saved about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$90,000</NUMEX> per aircraft,
for example.
<p>
   Such efforts and better communication with the government helped
the C-17 program get back on track. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last summer</TIMEX>, C-17s took off as
scheduled <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">99 percent</NUMEX> of the time in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> reliabliblity tests.
The plane received the prestigious Collier Trophy from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Aeronautic Association</ENAMEX> for ``the greatest achievement in
aeronautics.''
<p>
   The government, which already spent <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$13 billion</NUMEX> for 40 C-17s,
plans to 80 more for about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$18 billion</NUMEX> in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next few years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">fiscal 1997</TIMEX> request also includes <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.6 billion</NUMEX> for the
advanced F/A-18 and <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$398 million</NUMEX> for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX>'s Longbow
Apache helicopter.
</TEXT>
