<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>-2TAKES-N </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-08</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0753 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>-2TAKES-NYT
CHINESE MISSILE TESTING FAILS TO DISRUPT LIFE ON <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>
(bl)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">EDWARD A. GARGAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX> 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">KEELUNG</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Not long after three unarmed Chinese missiles
fell near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s shores, unsubtle weapons in a campaign of
intimidation, leaders here <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> made the expected calls for calm
and vowed to repel any attacks.
<p>
   But among the people of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, long accustomed to living in the
shadow of a hostile giant, only sporadic signs of anxiety
punctuated a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">day</TIMEX> that differed little from any other. Traffic jams
clotted <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX>'s streets, with motor scooters weaving madly between
honking taxis, lumbering buses and streams of delivery trucks. And
the campaign for the presidency, at the forefront of many people's
concerns, continued its furious pace.
<p>
   Typical was the response of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wang Chi-san</ENAMEX>, a dock worker at this
cargo and fishing port on the northern tip of the island. As a
crane swung a rope sling piled with crates of brain-numbing
kaoliang alcohol onto a truck at dockside here, he broke into a
laugh.
<p>
   ``Eeverybody's a little worried,'' he said, ``but really,
there's no reason to be afraid. No reason at all.''
<p>
   Only <TIMEX TYPE="TIME" MIN="12 hours">12 hours before</TIMEX>, an unarmed Chinese M-9 ballistic missile
had slammed into the sea barely <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">three hours</TIMEX>' sail north of this
port, marking the onset of a new Chinese campaign to intimidate
this island of 21 million people as it edges toward its first
presidential election in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two weeks</TIMEX>.
<p>
   In the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">predawn hours</TIMEX>, two other missiles crashed into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">South
China Sea</ENAMEX> west of one of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX>'s major container ports at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kaohsiung</ENAMEX>.
It was the closest Chinese missiles, armed or unarmed, have come to
this island in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">57 years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME" MIN="day">Throughout the day</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> kept up a rattle of bellicose
statements, with Foreign Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Qian Qichen</ENAMEX> warning <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> that
``a real disaster'' would befall <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> if it persisted in its
quest for independence.
<p>
   As <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">dawn</TIMEX>'s glow nibbled at the darkness, President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lee Teng-hui</ENAMEX>
was out in the street markets of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX> campaigning and chatting
with shoppers. Huge crowds cheered his arrival, but he refrained
from commenting on the missile tests.
<p>
   A spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Foreign Ministry</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael Chen</ENAMEX>, said that
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lee</ENAMEX> preferred to let other government organs speak on the issue.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kao Koo-liang</ENAMEX>, the vice chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mainland Affairs
Council</ENAMEX>, accused <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> of trying to intimidate <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s people as
they prepare to vote for in the island's first presidential
elections.
<p>
   And despite mounting threats from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> about <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s efforts
to elevate its posture internationally, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kao</ENAMEX> said that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> was
fully prepared to defeat a military assault by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``We will respond to this unreasonable provocation with reason
and self-restraint,'' he said. ``but we are thoroughly prepared to
deal with an armed invasion from the mainland.''
<p>
   ``As long as we can consolidate our psychological defenses,
unite together and remain steadfastly determined in our pursuit of
freedom and democracy, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> will fail in its attempt at armed
intimidation.''
<p>
   As if to emphasize this confidence, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX> stock market
soared more than 54 points, raising the index <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">1.14 percent</NUMEX> to
4,805.09, a sharp reversal from the panicky sell-offs <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this
week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   At the same time though, local banks continued to report runs on
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">American dollars</NUMEX>, with many banks running out of greenbacks as the
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">day</TIMEX> wore on. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bank of America</ENAMEX> announced that it would fly in a
plane loaded with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> currency <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> to cope with the demand.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s television channels hurtled back and forth between soap
operas, celebrity cooking contests and blanket coverage of the
missile tests. Boats chugged out into the mist with
miserable-looking correspondents peering into the brume.
<p>
   Reporters hovered around radar screens in air traffic control
terminals, the screens glowing with red boxes marking the air
exclusion zone declared by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>. And passengers and pilots were
buttonholed to see how they felt about the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">five-minute</TIMEX> delay of
their flights.
<p>
   Yet, even as <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> seemed bent on cowing <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> into some sort
of submission, submission leading to reunification with the
mainland, the missile tests appeared to be having an opposite
effect.
<p>
   ``Generally speaking, people are maintaining calm,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrew
Nien-tsu Yang</ENAMEX>, the secretary general of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Chinese Council of
Advanced Policy Studies</ENAMEX>, a research body in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX>. ``But there's a
lot of discussion about the missiles.''
<p>
   (MORE)
<p>
   nn
</TEXT>
