<DOCID> nyt960313.0607 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=i pri=u> A4692 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tad-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>-500&AMP;add-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-13</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0709 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX>-500&AMP;add-COX
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TAIWAN</ENAMEX> WILL SEEK ADVANCED <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> WEAPONRY <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">NEXT WEEK</TIMEX> TO COUNTER
CHINESE THREAT
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BOB DEANS</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CARACAS</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Venezuela</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> will seek advanced weapons and
related assistance from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>, amid ongoing
Chinese military exercises that have sparked alarm in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taipei</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Perry</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   He also said a second group of American warships is steaming
from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Persian Gulf</ENAMEX> toward <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>, where it will join a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
aircraft carrier and battle support ships already patrolling waters
east of the island.
<p>
   Talks between senior diplomats and defense officials from the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> begin <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> near the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>. They were
scheduled months before the exercises <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> has been conducting
near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> over the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past week</TIMEX>. Similar talks are held <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">each year</TIMEX>,
and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> invariably seeks additional weaponry and advanced
defense gear, citing the threat of military action from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>,
which regards <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> as a renegade province.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">This year</TIMEX>, however, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> has buttressed <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s position by
test firing Scud-like missiles  &MD;  four in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past week</TIMEX>  &MD;  to ocean
target areas as close as 20 miles from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s coast and by
staging live-fire exercises from ships and warplanes in the
140-mile-wide <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan Strait</ENAMEX> that divides <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Those activities, which the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> has decried as
``provocative'' and ``reckless,'' have unnerved Taiwanese, who are
sure to use the incident to press their requests for sales of
American missile defense systems, submarines and other military
gear.
<p>
   ``It's quite clear that the Taiwanese are going to come in with
increased concern and increased anxiety, which will lead them to be
requesting more support than we might have expected in the past,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Perry</ENAMEX> said in an interview with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox Newspapers</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``That's almost a predictable consequence of this,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Perry</ENAMEX>,
who is here on the last leg of a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="week">week-long</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Latin America</ENAMEX> trip.
``The Chinese government is trying to raise the anxiety level in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>. They will probably succeed in doing that.''
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> announced the award of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1.15 billion</NUMEX>
to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX> in a deal to provide 150 F-16 fighter jets
to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>. The first of the jets are to be delivered in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-1997</TIMEX>
under a previously awarded contract to help democratic <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>
upgrade its defenses.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX> also is seeking the purchase <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-made Harpoon
ship-killer missiles and Patriot antimissile batteries.
<p>
   Also on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s wish list is an antimissile defense umbrella
called ``theatre missile defense'' that would combine precision
radar, powerful computers and high-speed rockets to defend against
incoming missiles.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government has tried to limit weapons sales to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>
to avoid provoking <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>'s activities in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan
Strait</ENAMEX>, however, appear to add weight to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Taiwan</ENAMEX>'s request for more
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> weaponry.
<p>
   ``As of right now, the Chinese have made the case for the
Taiwanese,'' said former <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> diplomat <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John J. Tkacik Jr.</ENAMEX>,
president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Business Intelligence</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alexandria</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Va.</ENAMEX>
</TEXT>
