BC-SHUTTLE-NYT
IF WIND EASES, SPACE SHUTTLE WILL REVISIT RUSSIANS
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JOHN NOBLE WILFORD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CAPE CANAVERAL</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  For the third time in less than a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year</TIMEX>,
the space shuttle Atlantis is set for launching toward a linkup
with the Russian space station Mir, another rehearsal for the
assembly and operation of an international space station <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">later in
the decade</TIMEX>.
<p>
   But this is the first time the shuttle is to leave behind an
American astronaut. That astronaut, Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shannon Lucid</ENAMEX>, is to live
on Mir for nearly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">five months</TIMEX>. She is to be followed on Mir by at
least four other Americans on a rotating basis <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="spring of 1998">through the spring
of 1998</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Countdown preparations were proceeding smoothly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> for a
launching <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Thursday</TIMEX>. Liftoff is scheduled for <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">3:35 a.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   Officials at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> have been watching the
weather closely, and the prospects are not favorable. High winds,
whipping through the region, are expected to continue through
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">launching time</TIMEX>. Meteorologists said there was an <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">80 percent</NUMEX> chance
that weather would be unacceptable for a liftoff.
<p>
   If the launching has to be postponed, officials would try again
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Friday</TIMEX>, when the winds are supposed to have died down.
<p>
   Once off the ground, the crew of six astronauts is to steer the
Atlantis to a rendezvous and docking with Mir <TIMEX TYPE="TIME" MIN="43 hours">within 43 hours</TIMEX>  &MD;  on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, if the launching is not delayed. The shuttle is bringing
new scientific equipment and supplies to Mir, which has been in
orbit more than <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10 years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The two craft are to remain attached for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">five days</TIMEX> of joint
experiments and tests of procedures for assembling the
international space station, which is being developed under the
leadership of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> but with participation by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="sixth day">the sixth day of the flight</TIMEX>, two American astronauts  &MD;  Dr.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Linda Godwin</ENAMEX>, a physicist, and Lt. Col. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">M. Richard Clifford</ENAMEX> of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army</ENAMEX>  &MD;  are scheduled take a spacewalk to attach four experiments to
the outside of Mir. The experiments will investigate the space
environment in that particular orbit, which is the same one that
the international space station will travel.
<p>
   It will be the first spacewalk by American astronauts while the
shuttle is docked to Mir.
<p>
   After a flight of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine days</TIMEX>, the Atlantis is scheduled to land
at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cape Canaveral</ENAMEX>, with a crew of only five. Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX>, a
biochemist who has been on four previous shuttle missions, is to
remain with the two Russian astronauts on the orbiting station
until the next visit by Atlantis, scheduled for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early August</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The mission commander is Col. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kevin Chilton</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX>.
Other crew members are Lt. Col. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Searfoss</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX>
and Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ronald Sega</ENAMEX>, an electrical engineer. The Russian astronauts
on Mir are <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yuri Onufrienko</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yuri Usachev</ENAMEX>, who have been aboard
the space station for a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">month</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
