<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITE-SLUMP </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-25</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0904 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITE-SLUMP-UPDATE1-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>'S SATELLITE LAUNCHER LOSING CLIENTS TO RIVALS (UPDATE1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Hannam</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Updates with comment from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> official and more detail from
10th paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 25</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s bargain-basement
satellite launch program is losing clients to Russian and French
rivals after a spate of high-profile flops.
<p>
   At least two satellite companies, eager to meet <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX>'s growing
demand for satellite broadcasting and telecommunications, have
opted for competing launchers. A third is considering a switch.
<p>
   As more foreign companies look elsewhere, only the loyalty of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s own state-run companies is keeping the Chinese program
going, analysts said.
<p>
   ``Chinese investors are underpinning the commercial viability of
the Chinese launch program as it is losing foreign clients,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Jeffries</ENAMEX>, editor of the Asia Pacific Space Report. All
Chinese launches <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX> are expected to be delayed pending the
results of an investigation into <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last month</TIMEX>'s failure of a Long
March 3B rocket carrying an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> communications satellite.
Until recently, foreign companies were willing to trade reliability
for price to launch satellites in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Not anymore.
<p>
   Over the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">weekend</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Asia Satellite Telecommunications Co.</ENAMEX>, whose
first two satellites <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> launched, said it will send its third
into orbit on a Russian rocket. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">EchoStar Communications</ENAMEX>
canceled its <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">summer</TIMEX> launch in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX> and booked a flight
on a rocket of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianspace</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mabuhay Philippine Satellite Corp.</ENAMEX> President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Cesar Reyes</ENAMEX> said
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this month</TIMEX> the communications group will decide whether to
cancel its launch plan in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> after more tests on the cause of
the explosion. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s safety record was highlighted after an
Israeli scientist released a videotape on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> of what he said
was a village devastated by the rocket near the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX> launch site
in southwest <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>. The video, shown on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX> television,
showed dozens of flattened houses.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> has claimed only 6 people died in the crash. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Today</TIMEX>'s South
China Morning Post cited a witness as putting the figure at 100.
One industry executive said that a cover-up of casualty figures,
would raise suspicions that technology faults might also be hushed
up.
<p>
   ``There is a great deal of faith in the market in the
reliability of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s rockets,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeffries</ENAMEX> of the Space
Report. ``<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>, quite clearly, hasn't established that faith
yet.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> has successfully launched about 40 satellites in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
20 years</TIMEX>, including eight for foreign clients. It has plans to
launch 30 more satellites for foreign customers by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2000</TIMEX>. It has had
more than its fair share of accidents, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeffries</ENAMEX>. In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January
1995</TIMEX>, a Long March 2E rocket exploded one minute into its flight,
killing 6 villagers nearby. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Months earlier</TIMEX> an engineer had been
killed during a test fire.
<p>
   Officials at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall Industry Corp.</ENAMEX>, the satellite
launcher, said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s next launch, of an Apstar-1A satellite,
could come as early as <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May</TIMEX>. The launch was originally scheduled for
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX> on a Long March 3 rocket.
<p>
   The Apstar-1A satellite, built by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX>
subsidiary <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>, is owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX>
Its shareholders include <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Singapore Telecommunications Ltd.</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Thailand</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Charoen Pokphand Group</ENAMEX> and commercial arms of the
Chinese army, space and telecommunications authorities.
<p>
   Other launches lined up for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX> include the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CoSat</ENAMEX>
satellite, a joint venture between the Chinese military and the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ChinaSat</ENAMEX>, controlled
by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Telecoms Ministry</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   For customers without such loyalties there is an alternative. In
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> signed an agreement with 15 banks to provide
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$200-million</NUMEX> for the construction by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> of a high-performance
satellite. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> has selected <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Proton</ENAMEX> to launch it.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Proton</ENAMEX>, whose shareholders include <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Khrunichev State Research and Production Space Center</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RSC
Energia</ENAMEX>, is set to launch its first satellite some time <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX> official, who declined to be named, said the
``primary reason'' why <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> decided to switch was the
``astonishingly low price'' offered by the Russians. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Wade</ENAMEX>,
deputy chief executive officer of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX>, said that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX>
``could go pretty much either way'' in terms of price between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>
and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>. He said the main reason for the switch was the absence
of a Chinese launch slot in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1997</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> is partly owned by state-run <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China International Trust
and Investment Corp.</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hutchison Whampoa Ltd.</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Britain</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cable and Wireless Plc</ENAMEX> also have stakes.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sabrina Cubbins</ENAMEX>, marketing manager at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX>, said the contract
was signed before the explosion. She said that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> would look
at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s safety record when choosing who will launch <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AsiaSat</ENAMEX> 4
and 5 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">later this century</TIMEX>. Accidents affect future launch costs.
Insurance company officials will gather in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-April</TIMEX> to
review <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s investigation into the Long March 3B failure and
determine how much it will cost <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX> to insure the
next launch, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX> official said.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Shanghai</ENAMEX>-based state-owned <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Pacific Insurance
Co.</ENAMEX> insured the Apstar-1A satellite for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">2.3 billion yuan</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$280
million</NUMEX>).
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-25-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">0852EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
