<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PANAMSAT</ENAMEX>-SATELLITES-B </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-16</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0439 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PANAMSAT</ENAMEX>-SATELLITES-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PANAMSAT</ENAMEX> ORDERS TWO SATELLITES FROM <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SPACE SYSTEMS/LORAL</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Toni Clarke</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenwich</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Connecticut</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 16</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat Corp.</ENAMEX>
said it ordered two satellites from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Space Systems/Loral</ENAMEX> that will
boost its communications capacity by more than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenwich</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Connecticut</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> said the satellites will
be launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1997</TIMEX> and <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early 1998</TIMEX>, with one positioned over
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Indian Ocean</ENAMEX> to serve <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Africa</ENAMEX> and the other
over the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pacific</ENAMEX> to serve <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">North America</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eastern Asia</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Australia</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The companies didn't reveal the terms of the contract, though
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Marcus</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX>, said a satellite typically
costs <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">between $200 million and $250 million</NUMEX> to build, launch and
insure.
<p>
   The two satellites, named <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PAS</ENAMEX>-7 and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PAS</ENAMEX>-8, will include 92
transponders, the components that receive signals and relay them
back to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">earth</ENAMEX>. The greater the number of transponders, the greater
the amount of broadcast, telephone and data traffic the satellites
can handle. With the new satellites, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> will have 304
transponders in the air.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PAS</ENAMEX>-7 and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PAS</ENAMEX>-8 will enable <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> to offer vastly expanded
broadcast and business communications services to a total
geographic area representing more than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">80 percent</NUMEX> of the world's
population,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Frederick Landman</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX>'s president and
chief executive.
<p>
   Under the terms of the agreement, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Palo Alto</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">California</ENAMEX>-based
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Space Systems/Loral</ENAMEX>, a majority-owned subsidiary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX>,
will provide spacecraft components that can be put together rapidly
to produce a replacement satellite in the event of a launch
failure, or as an additional <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> satellite.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX>'s shares fell 3/4 to 28 3/4 in trading of 177,600
shares.
<p>
   The company is majority owned by Mexican broadcaster <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Grupo
Televisa SA</ENAMEX> and the family of its late founder, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rene Anselmo</ENAMEX>.
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Earlier this month</TIMEX>, it said it hired <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co.</ENAMEX> to seek a
buyer for the company.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> currently has four satellites in orbit and two under
construction, excluding <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PAS</ENAMEX>-7 and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PAS</ENAMEX>-A.
<p>
   The satellites deliver direct-to-home television services and
business communications for 300 companies in countries including
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">South Africa</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The company leases either entire transponders, or channels on a
transponder, to clients such as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Citicorp</ENAMEX>, which uses the satellite
to link its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> headquarters with branches in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Latin America</ENAMEX>, or
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Viacom Inc.</ENAMEX>, which uses it to distribute television programming to
cable systems around the world.
</TEXT>
