</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960417.0339 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A2729 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tth-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-STARS-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-17</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-STARS-SPI
SATELLITE SYSTEM COULD REVOLUTIONIZE COMMUNICATIONS ON JETLINERS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">T.M. SELL</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Seattle Post-Intelligencer</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">SEATTLE</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing Co.</ENAMEX> would like to make channel surfing a
habit for air travelers.
<p>
   A unit of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Information and Electronic Systems Division</ENAMEX>,
part of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense &AMP; Space Group</ENAMEX>, has developed an antenna that
would allow jetliners to snare satellite video feeds in midair. The
75 or so channels you can now get with the new, small home
satellite dishes could also be available in the sky.
<p>
   ``We definitely know the airlines are excited about this,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Miller</ENAMEX>, acquisition manager for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Phased Array Systems
Organization</ENAMEX>, which developed the system.
<p>
   It was, in fact, the high-powered satellites now in use for
direct-to-home broadcast that made the new product possible, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX>
said.
<p>
   Most satellite antennae involve dishes, large or small, that
have to be physically moved or rotated to pick up signals. Those
kinds of antennae won't work on jetliners because the aircraft
moves and the antenna would constantly be out of sync with the
satellite feed. Also, anything that protrudes more than a few
inches from the surface of an aircraft would change its handling
features and increase fuel consumption.
<p>
   So <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> engineers married the technology to a high-tech
antenna that doesn't mind moving, and called it STARS, for
Satellite Telemetry Airborne Receiving System.
<p>
   Instead of a big dish, STARS incorporates a series of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">dime</NUMEX>-size
receptors that are reoriented electronically to lock onto satellite
signals.
<p>
   The result is a flat antenna, 24 inches by 44 inches and less
than 2 inches high when mounted on an aircraft. Including
associated hardware, it weighs about 200 pounds and is relatively
easy to install on existing aircraft. It would be mounted atop the
fuselage between the wings.
<p>
   Airlines regard multiple TV channels as frosting on the cake,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said. They're especially interested in moving data on and
off aircraft, such as automatically downloading ``black box''
recorder information on a regular basis.
<p>
   ``Airlines are very interested in what it would do to their
operating costs,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said. Downloading flight data is labor
intensive; automatic downloading also would allow airlines to make
operational adjustments more rapidly.
<p>
   ``They would know what was wrong with the aircraft before it
ever landed,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   STARS can read two satellites at once, so any aircraft equipped
with the antenna can send as well as receive, setting up the
possibility of more interactive communications for passengers as
well as flight crew. The system sends information from the aircraft
in large bursts, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said, but to a passenger changing hotel
reservations at his or her next stop, the effect will be in real
time.
<p>
   Current systems move about 2,400 bits, or 2.4 kilobits, of data
a second, he said. STARS can move 500,000 kilobits a second. ``It's
a huge breakthrough as far as getting large volumes of data to a
moving platform,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Airlines are looking at loading manuals, weather maps and
operational data via STARS. They also could load movies via
satellite, instead of taking on new videotapes each month.
<p>
   ``With new entertainment systems, each passenger will basically
have a personal computer in their seat back,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The price is right, too: about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$95,000</NUMEX> for the antenna, or a
monthly fee for the antenna and the satellite system. The latter
will be supplied in part by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commercial Space Co.</ENAMEX>, the
company's budding space venture, which also is involved in
satellite launches, new satellite systems and data communications.
<p>
   ``We've made some huge strides in lowering the cost compared to
our competition,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The competition now is land-based communications systems, such
as those that let people talk by phone in midflight. Nobody else is
making an antenna quite like STARS, but <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> doesn't expect
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s head start to last long.
<p>
   ``That will only last <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="18 months">about 18 months</TIMEX>,'' he said. ``We're
already working on improvements.''
<p>
   The system started with military applications, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> is
still pursuing those. Smaller phased array antennae can be mounted
on battlefield vehicles, with satellite-feed data relayed via
military command jets or unmanned aerial vehicles.
<p>
   Even though it's becoming a commercial product, STARS will stay
with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Phased Array Systems</ENAMEX>. ``We're going to be working very closely
with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing Commercial Airplane Group</ENAMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Miller</ENAMEX> said. ``They open
all the doors.''
<p>
   The system probably won't go on sale until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1997</TIMEX>, and a lot of
in-flight testing remains. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">This summer</TIMEX>, the antenna will be mounted
on a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>-owned <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cessna</ENAMEX> 206. It eventually will make its way to
WA001, the original 777 aircraft that is <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s latest flying
test bed.
</TEXT>
