BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">ISRAEL</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LEBANON</ENAMEX>-440&AMP;add-COX
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> DIPLOMATIC EFFORT FOR TRUCE GRINDS ON, AS DOES THE FIGHTING
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CHARLES W. HOLMES</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">JERUSALEM</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Secretary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Warren Christopher</ENAMEX>, shuttling
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jerusalem</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Damascus</ENAMEX>, said he was confident of
achieving a cease-fire in southern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> despite ``some difficult
questions to work through.''
<p>
   But hopes for a quick truce faded further <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> as the
cross-border conflict between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX> guerrillas
entered <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="11th day">its 11th day</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Katyusha</ENAMEX> rocket attacks on northern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>
were answered by Israeli bombardments in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> by warplanes,
gunboats and artillery, although reports said the fighting had
eased compared to previous days.
<p>
   Despite the diplomatic scramble, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> officials told reporters
that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> still has not been informed by Syrian or Lebanese
intermediaries of the terms <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX>, the pro-Iranian <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Party of
God</ENAMEX>, would accept for a cease-fire.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> has said it would halt its operation when <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX>'s
rockets stop falling on its towns in the north. But the Israeli
cabinet reiterated <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> that the Jewish state would not
unilaterally halt its attacks in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> met <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> with President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hafez Assad</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX>
before traveling to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> for two rounds of talks with Prime
Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shimon Peres</ENAMEX>. He returned to the Syrian capital <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> for talks again on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Assad</ENAMEX>, and is expected to meet
with Prime Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rafiq Hariri</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>, possibly by going to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beirut</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX> has about 40,000 troops stationed in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> and greatly
influences political and security matters in the country. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX>
controls the routes through which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX> receives money and
weapons from its prime backer, the Islamic government in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> embarked on his diplomatic mission in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Middle
East</ENAMEX> after Israeli shelling killed more than 100 Lebanese civilians
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>. The urgent diplomacy comes after the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>
administration initially backed the Israeli air and artillery
assault.
<p>
   Now, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> is attempting to win assurances that the
current fighting will stop, at least temporarily, to allow
negotiations for new rules for limiting the conflict.
<p>
   ``We should try and not only get a cease-fire, but an enduring
set of understandings which commits the parties in the region to
prevent the recurrence of this kind of event,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Foreign Ministers <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yevgeny Primakov</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Herve de
Charette</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> were also in the region seeking to broker an end
to the fighting.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peres</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> considered only the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> effort the basis
for a lasting truce.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peres</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> would listen to all proposals, ``but we cannot
have three agreements on the same issue because this will mean no
agreement at all,'' he told the news conference after meeting with
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows).
<p>
   All the diplomatic efforts seek to build on an unwritten <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX>
agreement brokered by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> in which <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX>
agreed that civilians would be off-limits.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>'s blitz, launched <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 11</TIMEX> in response to rocket attacks,
has killed more than 150 Lebanese, most of them civilians, and
forced 400,000 Lebanese to flee their homes. In <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>, no one has
died, though more than 30 have been wounded and northern residents
have been forced to live in bomb shelters or flee south out of
range of the sporadic rockets.
<p>
   Lebanese officials say a permanent truce will be possible only
when <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> agrees to move its troops out of an occupation zone
inside southern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> that the Jewish state uses as a buffer to
protect its northern border from attacks.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX> gave priority <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> to a French proposal that reportedly
would put the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX> agreement in writing and call on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United
States</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX> and European nations to guarantee that
violations would not occur.
<p>
   ``The French plan has several positive points which are worth
discussion to solve the current crisis,'' Foreign Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Farouq
al-Sharaa</ENAMEX> said in the statement issued by the official <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Syrian News
Agency</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
