<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CANAL-PLUS</ENAMEX>-DIGITAL-TV </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-26</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0565 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CANAL-PLUS</ENAMEX>-DIGITAL-TV-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CANAL PLUS</ENAMEX> TO LAUNCH <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">EUROPE</ENAMEX>'S FIRST DIGITAL-TV SERVICE <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">TOMORROW</TIMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vidya N. Root</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 26</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>'s biggest
pay-TV company, will launch the continent's first digital
television service <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">tomorrow</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> will offer 10 digital channels on its satellite-TV
unit Canalsatellite, including films and sports, company officials
said. The company's three transponders for digital TV can broadcast
as many as 24 channels.
<p>
   The launch marks the ``a veritable cultural revolution that will
also shape the company,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pierre Lescure</ENAMEX>, chairman of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX>,
said in an interview with Le Monde.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> expects to log up to 1.5 million digital pay-TV
subscribers by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of the decade</TIMEX>. It needs more than 850,000
subscribers to break even and doesn't expect a return on its
investment for about <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">five years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   In recent trading, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> shares were up <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">17 francs</NUMEX> at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">1,262
france</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX>'s launch comes as a rival group called <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Television par
satellite</ENAMEX> prepares to broadcast its own program of digital-TV
programs in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX>. The group pools together French
television stations <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TF1</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">M6</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">France Television</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Luxembourg</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Compagnie Luxembourgeoise de Telediffusion</ENAMEX>, or <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CLT</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The group is a ``coalition of francophone interests against a
French company,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lescure</ENAMEX> said. Although he said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX>' talks
with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TF1</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CLT</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">France Television</ENAMEX> over digital television have
failed, ``the tensions between the various audiovisual groups <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>
will soon no longer be relevant,'' he said.
<p>
   Digital TV lets broadcasters send eight channels via a satellite
transponder that earlier carried only one. It does this by
converting television pictures into digital data -- a series of
electronic ones and zeros that can be manipulated to change just
parts of a picture, rather than the whole frame.
<p>
   While digitization increases the number of channels -- and thus
the amount of advertising -- that a company can broadcast, it also
demands huge investment in the face of unquantifiable demand.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> will distribute its digital service through its
Canalsatellite unit using the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Luxembourg</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Societe Europeene
des Satellites</ENAMEX>' Astra satellite.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> has also begun a pilot digital service in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>
with its partners, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Havas SA</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bertelsmann AG</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Sky
Broadcasting Group Plc</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Customers will need a special digital decoder to receive the
services.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1994</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> picked five companies to build decoders for
its digital service -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Thomson Multimedia</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philips Electronics NV</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sony Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pioneer</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sagem</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Thomson</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philips</ENAMEX> have machines
ready for sale, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> executives said, and will be followed by
the other three.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last month</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Thomson</ENAMEX> said it has produced 20,000 digital
decoders, or interactive terminals. The company said the decoders
will cost about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">4,000 to 4,500 French francs</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$800 to $900</NUMEX>).
<p>
   Because the cost of the decoders is high, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus</ENAMEX> said it's
also offering to buy the decoders from the five suppliers and lease
them out to users for about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">50 francs</NUMEX> a month, the company said.
<p>
   With several suppliers and possible increase in demand, the
price of decoders is expected to fall over the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next five years</TIMEX>, the
company said.
</TEXT>
