<DOCID> nyt960426.0663 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=k pri=u> A5420 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-EDIT-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MIDEAST</ENAMEX>-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-26</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-EDIT-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MIDEAST</ENAMEX>-NYT
EDITORIAL: THE CEASE-FIRE IN <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LEBANON</ENAMEX>
(HLW)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday, April 27</TIMEX>:
<p>
   Thanks to the tireless and skillful mediation of Secretary of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Warren Christopher</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two weeks</TIMEX> of warfare and upheaval in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> and northern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> are ending. No party emerged a
clear-cut winner from the fighting, but all can claim some benefit
from the diplomacy that ended it.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> achieved its minimum objectives, though at a cost. It won
a promise from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> to see that Iranian-backed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX>
guerrillas launch no further rocket attacks against <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> from its
territory. The bombardment, coming after recent suicide bombings in
Israeli cities, had caused many Israelis to question the efficacy
of peace agreements. Prime Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shimon Peres</ENAMEX>, who faces
elections <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next month</TIMEX>, demonstrated that he remains prepared to
defend <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>'s security with military force when necessary even as
he presses ahead with peace talks.
<p>
   But the civilian casualties caused by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>'s military
operations, especially the 75 killed in the accidental attack on a
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.N.</ENAMEX> base crowded with refugees, clouded the legitimate Israeli
objective of self-defense.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>, for its part, won relief from the pounding it has taken
from all sides. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> has now promised that its forces, in pursuit
of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX> fighters, will no longer fire at civilian targets in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>. In the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last two weeks</TIMEX>, more than 150 Lebanese civilians
were killed, 400,000 fled their homes and the country's roads and
water systems were heavily damaged.
<p>
   Israeli troops will remain in a security zone they have
maintained just inside <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX> since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1978</TIMEX>, and the Israeli forces
and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX> guerrillas will probably continue to exchange fire
there. But the new understanding also encourages peace talks
involving <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX> aimed at resolving some of the
issues that led to the fighting, including the existence of the
Israeli zone.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX>, which was not an innocent bystander to the conflict, may
have gained the most from the cease-fire agreement by reclaiming a
central role for itself in the region.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Syrian army</ENAMEX> controls security in much of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>, and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX> would probably not have launched its rocket attacks
without Syrian approval. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX>'s president, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hafez Assad</ENAMEX>, no doubt
knew the inevitable consequence of unleashing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX> would be
Israeli military action against <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>. Once the shooting started,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Assad</ENAMEX> sat back in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Damascus</ENAMEX> and waited for <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christopher</ENAMEX> and other
foreign diplomats to pay him court.
<p>
   After a semblance of peace is restored to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Syria</ENAMEX> must resume the hard business of negotiating their own peace
agreement. It will not be a moment too soon.
</TEXT>
