<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A0787 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LORAL</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANE</ENAMEX>-UPDATE2- </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-01</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0628 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LORAL</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANE</ENAMEX>-UPDATE2-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LORAL</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANESPACE</ENAMEX> SIGN AGREEMENT FOR 5 LAUNCHES (UPDATE2)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kristin Jensen</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Adds closing share price in paragraph 7. Adds <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> comment
in last two paragraphs.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 1</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Space
Systems/Loral</ENAMEX> signed an agreement to launch five commercial
satellites <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2000|year 2000">through the year 2000</TIMEX>.
<p>
   As part of the agreement, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> satellites will be launched on
an Ariane 5 launcher in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">first half of 1998</TIMEX> and four other
flights <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2000|year 2000">through the year 2000</TIMEX>, said executives from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>. The exact payloads of each launch have yet to be
determined, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Berry</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SS/L</ENAMEX>, a subsidiary of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Space &AMP; Communications Ltd.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   ``By making these future launch service commitments at <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
time</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SS/Loral</ENAMEX> obtains a set competitive price and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>
firms up its calendar for future bookings,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Still, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis Avanzi</ENAMEX>, executive vice president and
chief operating officer of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, refused to give any details
of the cost of the contract.
<p>
   ``It's within a competitive framework of all the launchers,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX> said. ``It's not the lowest price launch, but it is a launch
service that's able to compete around the world.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Avanzi</ENAMEX> said his company wanted to speak about ``value to our
customers'' rather than price.
<p>
   Shares in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Space &AMP; Communications</ENAMEX> rose 1/8 to close at 14
1/2 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, a privately-held consortium of more than 50
European aerospace-related manufacturers, has stepped up its joint
satellite-launch ventures to respond to a potential glut of rocket
launch service providers. ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> is obviously open to this
kind of thing,'' chairman and chief executive <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles Bigot</ENAMEX> said in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tokyo</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> is also planning to set up a subsidiary to offer
customers financing, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Avanzi</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The first launch of an Ariane 5 will take place <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Avanzi</ENAMEX> said. By the time the first <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> launch takes place,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> hopes to have had 5 or 6 other Ariane 5 launches, he
said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX>'s decision to sign an agreement for five <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>
launches is ``an expression of confidence'' in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX>
said. It doesn't mean that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> won't be working with other
companies, he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> is looking at American companies to provide launches for
satellites, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX> said. The company is also keeping its options to
send satellites on Long March rockets from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>, even after a Long
March 3B rocket carrying an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> satellite exploded in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX> had built the satellite, which <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert
Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> had planned to
use to beam television signals to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Latin America</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX> referred critics of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s commercial space program to
setbacks in the early days of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> space program.
<p>
   ``Pay attention to what has happened and what hasn't happened
and then put it into context,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Berry</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Space</ENAMEX> was created as part of the merger of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX> Under terms of that agreement, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> can
own as much as <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">20 percent</NUMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Space</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> has launched many <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> satellites in the past, said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Virnell Bruce</ENAMEX>, a spokeswoman for the company's space and strategic
missiles sector. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX>'s decision to sign an agreement with
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> for five launches isn't a reflection on future launches
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> may do for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX>, she said.
<p>
   ``Many factors determine launch vehicle selection for
satellites, including availability, capability and cost,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bruce</ENAMEX>
said. Besides, she said, ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> and other satellite manufacturers
have long-standing relationships with all the launch vehicle
manufacturers.''
</TEXT>
