<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSKYB</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">9-MONTH</TIMEX> PRETAX UP <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">71%</NUMEX>; BUYS DIGITAL CAPACITY (UPDATE2)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edward Orlebar</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Rewrites 1st paragraph; adds finance director's comment in 4th,
5th paragraphs; background in 6th paragraph.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 7</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc</ENAMEX>
said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine-month</TIMEX> pretax profit rose <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">71 percent</NUMEX> and said it had
leased satellite capacity for a digital television service to be
launched in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> satellite television broadcaster said its subscriber
base grew <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">17.5 percent</NUMEX> during <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the past year</TIMEX> to 5.35 million,
boosting pretax profit for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine months to March 31</TIMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">178
million pounds</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$269 million</NUMEX>). That's up from <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">104 million pounds</NUMEX> in
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year-earlier period</TIMEX>. Earnings per share rose <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">53 percent</NUMEX>, to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">9.7
pence</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX> also said it had agreed with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Societe Europeene des
Satellites</ENAMEX> to lease half the capacity of a new Astra satellite,
which will be launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1997</TIMEX>. The 14 transponders, which
transmit television signals to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>, will be used to provide a
digital service in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next year</TIMEX> with space for up to 140
channels.
<p>
   ``We will probably offer the digital service from the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">autumn of
next year</TIMEX>, when the satellite is launched,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Brooke</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>'s finance director, in an interview.
<p>
   He said the agreement with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SES</ENAMEX> cost less than the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">375 million
pounds</NUMEX> it's paying for 10 digital transponders on other Astra
satellites, which would be used for transmission to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   With digital technology between six and ten channels can be
broadcast at the same time through a single transponder, compared
with only one under existing analogue systems.
<p>
   Sales rose <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">30 percent</NUMEX>, to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">736 million pounds</NUMEX>, and operating
profit <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">32 percent</NUMEX>, to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">223 million pounds</NUMEX>.
<p>
   ``The results are in line with expectations,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeffrey
Harwood</ENAMEX>, an analyst at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Robert Fleming Securities</ENAMEX>. ``The subscriber
numbers are quite good.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>'s shares rose as much as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">10 pence</NUMEX> or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2.2 percent</NUMEX>, before
falling back to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">461p</NUMEX>, up <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">7p</NUMEX>. That's down from a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">52- week</TIMEX> high of
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">484.5</NUMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 2</TIMEX>. The shares have risen from a low of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">266</NUMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 23
last year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">From January to March</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> subscribers rose by 149,000 compared
with 90,000 for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">equivalent period in 1995</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``The excellent financial performance reflects the continued
growth in our subscriber base, which has been at record levels <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
year</TIMEX>,'' said Chief Executive <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam Chisholm</ENAMEX> in a statement.
<p>
   ``The company is strongly positioned to take advantage of the
further opportunity offered by digital technology in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> and
mainland <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>,'' he said.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>, which is <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX> owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX>, said it would forge an alliance with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bertelsmann AG</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus SA</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Havas SA</ENAMEX> in what analysts say is an attempt to
dominate the emerging digital pay-TV market.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX> said about 660,000 subscribers paid to watch <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Frank Bruno</ENAMEX>
defend his WBC World Heavyweight title fight against <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mike Tyson</ENAMEX> on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 17</TIMEX>, in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX>'s first pay-per-view broadcast.
<p>
   It said its churn rate, the rate of cancellations, ``was not
materially affected by the launch of a pay-per-view event, nor by
higher prices in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX>.''
</TEXT>
