million pounds</NUMEX> from <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">49.04 million pounds</NUMEX> previously. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nigel Reed</ENAMEX>, an
analyst at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Paribas Capital Markets</ENAMEX>, said the company is on course
for his <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">full-year</TIMEX> forecast of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">248 million pounds</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>'s shares rose as much as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">10 pence</NUMEX> or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2.2 percent</NUMEX>, before
falling back to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">454p</NUMEX>, unchanged. That's down from a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">52-week</TIMEX> high of
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">484.5</NUMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 2</TIMEX>. The shares have risen from a low of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">266</NUMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 23
last year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">From January to March</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> subscribers rose by 149,000
compared with 90,000 for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">equivalent period in 1995</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``The excellent financial performance reflects the continued
growth in our subscriber base, which has been at record levels <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
year</TIMEX>,'' said Chief Executive <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam Chisholm</ENAMEX> in a statement.
<p>
   ``The company is strongly positioned to take advantage of the
further opportunity offered by digital technology in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> and
mainland <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>,'' he added.
<p>
   Press reports have said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX> is negotiating with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BBC</ENAMEX> for it
to provide up to 12 new channels for the digital system, and with
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Branson</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Virgin Group Ltd</ENAMEX>, which may provide channels for
young people.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brooke</ENAMEX> said the company is talking to most of the
terrestrial broadcasters and was interested in signing agreements.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>, which is <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX> owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX>, said it would forge an alliance with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bertelsmann AG</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Canal Plus SA</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Havas SA</ENAMEX> in what analysts say is an attempt to
dominate the emerging digital pay-TV market.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX> said about 660,000 subscribers paid to watch <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Frank Bruno</ENAMEX>
defend his <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WBC</ENAMEX> World Heavyweight title fight against <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mike Tyson</ENAMEX> on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 17</TIMEX>, in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX>'s first pay-per-view broadcast.
<p>
   It said its churn rate, the rate of cancellations, ``was not
materially affected by the launch of a pay-per-view event, nor by
higher prices in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX>.'' The churn rate is <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">between 12 percent
and 13 percent</NUMEX>, it said.
</TEXT>
