<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-ROCKET-2TAKES-$A </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-10</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0896 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-ROCKET-2TAKES-$ADV12-HNS
(EDs: For release <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday, May 12</TIMEX>)
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> EMBARKS ON QUEST FOR REUSABLE ROCKET TO REPLACE SHUTTLE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Though faced with daunting technical and financial
hurdles, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX> embarks
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this week</TIMEX> on an ambitious campaign to develop a revolutionary
reusable rocket.
<p>
   It is the first attempt by the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> to build a major
new rocket transportation system since the space shuttle a
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">quarter-century ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Proponents believe plans by the space agency to spend <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 billion</NUMEX>
to build and fly the X-33 in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">three years</TIMEX> will blaze a trail to the
spacefarers' Holy Grail  &MD;  cheap transportation off the planet.
<p>
   The X-33 is a small, test version of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s ultimate goal, a
fully reusable, single-stage, unpiloted rocket that would gradually
replace the shuttle and the country's stable of commercial rockets
after the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">turn of the century</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Skeptics question, however, whether technologies will emerge
rapidly enough to supply the tough but lightweight construction
materials and robust propulsion system vital to the program's
success.
<p>
   More significantly, they wonder if the space agency, which faces
sharply falling budgets, has a practical financing strategy for the
estimated <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5 billion to $10 billion</NUMEX> that will be required to build
the full-sized craft.
<p>
   ``There is some real thrust behind this,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jerry Grey</ENAMEX>,
director of aerospace and science policy for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Institute
of Aeronautics and Astronautics</ENAMEX>. ``But there are some real
problems, any of which could be a show stopper.''
<p>
   Within aerospace circles, the groundbreaking technology <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> is
pioneering is called single-stage-to-orbit, or SSTO, and the craft
is known as a reusable launch vehicle, or RLV. The shuttle, in
comparison, has a two-stage propulsion system, with a towering
costly external propellent tank that is used once.
<p>
   The ultimate aims of the effort are to:
<p>
    &MD;  Produce a fully reusable, one-stage rocket by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2008</TIMEX>.
<p>
    &MD;  Design it for 100 orbital missions and simplified ground
operations in order to drop the cost of delivering cargo to orbit
from <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10,000</NUMEX> per pound now to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1,000</NUMEX> per pound or less.
<p>
   In a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1994</TIMEX> policy decision, the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> administration asked <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>
to develop a craft that remedied the main frustration with the
shuttle, which can do many things but is too mechanically complex
to be an inexpensive, frequent flier.
<p>
   The space agency is using a phased approach. The X-33 must score
high marks during its series of test flights before a national
policy decision to proceed with the RLV.
<p>
   For the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past year</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell International</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>, using <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$7 million</NUMEX> each in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> seed money, have
been preparing competitive proposals for an X-33 and a development
scheme for an SSTO. All three plan to meet <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> deadline
for the submission.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early July</TIMEX>, the space agency will select one of the companies
as its industrial partner for the X-33. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Marshall Space Flight
Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Huntsville</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ala.</ENAMEX>, will lead the development effort.
<p>
   As it gradually replaces the space shuttle, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> envisions
equipping the new rocket with a crew capsule or possibly a small
spaceplane to carry its astronauts to and from orbit.
<p>
   ``This program has strong support in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> and from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White
House</ENAMEX>.'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lori Garver</ENAMEX>, executive director of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Space
Society</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>-based public interest group, and a member of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA Advisory Council</ENAMEX>. ``There have been several other attempts
with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of Defense</ENAMEX> that took a stab at a new vehicle.
All have failed.''
<p>
   A succession of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>-led programs called the Advanced Launch
System, the National Launch System and Spacelifter as well as a
joint effort with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> called the National Aerospace Plane all
faltered over the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past decade</TIMEX> from lack of legislative backing.
<p>
   ``We are changing the rules of the game,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gary Payton</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>-based director of advanced transportation. ``We
are not trying incremental improvements. Everything is brand new.''
<p>
   If <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> adheres to the safeguards of its SSTO development
strategy, it could never proceed further than the X-33 without
demonstrating prescribed breakthroughs, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Payton</ENAMEX> contends.
<p>
   Those include lightweight composite propellant tanks; a sensor
system throughout the spacecraft to alert a small ground crew to
maintenance needs and potential equipment failures; and rocket
engines superior to the shuttle's.
<p>
   MORE ... MORE
</TEXT>
