<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A9909 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-17</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
SHUTTLE CREW TO DEPLOY GIANT BALLOON
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">STEFANIE ASIN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CAPE CANAVERAL</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Macy</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thanksgiving Day</TIMEX> parade may
have to give up bragging rights after the space shuttle Endeavour
crew flies its version of a giant balloon <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The astronauts will inflate a 100-foot-long Mylar antenna that
will grow to almost the size of the shuttle. The exercise is
designed to test techniques for deploying large but lightweight
inflatable structures.
<p>
   The antenna is the centerpiece of a variety of science and
technology experiments on the mission.
<p>
   The shuttle and its six astronauts are scheduled to lift off
from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy
Space Center</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">6:30 a.m. EDT</TIMEX>. Countdown activities for
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10-day</TIMEX> mission were proceeding smoothly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, and the weather
outlook remained favorable.
<p>
   ``Overall, we have no technical concerns,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Debbie
Frostrom</ENAMEX>, who supervises countdown activities at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The crew, with one rookie and five veterans, will deploy two
research satellites in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="first four days">the first four days of the mission</TIMEX> and then
maneuver the shuttle to rendezvous with the small crafts.
<p>
   The shuttle's pilot, Lt. Col. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Curtis Brown, Jr.</ENAMEX>, said the
mission is a dream flight for a pilot.
<p>
   ``We get to do a lot of flying,'' he said. ``The rendezvous will
be the cream of the flight.''
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="second day">the second day of the mission</TIMEX>, the astronauts will release a
small spacecraft called Spartan-207, which has been used for
astronomy research on seven prior missions. On this trip, Spartan
will serve as a platform for unfurling the inflatable antenna.
<p>
   ``This is going to be a unique one. And one that has the
potential to be very visually exciting and spectacular even,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark Steiner</ENAMEX>, Spartan mission manager.
<p>
   By successfully inflating the antenna in orbit, researchers hope
to figure out a way to deploy other large structures at low cost.
<p>
   Here's how the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$14 million</NUMEX> technology experiment works: The
Spartan, carrying a canister about the size of a kitchen table,
will be lifted out of the payload bay by the shuttle's long robotic
arm and released.
<p>
   As it orbits, Spartan will be activated, and the shuttle will
back 400 feet away from the 2,800-pound experiment.
<p>
   Almost immediately, the side flaps on the canister will fold
down and the antenna, with its three 92-foot-long struts and
50-foot-wide dish, will be inflated like a balloon with nitrogen
gas. The <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">million-dollar</NUMEX> structure will grow to about the size of a
tennis court within <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">five minutes</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The crew will then observe the structure for an orbit (about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">90
minutes</TIMEX>) before the antenna is jettisoned from the satellite. ``I
think it's going to be a really amazing sight, because it'll be a
huge ... silver mirror,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andy Thomas</ENAMEX>, the rookie mission
specialist on the flight.
<p>
   The <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next day</TIMEX>, the shuttle will rendezvous with Spartan, and a
crew member will use the robotic arm to retrieve the carrier and
return it to its cargo bay cradle. The inflatable structure should
burn up within days.
<p>
   If the deployment procedure proves workable, functional versions
of the antenna will be coated with a substance that hardens when
exposed to sunlight, giving the structure a protective shell.
<p>
   Endeavour also will carry a Satellite Test Unit to try out a new
laser-based attitude system for positioning spacecraft. On the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="fourth day">fourth day of the mission</TIMEX>, the STU, a small, brightly colored
canister, will be ejected from the payload in an unstable attitude,
with the top weighted like a dart. The shuttle will immediately
back away from the tumbling satellite.
<p>
   Scientists hope the thin atmosphere and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s magnetic
field will stabilize the satellite, eliminating the need for
heavier and more costly guidance and steering thruster systems. The
STU's stabilization and performance will be measured by using a
laser that illuminates the STU's reflectors and records images on a
mounted camera.
<p>
   The shuttle will rendezvous with the STU <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="three days">three days after its
release</TIMEX> and possibly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">four days later</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Also aboard Endeavour will be a series of science experiments,
including the study of crystal growth in microgravity, the study of
semi-conducting material when heated in space, and the observation
of 12 rats.
<p>
   Mission specialist <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Bursch</ENAMEX>, Commander <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Casper</ENAMEX>, Mission
Specialist <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mario Runco</ENAMEX> and Canadian mission specialist <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marc Garneau</ENAMEX>
make up the rest of the crew.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-17-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2124EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
