BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ASTRONAUTS INFLATE ANTENNA IN SPACE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">STEPHANIE ASIN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Endeavour's astronauts inflated a huge Mylar antenna
in space <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, but it unexpectedly tumbled end over end, leaving
researchers unable to get a good look at it.
<p>
   The release of the tennis court-sized balloon on the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="second day">second day
of the shuttle's <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10-day</TIMEX> mission</TIMEX> appeared to go smoothly. The
prototype antenna popped from its carrier like a jack-in-the-box,
and its three 92-foot accordion struts inflated as planned. But the
antenna, with its large parabolic dish supported by the struts,
began rotating and tumbling.
<p>
   Researchers could not confirm if the 50-foot diameter dish
inflated fully because of the constant motion.
<p>
   ``There is a concern that maybe it didn't,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Steven Bard</ENAMEX>,
project manager. ``It didn't look like we thought it would, but
maybe we didn't know what it would look like with the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> in the
background and the way the lighting was.''
<p>
   Researchers also were surprised by what appeared to be a
rippling on the surface of the dish. The researchers will get some
answers when the shuttle returns to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> with the recorded data.
<p>
   Regardless, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bard</ENAMEX> said, the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$14 million</NUMEX> experiment showed that
large structures can be inflated in orbit. Researchers want to
learn how to deploy inflatable structures, because they weigh less,
cost less and may be more reliable.
<p>
   ``Even in the worst case, from what we've seen, it's very close
to a full success,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bard</ENAMEX> said of the experiment. ``I think we will
learn a lot from this that will take us to using it for
applications.''
<p>
   Astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mario Runco</ENAMEX> used the shuttle's 50-foot robotic arm to
deploy Spartan, a satellite used as the inflatable's platform. The
antenna was stored in a large box atop Spartan. After the satellite
was released, the shuttle backed away by about 400 feet.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Two hours later</TIMEX>, when the flaps of the box folded down, the
antenna unfurled. It was inflated with nitrogen gas within minutes
and looked like a silver parachute.
<p>
   From the shuttle, video pictures taken of the huge antenna
reflecting the sun with the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Grand Canyon</ENAMEX> in the background were
breathtaking. The antenna was observed for one orbit, about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">90
minutes</TIMEX>, and then was jettisoned from Spartan.
<p>
   The antenna is expected to re-enter the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere and
burn up sometime <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>. Spartan mission manager <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark Steiner</ENAMEX> said
the tumbling problem will have to be resolved before a working
antenna can be deployed.
<p>
   The deployment of the balloon came a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">day</TIMEX> after the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">dawn</TIMEX> launch
of Endeavour from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX>. For the
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME" MIN="Monday">rest of Monday</TIMEX>, the crew turned its attention to several science
experiments, including studies of sea urchin eggs and mussels.
<p>
   ~
</TEXT>
