BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
SHUTTLE CREW RETRIEVES SATELLITE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">STEFANIE ASIN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Endeavour's Canadian astronaut used the shuttle's
robot arm to pluck an 1800-pound satellite from space and return it
to its berth in the cargo bay <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The shuttle flew within 35 feet of the Spartan satellite after a
series of small steering-jet maneuvers. The rendezvous was the
first of a record four planned for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10-day</TIMEX> shuttle mission.
<p>
   ``That was a real pretty piece of flying <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission
Control</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX> told shuttle Commander
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Casper</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marc Garneau</ENAMEX>, who became the first Canadian in space
in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1984</TIMEX>, reached out from the shuttle with the 50-foot mechanical
arm to capture the Spartan satellite, which was used in the
mission's primary experiment <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>. The satellite was hooked to
the arm for about an <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">hour</TIMEX> before it was slowly returned to its
cradle and latched down.
<p>
   Spartan was used as a platform for the inflation of a huge
antenna, which later was jettisoned from the satellite. Spartan
carries important data from that experiment, which tested lighter
and less expensive ways to put large structures in space.
Researchers are anxious to get Spartan back to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>, because it
was difficult for them to see if the antenna's parabolic dish had
inflated. The antenna had unexpectedly tumbled end over end, making
it hard to see its shape clearly.
<p>
   Inside Spartan are measurements taken by lasers and pressure
sensors that will provide some answers for researchers. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>
officials said the antenna, Spartan and the shuttle were visible in
some parts of the southern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE|TIME">early Tuesday morning</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Officials at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX> saw the spacecraft.
<p>
   ``It was the brightest orbiting object I think most of us have
seen,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill McArthur</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission Control</ENAMEX>. ``We saw a faint
little Spartan streaking across the sky with Endeavour in hot
pursuit.''
<p>
   The antenna was expected to re-enter <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere and burn
up.
<p>
   The shuttle crew will deploy a second satellite <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> in an
experiment to test whether <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s magnetic field can be used to
help stabilize an object in orbit. It the test is successful, it
could lead to a new generation of satellites that would not need
steering jets.
<p>
   The multiple rendezvous required on Endeavour's mission make
fuel conservation crucial. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Casper</ENAMEX> had to burn more fuel than
planned <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> to keep up with the tumbling antenna but made up for
it <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> by using less than expected for the Spartan rendezvous.
<p>
   Endeavour's only problem on the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="third day">third day of the mission</TIMEX> was
that its Coke machine is on the fritz. The soft drinks, which are
flying as part of a fluids experiment, are not being dispensed
properly. The crew spent some time before <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">bedtime</TIMEX> troubleshooting
the problem.
</TEXT>
