<STORYID cat=w pri=u> A5128 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tad-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CLINTON</ENAMEX>-477&AMP;ADD-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-22</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0732 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CLINTON</ENAMEX>-477&AMP;ADD-COX
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CLINTON</ENAMEX>: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GOP</ENAMEX> MISSILE PLAN `MISGUIDED,' `WASTEFUL'
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JULIA MALONE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW LONDON</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Conn.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> used a commencement speech
at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Coast Guard Academy</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> to launch a broad
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">election year</TIMEX> defense of his foreign policy and attack Republicans
for a ``misguided'' missile defense program.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> lashed into the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GOP</ENAMEX> anti-missile system just as the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congressional Budget Office</ENAMEX> was estimating the cost at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$30 billion
to $60 billion</NUMEX>, a price tag so high that even congressional
Republicans who were expecting the cost to be <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">between $4 billion
and $15 billion</NUMEX> were backing away from it.
<p>
   On Capitol Hill, lawmakers delayed action on the missile defense
shield, which has been proposed by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s Republican
presidential rival <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> Majority Leader <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert J. Dole</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House</ENAMEX>
Speaker <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Newt Gingrich</ENAMEX>, R-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ga.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   Even so, the cost estimates gave the Democratic president an
opening to attack his conservative critics for wasteful spending.
<p>
   ``The possibility of a long-range missile attack on American
soil by a rogue state is more than a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">decade</TIMEX> away,'' the president
said, as he dismissed the Republican plan as a costly program that
could be obsolete by the time it's built.
<p>
   ``I believe this plan is misguided,'' he said. ``It would weaken
our defenses by taking money away from things we know we need right
now.''
<p>
   The so-called National Missile Defense system calls for air- and
ground-based weapons to shoot down incoming missiles, and is
especially designed to ward off future threats from countries such
as <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iraq</ENAMEX> or <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> argued that his own program is ``based on
real threats and pragmatic responses.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s aides offered cost details later that gave a somewhat
less drastic picture of the Republican proposal. The price estimate
of up to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$60 billion</NUMEX> would include both research and construction
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2010|year 2010">through the year 2010</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> press secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael McCurry</ENAMEX>
told reporters. The Republican system is estimated to cost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10
billion</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">between now and the year 2003</TIMEX>, he said.
<p>
   By contrast, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> called for spending <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.5 billion</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2003|year 2003">through
the year 2003</TIMEX>, but only for researching and developing a defensive
shield against long- and medium-range missiles. He has offered no
plans for actual construction.
<p>
   On a shimmering day with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX>'s three-masted tall
ship, the Eagle, visible in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Thames River</ENAMEX> nearby, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>
defended his record of sending <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> troops to foreign trouble spots
and forging international trade accords.
<p>
   ``We cannot withdraw into a fortressed <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">America</ENAMEX>'' on trade or
security matters, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said as he portrayed his foreign policy
course as one of ``rejecting the call to isolation'' but also
``refusing to be the world's policeman.''
<p>
   Hailing the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX>'s role in combating drug smuggling, he
told the class of about 230 graduating cadets, including 30 women,
in dress white uniforms that ``you will have the tools you need to
get the job done.''
<p>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
<p>
   As the president visited the military academy, his aides were
fending off a new attack on his role as commander-in-chief.
<p>
   In a statement released by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s lawyer
charged Republicans in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> were attempting to ``distort'' a
legal brief in which the president claimed that he should not have
to face a trial in a sexual harassment suit while he's in office.
<p>
   As part of the brief filed in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Supreme Court</ENAMEX>, the
presidential lawyer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert S. Bennett</ENAMEX> had used a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1940</TIMEX> law passed to
protect <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> servicemen from facing lawsuits while on duty.
<p>
   Chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House Veterans Affairs Committee</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Stump</ENAMEX>,
R-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ariz.</ENAMEX>, and Rep. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Dornan</ENAMEX>, R-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>, attacked that claim. ``You
are not a person in military service, nor have you ever been,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stump</ENAMEX> wrote in a letter to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bennett</ENAMEX> admitted that he included the immunity law in his brief,
``although we have not relied on it in this case.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McCurry</ENAMEX> brushed off the complaint: ``This goes to the heart of
the matter, which is that the president is president <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">24 hours a
day</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> has been sued by a former <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Arkansas</ENAMEX> employee, but the
case has been appealed to the high court as his lawyers attempt to
hold off the trial until <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> has left the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
