<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A0387 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=sci-z> BC-ROCKET-SCI-644&AMP;ADD-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-27</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1195 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-ROCKET-SCI-644&AMP;ADD-NYT
VERTICAL-LANDING ROCKET TESTS NEW TECHNOLOGIES
(<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Science Times</ENAMEX>)
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: contact <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karl Horwitz</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> for
details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: contact <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Paul Finch</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX> (Phone:
310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089).
(kd)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">WARREN E. LEARY</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The Delta Clipper, the experimental rocket that
takes off and lands on its tail, is flying again to test new
technology that may be applied to the next generation of satellite
launchers.
<p>
   The unmanned rocket, renamed from DC-X to DC-XA for Delta
Clipper Experimental Advanced, spent <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="year">almost a year</TIMEX> on the ground
being fitted with new components before resuming its airborne test
program on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 18</TIMEX> with a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">one-minute</TIMEX> flight at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">White Sands
Missile Range</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Mexico</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Crammed with new lightweight components, including a
liquid-oxygen fuel tank and a backup power system made in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>,
the vertical-landing rocket is testing technologies that could put
future cargoes into space at far less cost than <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``The DC-XA is essentially the DC-X rebuilt from the inside
out,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Dumbacher</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX> manager of the program. ``Externally, it looks the
same, but it's really a very different vehicle.''
<p>
   Inside the 42-foot-tall, four-engine rocket, a liquid-hydrogen
fuel tank made of aluminum has been replaced with one made of
graphite-epoxy composite material 1,100 pounds lighter. In
addition, composites have replaced heavier metal for a support
structure between fuel tanks and for a liquid-hydrogen fuel line
and valve.
<p>
   The Russian-made liquid-oxygen fuel tank, made of an
aluminum-lithium alloy, is one-third lighter than a conventional
aluminum tank. Another Russian component is a modified auxiliary
power unit, run by gases taken from the rocket's liquid propellants
instead of a separate fuel supply, that is being used to power the
craft's hydraulic system.
<p>
   Over all, the modifications reduced the bullet-shaped DC-XA's
dry weight to 20,000 pounds, a <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10 percent</NUMEX> drop, giving the vehicle
a fueled takeoff weight of 42,000 pounds, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dumbacher</ENAMEX> said in an
interview.
<p>
   Engineers are particularly interested in knowing how the strong,
plastic-like composite materials, which are increasingly being used
in aircraft and spacecraft because of their light weight, will hold
up after repeatedly being exposed to super-cold liquid fuels under
pressure, experts said.
<p>
   The Delta Clipper was developed by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ballistic Missile Defense
Organization</ENAMEX> for the ``Star Wars'' missile defense program and flew
eight times <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">from August 1993 to July 1995</TIMEX>. The one-of-a-kind rocket
was then transferred to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> to demonstrate technology for its X-33
program. This is a government-industry effort to build a larger
experimental rocket that would fly in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1999</TIMEX> and serve as a prototype
for an even bigger commercially owned launcher that could be the
nation's main cargo carrier in space <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="decade">within a decade</TIMEX>, eventually
replacing the space shuttle.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 13</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> received rocket design studies and business
plans for operating the craft from three aerospace groups vying to
be selected to build the X-33 rocket. The X-33 will be the working
model for a bigger, single-stage vehicle that could fly into space
and back without any disposable parts, like strap-on boosters that
drop off in flight. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> will decide in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July</TIMEX> which of the
proposals, which differ radically in design, to build to test the
advanced technology needed for an operational rocket.
<p>
   In addition to the vertical-takeoff and vertical-landing
proposal from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas Corp.</ENAMEX> and its partner, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing Co.</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell International Corp.</ENAMEX> and partners have
proposed making a winged craft that looks somewhat like a larger
version of the space shuttle, which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX> builds, but without
the auxiliary booster rockets and large external tank. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX>
design for the X-33 would rise vertically and land on a runway like
an airplane.
<p>
   The third proposed design, by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>, is for a
wingless, flat-bottomed rocket called a lifting body that would
take off vertically and land horizontally on a runway.
</TEXT>
