<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ASTRONAUTS RETURN TO <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">EARTH</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">STEFANIE ASIN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The shuttle Endeavour glided to a landing <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX> at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX>, ending a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10-day</TIMEX>
science extravaganza in space.
<p>
   The shuttle touched down on time at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">7:09 a.m. EDT</TIMEX> after the
threat of rainy weather at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cape Canaveral</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, diminished. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>
workers were ready at the shuttle's backup landing site at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Edwards
Air Force Base</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">California</ENAMEX> in case the weather prevented an <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">East
Coast</ENAMEX> touchdown.
<p>
   ``Welcome back, Endeavour. Congratulations on a highly
successful flight,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eileen Collins</ENAMEX>, spacecraft communicator
at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mission Control</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson Space Center</ENAMEX>, as the
shuttle came to a stop on the runway.
<p>
   The astronauts appeared tired at a news conference <TIMEX TYPE="TIME" MIN="six hours">six hours
after landing</TIMEX> but were enthusiastic about their flight. ``This was
a great mission. Just a fantastic mission for all of us,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Casper</ENAMEX>, the commander.
<p>
   The lone rookie on Endeavour, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andy Thomas</ENAMEX>, said he was having
trouble getting his ``<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> legs back'' and feeling a bit shaky in
gravity. But of the mission, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Thomas</ENAMEX> said: ``It's the stuff dreams
are made of.''
<p>
   The other crew members were pilot <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Curt Brown</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Bursch</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mario
Runco Jr.</ENAMEX> and Canadian <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marc Garneau</ENAMEX>. During the mission, the
astronauts deployed two research satellites and made a record four
rendezvous with the crafts. ``This was a pilot's dream flight,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Casper</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The flight's most spectacular experiment came on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="second day">the second day
of the mission</TIMEX>, when the astronauts deployed a satellite called
Spartan and inflated a Mylar antenna the size of a tennis court.
Spartan served as a platform for the antenna, which, supported by
three 92-foot-long struts, was inflated in a matter of minutes with
nitrogen gas. The balloon was jettisoned from Spartan and burned up
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a few days later</TIMEX>. Spartan was retrieved with
the shuttle's robot arm.
<p>
   The <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$14 million</NUMEX> experiment was designed to show that large,
lightweight structures can be inflated in space for less cost than
mechanical ones.
<p>
   Scientists were eager to get Spartan back on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>, because it
holds data from the experiment. The antenna had unexpectedly
tumbled end over end, making it difficult to see if its parabolic
dish had inflated. A second satellite, called STU, was chased down
three times after deployment for observations. The experiment
proved that satellites can stabilize by using their mass and
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s magnetic field. Conventional satellites rely on expensive
thruster jets.
<p>
   The STU is expected to burn up in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX>.
<p>
   When the astronauts weren't tracking satellites, they focused on
dozens of science experiments aboard the shuttle. Fourteen
ultrapure semiconductor crystals were grown in a hot furnace,
giving researchers good seed material for making pure semiconductor
materials on the ground. Thousands of fertilized sea urchin eggs,
starfish and blue clams returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> with the astronauts.
Researchers hope to learn about embryonic development and feeding
patterns from the tiny animals in the shuttle aquarium.
<p>
   Endeavour will be ferried to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Palmdale</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>, for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">eight months</TIMEX>
of refurbishing and modification, so it can carry hardware for the
planned international space station. It is not expected to fly
again until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December 1997</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
