<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A6174 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttc-z> BC-OBIT-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LEARY</ENAMEX>-LADN </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-31</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0807 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-OBIT-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LEARY</ENAMEX>-LADN
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">TIMOTHY LEARY</ENAMEX> DIES OF CANCER AT 75
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">STEVEN J. GORMAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Los Angeles Daily News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LOS ANGELES</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Timothy Leary</ENAMEX>, the former <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ivy League</ENAMEX> professor and
LSD guru who dabbled heavily in cyberspace as an elder statesman of
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">'60s</TIMEX> counterculture, died at his home after an <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">18-month</TIMEX> bout
with cancer. He was 75.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>'s death <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Friday</TIMEX>, announced on his Internet home
page and videotaped by friends and family assembled at his bedside,
will not end the ex-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Harvard</ENAMEX> psychologist's lifelong pursuit of the
ultimate cosmic experience.
<p>
   Loved ones have arranged to have a quarter-ounce of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>'s
cremated remains tucked into a satellite and blasted into orbit by
a Pegasus rocket <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this fall</TIMEX> as part of the world's first burial in
space.
<p>
   If all goes as planned, his ashes will eventually burn up in the
atmosphere with the satellite when it falls back to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>, a
fitting final act of hyperbole for the firebrand who shocked the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1960s</TIMEX> establishment by advocating the use of mind-altering drugs
and exhorting a generation of young people to ``turn on, tune in
and drop out.''
<p>
   ``That's his style. He wanted to go out with a bang,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>'s stepson, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Leary</ENAMEX>, 22, outside the hilltop home he
shared with his father. ``He really always thought space was the
final frontier.''
<p>
   ``I think he'd like to be remembered as a philosopher, and as a
champion of the human mind and the human spirit,'' his stepson
added. ``He was all about the mind.''
<p>
   He said part of his stepfather's final mission was to use his
terminal illness to tear down the taboos surrounding death.
<p>
   ``He really made sure that we knew that the mystery of death is
as beautiful as the mystery of life,'' the younger <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>, who married five times and also leaves a son named <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jack</ENAMEX>,
was diagnosed with prostate cancer in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January 1995</TIMEX> and in recent
months had mused about the possibility of committing a public
suicide over the Internet.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Leary</ENAMEX> said his father and friends decided
``communally'' not to go through with his idea of because of legal
complications and because ``it would have been very difficult for
us.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>'s homepage on the World Wide Web said in a brief
announcement of his death: ``Just after <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">midnight</TIMEX>, in his favorite
bed among loving friends, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Timothy Leary</ENAMEX> peacefully passed on. His
last words were `why not?' and `yeah.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Leary</ENAMEX> said the final word his father actually uttered
was, ``beautiful.''
<p>
   ``I told him I loved him and he smiled,'' his son recalled. ``He
just slipped away very peacefully.''
<p>
   He said a hospice nurse at his bedside pronounced <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX> dead at
about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">12:45 a.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   ``I had my finger on the pulse of his neck and felt it
disappearing,'' said longtime friend <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Carol Rosin</ENAMEX>, 52, another one
of about a dozen close companions and family members with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>
when he died.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Winona Ryder</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>'s goddaughter, issued a statement through
her publicist.
<p>
   ``One of the gazillion ... things I learned from <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tim</ENAMEX> in my <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">24
years</TIMEX> of knowing him, and particularly during <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="last few months">these last few
months</TIMEX>, is how noble, beautiful and funny a person can be when
faced with death. It made me less afraid. I was glad to be there
with him to say goodbye.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Leary</ENAMEX> said his father's final days, including his death,
were chronicled on videotape. He said no decision had been made
about what to do with the footage, but ``there will probably be a
tie-in with the Internet site.''
<p>
   ``It was his dream to keep his Internet site alive,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary
Leary</ENAMEX> said. ``That's really the ultimate form of immortality for
him.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Leary</ENAMEX> said a wake will be held for close friends and
family, but the only other ceremony planned is the lofting of a
portion of his stepfather's cremated remains into orbit.
<p>
   That mission will be carried out by a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two-year</TIMEX>-old <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>-based
company called the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Celestis Inc.</ENAMEX>, which offers to orbit the ashes
of the dearly departed at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4,800</NUMEX> a trip under contract with the
private space launch contractor, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Orbital Sciences Corp.</ENAMEX>, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dulles</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Va.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   For the company's first such trip in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX>, a satellite
bearing the ashes of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>, the late ``Star Trek'' creator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gene
Rodenberry</ENAMEX> and about two dozen others will be lifted into space by
a Pegasus rocket launched from a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> L-1011 aircraft at high
altitude, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Celestis</ENAMEX> vice president <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gary Gartner</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Leary</ENAMEX> said he and a group of about 20 others who were in
the house <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this week</TIMEX> contacted <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leary</ENAMEX>'s more distant friends and
family as it became clear <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> that the end was near.
<p>
   Among those who called to say a final farewell were Beat
Generation writer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Borroughs</ENAMEX>, and author <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ken Kesey</ENAMEX>, best
known for his novel ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary
Leary</ENAMEX> said.
</TEXT>
