<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FRANCE</ENAMEX>-ROCKET-LAUNCH-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANESPACE</ENAMEX> PLANS TO LAUNCH FIRST <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANE</ENAMEX> 5 ROCKET <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">TOMORROW</TIMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrea Rothman</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 3</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- European satellite launch group
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> is scheduled <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">tomorrow</TIMEX> to send up its first <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5
rocket, one capable of sending into orbit loads <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">30 percent</NUMEX> heavier
than the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 launch, scheduled for <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">noon, Paris time,</TIMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">French
Guyana</ENAMEX> near the equator, will send up four <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX>
Cluster satellites to study interactions between the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">sun</ENAMEX> and the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The mission had originally been scheduled for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last November</TIMEX> but
has been put off numerous times.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, a group of 53 European aerospace and defense
companies that builds rockets to launch telecommunications and
scientific satellites, has promised that launch costs will be <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10
percent</NUMEX> lower than with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4.
<p>
   With a claim on <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">50 percent</NUMEX> of the world's satellite launching
business, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> has said it is counting on the new rocket to
maintain its position in the industry.
<p>
   The group was the first to launch commercial payloads regularly.
Competition has grown in recent years, however, as the explosion of
telecommunications services has multiplied the need for launches.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX> is <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX>'s biggest rival. The Russians
and Chinese also have started becoming significant competitors.
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">India</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX> have launching facilities, but send up smaller
payloads than those put into geostationary orbit by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> is predicting a big upturn in the demand for
launchers. Up to 35 satellites a year could be sent into orbit
within the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next 10 to 15 years</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> estimates. Those
figures, published <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this year</TIMEX>, represent an increase from
the company's old estimate of about 25 launches a year.
<p>
   Since its inception, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> has signed 159 launch contracts
and successfully placed into orbit 112 large satellites for
commercial, international and government organizations, and 26
auxiliary payloads for experimental purposes.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> now has a backlog of 44 satellites on order to be
launched.
</TEXT>
