<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANE</ENAMEX>-EXPLODE-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-04</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANE</ENAMEX>-EXPLODE-NYT
EUROPEAN ROCKET BLOWN UP ON MAIDEN FLIGHT
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CRAIG R. WHITNEY</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">PARIS</ENAMEX>  &MD;  A huge new rocket that had been intended to put <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>
further ahead of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> in the world commercial
satellite-launching market had to be blown up <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">40 seconds</TIMEX>
into its maiden flight, after it veered from its trajectory.
<p>
   Stunned technicians and invited guests at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space
Agency</ENAMEX>'s launch center at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kourou</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">French Guiana</ENAMEX>, watched pieces of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 rocket rain down in flames from 13,120 feet, where the
self-destruct mechanism exploded it on a command from the ground.
<p>
   ``Of course it's a disappointment, but we have to bounce back,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Claude Bigot</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, the commercial arm of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX>, which had spent <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">10 years</TIMEX> and <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$7 billion</NUMEX>
to develop the new launcher. No one was hurt, according to the
agency, but four uninsured science satellites the rocket was to
carry into space were lost.
<p>
   The two-stage rocket, with two solid-fuel boosters strapped to
its side much like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s space shuttle, was designed to be the
successor to the highly successful <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4, which launched 12 out
of the 26 nonmilitary satellites that various countries sent into
orbit <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>, its space program long hampered by the
Challenger space shuttle disaster in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1986</TIMEX>, launched nine commercial
satellites <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>, according to European figures.
<p>
   Whether <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>'s accident would represent a so serious a
setback for the European space program was not clear.
<p>
   But French television commentators watching the launch live on
television in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> looked as dejected as their American
counterparts did almost <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">40 years ago</TIMEX>, when Soviet rockets were
sending Sputniks into space while American ones repeatedly blew up
on the launch pad.
<p>
   For <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX>, which views the European program with a proprietary
air, the failure <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> was an embarrassing setback. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>
had been so confident of success that it forecast the new rocket's
expected launch reliability at <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">98.5 percent</NUMEX> and offered a free
repeat launch to customers in the unlikely event of failure.
<p>
   Through its smaller <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4 single-stage rockets, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>,
a partnership of 40 European aerospace companies led by
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" MIN="Aerospatiale">Aerospatiale of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX></ENAMEX> and the French space agency, now controls
about <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">60 percent</NUMEX> of the world's commercial launch market and takes
in about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 billion</NUMEX> a year.
<p>
   The Atlas rocket produced by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX> is the main
American commercial launcher, and together with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell
Douglas</ENAMEX> medium-sized Delta, had less than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">30 percent</NUMEX> of advance
orders <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>. The Russian <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Proton</ENAMEX> and the Chinese Long March
rockets have the rest.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bigot</ENAMEX>, the president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, said that an investigation
into what went wrong would be completed by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-July</TIMEX>. Originally,
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European space agency</ENAMEX> planned two <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 launches <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>,
three in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1997</TIMEX>, four in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1998</TIMEX> and five or six in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1999</TIMEX>. Fourteen of
the new launchers are on order.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis Avanzi</ENAMEX>, general manager of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, told the
newspaper Le Monde on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that the consortium planned to keep
using the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4 until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1999</TIMEX> and then carry out seven or eight
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 launches a year after the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">turn of the century</TIMEX>, lofting
several satellites at a time. The American Atlas rocket, by
contrast, usually can carry only one.
<p>
   He said that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 was capable of putting 7.6 tons into
the orbit used by telecommunications satellites with a single-phase
launch and 6.58 tons, employing a two-phase launch. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">After 2003</TIMEX>, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 would be able to lift 8.16 tons into orbit.
<p>
   ``We are the only ones on the market with these dimensions,'' he
said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> calculated the commercial market at 200 to 240
satellites over <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the next eight years</TIMEX>, <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">80 percent</NUMEX> of them for
telecommunications.
<p>
   French <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Space and Telecommunications</ENAMEX> Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francois Fillon</ENAMEX>,
who watched the launch attempt from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Louvre</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>, said: ``It
was an experimental flight. We knew the risks we were running. We
will do all we can to insure that the great European space
adventure remains a success.''
<p>
   Officials of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> said the 87th satellite launch of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4 would take place <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="eight days">in eight days</TIMEX>, the first of eight more
scheduled <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
