<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITES-UPDA </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-05</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0824 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITES-UPDATE1-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>'S <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GREAT WALL</ENAMEX> SAYS <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> DELAYING ROCKET LAUNCH (UPDATE1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Hannam</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Updates with additional details and background in paragraph six
and after the sub-headline ``Good Results'' )
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 5</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall Industry Corp.</ENAMEX>
officials say <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s next satellite launch is being held up by the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> is delaying the release of an international review
examining the reasons for a rocket failure in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sun
Shaolin</ENAMEX>, director of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s information office.
<p>
   ``The review was to have been released on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 10</TIMEX> so that
insurers could get more information (about the failed launch),''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sun</ENAMEX> said. ``However, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government suddenly said it wanted to
examine the report before it is released.''
<p>
   Insurers have said they will not underwrite <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s next launch
until they receive a report on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>'s explosion of a Long March
3B rocket.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Embassy</ENAMEX> officials contacted said they were not aware of the
delay.
<p>
   An official with leading reinsurer <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson and Higgens</ENAMEX> in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> said he had ``heard something like that,'' regarding the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government blocking the report's release.
<p>
   One embassy official said the delay might be caused by questions
of technology transfer.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government lays down strict rules on the transfer of
satellite and aerospace technology to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Jefferies</ENAMEX>
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>-based Asia-Pacific Space Report.
<p>
   Since the review is examining the rocket launch, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> may
be concerned that an international study could contain information
aiding <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s launch industry, in the process helping the
country's improve its missile launch reliability.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>, a Chinese-made Long March 3B rocket carrying an
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> satellite exploded seconds after lift-off from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX>
rocket base in southwest <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>. Early studies indicated a faulty
guidance system caused the rocket failure.
<p>
   The review committee set up in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX> to boost the confidence of
the insurance community is headed by Dr <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wah L. Lim</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-based
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX>'s space systems division.
<p>
   The next proposed launch by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> is a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>-built satellite
for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX> on a Long March 3 rocket, a
smaller version of the failed Long March 3B.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX>'s shareholders include <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Singapore Telecom</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Thailand</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Charoen Pokhpand Group</ENAMEX> and commercial arms of the
Chinese army, space and telecommunications authorities.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX> is very anxious to resume launching,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sun</ENAMEX>.
``The Apstar-1A is already in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX>. Without the release of the
report, insurers are unwilling to go ahead with the launch.''
<p>
   Although <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX> is yet to receive the international
committee's findings, the company is confident that the review
backs their own findings.
<p>
   ``We are sure of the cause of the failure,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sun</ENAMEX> said. ``The
report of the independent review committee will give a more
detailed conclusion.''
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s parent, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Aerospace Corp.</ENAMEX> said
initial results of the investigation into the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> failure
published by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall</ENAMEX> indicated a faulty gyroscope system,
called the Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU).
<p>
   The unit sent the wrong signals to the rocket's movable exhaust
nozzles, changing their angles and tilting the rocket's trajectory.
<p>
   The independent review confirmed that the problem is isolated to
the Long March 3B rocket and is not connected to the Long March 3
version set to carry the Apstar-1A satellite into space, an
industry analyst said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> is anxious to resume its satellite launches. The Apstar-1A
was originally to have been launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March</TIMEX>, with as many as four
more satellites to be launched <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The other launches include the launch of a Chinese-made
DongFangHong3 satellite on a Long March 3A, originally set for
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX> or <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May</TIMEX> but now postponed.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July</TIMEX>, a Long March 3 rocket was scheduled to carry a
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ChinaSat</ENAMEX>-7 communications satellite for a Chinese controlled
company. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> will build the satellite.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July</TIMEX> or <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">August</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> had planned to launch a recoverable spy
satellite aboard a Long March 2-C rocket from its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jiuquan</ENAMEX> launch
base in northern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Gansu</ENAMEX> province.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Later in the year</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> hopes to win a bid to launch the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mabuhay</ENAMEX> communications satellite for a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manila</ENAMEX>-based consortium led
by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co.</ENAMEX> The satellite is to be
supplied by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX>, the company which made the
satellite destroyed on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 15</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sun</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX>'s failure of the European-backed
Ariane 5 rocket on its maiden flight would have little effect on
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s satellite program.
<p>
   ``In any scientific experiment, failures are always possible,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sun</ENAMEX> said. ``We don't think the failure will promote or negatively
affect the business of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>.''
</TEXT>
