<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITE-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX> GETS INSURER APPROVAL FOR <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">JULY</TIMEX> SATELLITE LAUNCH (UPDATE2)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Adds comment from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX>, details on insurance,
upcoming program launches.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 10</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> will resume its commercial
space program in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July</TIMEX> after international insurers agreed to
underwrite the next launch, said a spokesman for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s rocket
launcher, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall Industry Corp.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s satellite program has been held up since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> when a
Long March 3B rocket carrying an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> satellite exploded
seconds after take-off from southwest <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX> space base.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Munich Re</ENAMEX>, the world's biggest reinsurer, will lead the
international group of companies backing the launch of the
Apstar-1A satellite owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT</ENAMEX>'s shareholders
include <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Singapore Telecom</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Thailand</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Charoen Pokhpand Group</ENAMEX> and
commercial arms of the Chinese army, space and telecommunications
authorities.
<p>
   The launch ``was insured <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last Saturday</TIMEX> and is likely to be
launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early July</TIMEX>,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX> spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ma Qimin</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Freeman Zhang</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>-based official with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Johnson and
Higgens</ENAMEX>, an international reinsurance company, said ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Munich Re</ENAMEX> is
the leading reinsurer.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Munich Re</ENAMEX> is formally known as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Muenchener
Rueckversicherungs-Gesellschaft</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The satellite is made by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" MIN="Hughes Space and Communications">Hughes Space and Communications
division</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX> It's already been delivered to the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX> launch site. It will go up on a Long March 3 rocket.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ma</ENAMEX> said insurers backed the launch before receiving
a full report of an international committee set up to review
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s own analysis of the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> failure.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> charges the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> government is holding up the report's
release. The review committee, set up in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX> to boost the
confidence of the insurance community, was headed by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wah L. Lim</ENAMEX> of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX>'s space systems division.
<p>
   ``You can read this to mean that insurance companies support the
conclusions of our investigations,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ma</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s parent, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Aerospace Corp.</ENAMEX> said in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX> the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> failure was caused by a faulty gyroscope system, called
the Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU).
<p>
   The unit sent the wrong signals to the rocket's movable exhaust
nozzles, changing their angles and tilting the rocket's trajectory.
<p>
   ``We tried to explain to insurers that the Long March 3B is
different from the Long March 3,'' said Professor <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bao Miaoqin</ENAMEX>, a
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>-based engineer with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX> ``It looks like they
have accepted the arguments.'' The Long March 3 has a launch
capacity of about 1450 kilograms, compared to the 4800 kilogram
capacity of the Long March 3B
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bao</ENAMEX> said the company will pay the premium rate insurers offered
before the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> explosion. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bao</ENAMEX> declined to disclose the premium
rate. In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Shanghai</ENAMEX>-based state-owned <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Pacific
Insurance Co.</ENAMEX> agreed to insure the Apstar-1A satellite for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">2.3
billion yuan</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$280 million</NUMEX>).
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ma</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> will reschedule the rest of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
year</TIMEX>'s launches after the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT</ENAMEX> launch.
<p>
   Other launches planned for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">later this year</TIMEX> include the
DongFangHong3 satellite on a Long March 3A.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> has also earmarked a Long March 3 rocket to carry a
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ChinaSat</ENAMEX>-7 communications satellite for a Chinese controlled
company. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> will build the satellite.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Radio, Film and Television Ministry</ENAMEX> is particularly
anxious for a speedy launch of the ChinaSat7, analysts said. Much
of the nation's television signals are being beamed from ChinaSat5,
an aging satellite nearing the end of its usable life.
<p>
   The shortest span between launches in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> is about <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">50 days</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> also plans to launch a recoverable spy satellite aboard a
Long March 2-C rocket from its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jiuquan</ENAMEX> launch base in northern
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Gansu</ENAMEX> province.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Later in the year</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> hopes to win a bid to launch the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mabuhay</ENAMEX> communications satellite for a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manila</ENAMEX>-based consortium led
by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co.</ENAMEX>
-- <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Hannam</ENAMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> bureau (8610) 6532-4492 through the
