<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MICROSOFT</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NINTENDO</ENAMEX>-IN </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-26</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0543 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MICROSOFT</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NINTENDO</ENAMEX>-INTERNET-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NINTENDO</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MICROSOFT</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NOMURA</ENAMEX> ANNOUNCE INTERNET TIE-UP (UPDATE6)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Malcolm Foster</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Phred Dvorak</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Rewriting throughout, adding comments from press conference,
details about system.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tokyo</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 26</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo Co.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nomura Research
Institute Ltd.</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft Corp.</ENAMEX> will team up to offer
entertainment, sports, shopping and other information services
through home personal computers in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The companies will deliver the information via satellite and
through <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX>'s on-line computer service, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX>
Network, which also provides access to the global computer network
known as the Internet.
<p>
   The three companies will invest a total of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">1 billion yen</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$9.1
million</NUMEX>) in the venture, which will be formed by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of this
year</TIMEX> and begin offering services by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">middle of next year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX> will put up <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX> of the initial investment, while
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nomura</ENAMEX> will put up <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">30 percent</NUMEX> each.
<p>
   The service, which will be limited to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>, will be offered to
subscribing members. Users will install a satellite modem to read
data into a personal computer utilizing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX>'s Windows
operating system.
<p>
   ``This venture draws on the strengths of all three companies,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Gates</ENAMEX>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX> said
at a press conference.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX> will develop the satellite modem and the software for
the service. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX> will manage membership and provide modem
support with Windows. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nomura</ENAMEX>, the research arm of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nomura Securities
Co.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s largest brokerage, will oversee the entire system.
<p>
   Subscription rates are estimated to be about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">1,000 yen</NUMEX> a month,
or about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$9.17</NUMEX>, company officials said.
<p>
   ``We want to create something totally new,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hiroshi
Yamauchi</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Once undisputed king of video game makers, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX> is facing
increasingly stiff competition from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sony Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sega Enterprises
Ltd.</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX>'s sales fell <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">14.8 percent</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>, while <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sega</ENAMEX>'s
rose <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">3.9 percent</NUMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">This past Sunday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX> released its newest game machine, a
64-bit player the company has billed as state-of-the-art. That move
was meant to leapfrog <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sony</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sega</ENAMEX>, which released 32-bit game
machines that were faster and more powerful that what <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX> was
offering.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sega Enterprises Ltd.</ENAMEX> has said it will sell products allowing
users of its Saturn video game player to dial into the Internet
network, in what could be the first step towards worldwide
interactive video games.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sega</ENAMEX> sells a modem and software that will allow Saturn users to
dial into the computer network from their home television sets
without the need to buy a personal computer.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sega</ENAMEX> is already making some of its games available for computer
users to take advantage of a growing demand for computers, and has
started tests of a cable television game channel that allows users
to dial up games they want from their television.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nintendo</ENAMEX> share rose as much as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">150 yen</NUMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">8250</NUMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft</ENAMEX> shares
fell 2 1/8 in trading <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX>, to 122. Shares of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nomura
Securities Co.</ENAMEX>, the parent company of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nomura Research</ENAMEX>, rose as much
as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">10 yen</NUMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">2,170</NUMEX>.
</TEXT>
