<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX> PLANS SATELLITE LAUNCH <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">WEDNESDAY</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">EVENING</TIMEX> (UPDATE1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Updates to mention increasing competition from Russian and
European rockets in paragraph two. Rewrites throughout.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 2</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> plans to send a satellite
into orbit <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, reigniting its commercial-space program
nearly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">five months</TIMEX> after its last launch ended in an explosion
shortly after take-off.
<p>
   The launch comes at a crucial time for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s space program.
After two spectacular failures the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past two years</TIMEX>, it's now facing
increased competition from Russian and European rockets.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">tomorrow</TIMEX>'s launch, a Long March 3 rocket will carry an
Apstar-1A satellite for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX>, whose shareholders
include <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Singapore Telecom</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Thailand</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Charoen Pokphand Group</ENAMEX> and
commercial arms of the Chinese army, space and telecommunications
authorities.
<p>
   The satellite was built was <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Space and Communications Co.</ENAMEX>,
a division of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Co.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   ``The rocket is scheduled to blast off at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">6:46 p.m.</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">tomorrow</TIMEX>,
weather permitting,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ma Qimin</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for launch-service
operator <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall Industry Corp.</ENAMEX> ``The launch will not be
televised.''
<p>
   Officials at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>
confirmed the launch plans.
<p>
   The launch got the go-ahead from international insurers <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
month</TIMEX> after they reviewed an analysis of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> launch
failure.
<p>
   Officials from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT</ENAMEX> are now at the launch site in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX>, in the southwestern Chinese province of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sichuan</ENAMEX>.
-- <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Hannam</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> (8610) 6532-4492 through the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>
newsroom jdh
