<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1757 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-ROCKET-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-02</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-ROCKET-HNS
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LOCKHEED MARTIN</ENAMEX> TO DEVELOP NEW SPACECRAFT FOR <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" MIN="Lockheed Martin">Lockheed Martin <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Skunk Works</ENAMEX></ENAMEX> will lead a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 billion</NUMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>-financed effort to develop a revolutionary, reusable rocket to
replace the space shuttle in the fight to regain <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> pre-eminence
in the global commercial launch market.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Palmdale</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>-based company, which earned belated
recognition for its clandestine Cold War development of
high-altitude spy planes, snared the project from competitors
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas Aerospace</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell International</ENAMEX>, both also
based in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">California</ENAMEX>. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Skunk Works</ENAMEX> division of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>
takes its name from the ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Li'l Abner</ENAMEX>'' comic strip.
<p>
   ``This is the craft that can carry <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">America</ENAMEX>'s dreams aloft and
launch our nation into <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a sparkling new century</TIMEX>,'' Vice President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Al
Gore</ENAMEX> told the audience gathered for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>'s announcement at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jet Propulsion Laboratory</ENAMEX> in suburban <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Under terms of the agreement with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX> will design and fabricate a
single test craft  &MD;  called the X-33 by the space agency and
VentureStar by its design team. Shaped like a fat arrowhead, the
67-foot-tall, 68-foot-wide spacecraft will undergo a series of
increasingly ambitious suborbital test flights in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1999</TIMEX>, most likely
launching from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Edwards Air Force Base</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Marshall Space Flight Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Huntsville</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ala.</ENAMEX>, will
manage the project for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The space agency's commitment of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 billion</NUMEX> to the project will
be supplemented by <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$220 million</NUMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Once flight test evaluations of the X-33 are complete, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White
House</ENAMEX>-level policy decision will be made on whether to proceed
toward the development of a much larger spacecraft, 125 feet tall.
<p>
   The single-stage, reusable launch vehicle will cost an estimated
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5 billion to $10 billion</NUMEX>.
<p>
   As envisioned, the vehicle's development cost would be borne
largely by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>. The spacecraft would be used to launch
government cargo to the planned <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-led international space
station, as well as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of Defense</ENAMEX> cargo and privately owned
communications and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>-observing satellites.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> Administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Goldin</ENAMEX> said his agency expects to respond
to declining budgets by contracting for its space flights rather
than operating its own fleet of space shuttles, which now cost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$3.2
billion</NUMEX> annually.
<p>
   ``This is <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">an historic day</TIMEX> for the space program,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Goldin</ENAMEX> said.
``Now, we fly dozens of astronauts a year. This vehicle should
allow hundreds of you to fly, and vehicles that come behind should
allow thousands to fly.''
<p>
   The space shuttle, designed a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">quarter century ago</TIMEX>, represents
the most recent <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> effort to develop a new rocket. The country's
fleet of expendable Atlas and Delta rockets trace their lineage to
early ballistic missiles.
<p>
   The combination of aging technologies and a national policy that
until the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1986</TIMEX> Challenger disaster restricted all satellite
launches to the shuttle has allowed French <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> and, more
recently, Russian rockets to win more than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">60 percent</NUMEX> of the
lucrative global commercial launch market.
<p>
   The goal of the new vessel is to lower the cost of launching
cargo to orbit from about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$10,000</NUMEX> a pound aboard the shuttle to
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1,000</NUMEX> or less through the use of tougher, lighter materials in the
airframe, propellant tanks and outer surfaces of the spacecraft.
None of the vehicle's components would fall away during ascent as
do the solid rocket boosters and external fuel tank of the current
shuttle.
<p>
   The new spacecraft would be designed for airliner-like ground
operations, so back-to-back flights could occur days instead of
several months apart, as they do with the shuttle. A ground team of
a few dozen people could prepare, launch and fly the new rocket
instead of the hundreds required by the shuttle.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>'s spacecraft will launch vertically and land
horizontally on a runway. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX>'s proposal, which resembled a
winged shuttle, did the same.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX>' proposal resembled the vertical take-off and
landing craft that has undergone a series of subsonic, low-altitude
tests at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">White Sands Missile Range</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Mexico</ENAMEX> since
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
