<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">UK</ENAMEX>-MEDIA-BILL-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-03</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">UK</ENAMEX>-MEDIA-BILL-BLOOM
NEW <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> MEDIA LAW TO BE APPROVED BY <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">AUGUST</TIMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dawn Hayes</ENAMEX> through the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX> newsroom 
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 3</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> government expects to
approve a new media law by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">August</TIMEX>, which will loosen some media
cross-ownership rules, after opposition to continued ownership
rules and access to all for digital TV was defeated <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">last night</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Once approved, the new law is likely to prompt takeovers and
mergers of commercial TV companies <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this fall</TIMEX>, analysts said.
<p>
   Moves to loosen cross-ownership rules further have created
volatility in the shares of small commercial TV companies,
including <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Yorkshire Tyne-Tees Holdings Plc</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">HTV Group Plc</ENAMEX>, as
speculation grows that they will become takeover targets once the
bill is approved.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Yorkshire Tyne-Tees</ENAMEX>' shares fell as much as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">3 pence</NUMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">1235p</NUMEX>
after closing up <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">7 percent</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX> and rising <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">8 percent</NUMEX> in the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">HTV</ENAMEX>'s shares rose as much as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">7 pence</NUMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">336p</NUMEX> after
rising <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">3 percent</NUMEX> in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Scottish Television</ENAMEX>'s shares
were unchanged after falling <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2 percent</NUMEX> in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX> and <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">6
percent</NUMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the last two weeks</TIMEX>. The new rules will not come into
effect until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September</TIMEX>, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Stevenson</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of National Heritage</ENAMEX>. He said the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> government
succeeded <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">last night</TIMEX> in quashing attempts to prevent certain
companies, including <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp</ENAMEX>, which owns <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40
percent</NUMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc</ENAMEX>, from winning
licenses for digital TV.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX> has the only satellite TV license in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> at present.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Digital TV</ENAMEX> is expected to start as soon as <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Under consideration for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the past 18 months</TIMEX>, the broadcasting
bill shifts regulation from the number of media franchises a
company may hold to a <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">15 percent</NUMEX> total audience share.
<p>
   A key change is that commercial TV companies, called Channel 3,
may now own as many franchises as they like provided they don't
cross the <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">15 percent</NUMEX> total audience share in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> At the
moment, they are permitted to own up to two TV franchises.
<p>
   In anticipation of its approval, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MAI Group Plc</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United News &AMP;
Media Plc</ENAMEX> have already merged to form a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">3.3 billion pound</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5
billion</NUMEX>) company. To stay within existing rules, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United News</ENAMEX> put
some of its newspaper assets into a separate company.
<p>
   However, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News International</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British
Telecommunications Plc</ENAMEX>, which dwarf most <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> media companies,
could each have a share in operating digital television multiplexer
licenses and a share in the transmission of digital channels.
<p>
   Analysts said the new rules risk being overtaken by the flood of
rights agreements signed by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> and a handful of other
companies, to buy up sports and movie programs around the world,
including in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   They recalled the fate of rules the government put in place in
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1980s</TIMEX> for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Satellite Broadcasting</ENAMEX> to operate a British
satellite TV service. When <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sky Broadcasting</ENAMEX> launched a
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX> service from a satellite over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Luxembourg</ENAMEX>, the rules became
superfluous. The result was that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sky</ENAMEX> merged with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BSkyB</ENAMEX> to form
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc</ENAMEX>, which now has a monopoly on
satellite TV in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   At present, companies' control of the market is measured by the
number of franchises they hold.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Granada Group Plc</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX> it would like to buy
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Yorkshire-Tyne</ENAMEX> because it is located next to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Granada</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manchester</ENAMEX>
region franchise. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Granada</ENAMEX> now owns <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">23 percent</NUMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Yorkshire
Tyne-Tees</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Independent Television Commission</ENAMEX>, the industry regulator,
said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Granada</ENAMEX> has a <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">7.2 percent</NUMEX> share of total TV audience in the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX>, so it could now buy <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Yorkshire-Tyne</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   In addition to being able to own more than two independent TV
franchises, Channel 3 companies may now own cable TV services in
the areas they cover.
<p>
   Local newspapers with <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">more than 20 percent and less than 50
percent</NUMEX> of local circulation can buy up to <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">50 percent</NUMEX> of the local
radio audience.
</TEXT>
