<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A2200 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-03</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>'S <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CANADA</ENAMEX> SATELLITE REQUEST RAISES ADMINISTRATION CONCERNS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Liza McDonald</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 3</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- The <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> administration is
urging regulators to hold off approval of a plan by
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> affiliate and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest Ventures LLC</ENAMEX> to use
Canadian satellites to beam cable TV shows to American viewers.
<p>
   The unusual recommendation, in a letter from four executive
branch agencies to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Communications Commission</ENAMEX>, stems in
part from concerns that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> continues to restrict <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> satellite
services and television programming.
<p>
   The administration's recommendation, though not binding on the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> as an independent agency, represents ``the death knell'' for
the venture, said a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> communications lawyer who until
recently headed the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> bureau that is reviewing the application.
<p>
   The letter from the four agencies -- the departments of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> Trade Representative's office
--``is something that happens only rarely'' in pending applications
before the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>'s international bureau, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott Blake Harris</ENAMEX>, who
headed the bureau until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-May</TIMEX>.
<p>
   It means ``this administration is serious about getting equal
opportunities for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> companies. The executive branch is sending a
very clear signal,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Harris</ENAMEX>, who is now a partner with the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> law firm of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher LLP</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   In the letter, the four executive branch departments urge the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> to wait until they know under what terms the Canadian
government authorizes the arrangement.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> is still reviewing the application.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Harris</ENAMEX>, free now to discuss <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> business, said it is
``inconceivable'' that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> would grant the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest</ENAMEX> request
since equal opportunities do not exist for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> companies wishing
to beam to Canadian audiences.
<p>
   The executive branch letter ``clinches it,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Harris</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>'s international bureau now will ``simply deny'' the
application, he predicted.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> is currently set to make a decision on the application
by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 15</TIMEX>. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">That date</TIMEX> was requested by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest</ENAMEX> because it
gives them time to make their launch date if the agency approves
their request. ``I believe I'll be able to tell them by then,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>
international bureau chief <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Don Gips</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gips</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX>
will consider the executive agencies' letter but is restricted from
commenting substantively on the matter.
<p>
   The executive branch concerns come as the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> considers whether
to let <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Western Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> affiliate, and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest</ENAMEX> use two satellites owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ottawa</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TeleSat Canada</ENAMEX> to
beam subscription video services into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>-led <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar
Partners</ENAMEX> has also informally agreed to join the venture.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> shares were up 1/8 at 18 at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">midday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> is the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>'s biggest cable TV company, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest</ENAMEX> is
controlled by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jared E. Abbruzzese</ENAMEX>, the chairman of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CAI Wireless
Systems</ENAMEX>, a wireless cable company in which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bell Atlantic Corp.</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nynex</ENAMEX> have an option to buy a stake. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Primestar</ENAMEX>'s partners include
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Time Warner Inc.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox Communications Inc.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Comcast Corp.</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Continental Cablevision</ENAMEX>, among others.
<p>
   In their letter, the executive branch agencies expressed concern
over Canadian restrictions on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> companies, as well as
international agreement obligations that would require modification
if the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest</ENAMEX> application were approved.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> discriminates against <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> and other foreign
programmers and service providers in a number of ways,'' the letter
said, including ``extensive content restrictions'' on TV and cable
broadcasting, the letter said. Also, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> restricts <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
satellite, telephone and broadcasting services, the agencies said.
<p>
   International agreements between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> would need
to be modified before a Canadian satellite could beam TV shows into
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>, the agencies said. Also, the agencies said there is
``some concern'' that ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX>, given its market position, may have an
incentive to engage in anti-competitive behavior in parts of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> market.''
<p>
   The letter, dated <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 1</TIMEX>, was signed by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vonya McCann</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
coordinator for international communications and information policy
at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Department</ENAMEX>; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeffrey Lang</ENAMEX>, deputy <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> trade
representative; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Turetsky</ENAMEX>, deputy assistant attorney general
in the antitrust division at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice Department</ENAMEX>; and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Larry
Irving</ENAMEX>, assistant secretary for communications and information at
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce Department</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI Communications Corp.</ENAMEX> have
also asked the agency to block the companies' request. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX>
and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MCI</ENAMEX> together paid <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$682 million</NUMEX> for a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> direct broadcast
satellite license. Their joint venture, called <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Sky
Broadcasting</ENAMEX>, argued to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FCC</ENAMEX> that it would be unfair for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TCI</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TelQuest</ENAMEX> to circumvent the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> auction and licensing process by
going to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> for the needed satellite slot.
<p>
   Also, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Sky</ENAMEX> said it would be unfair to give a Canadian
satellite free access to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> customers unless reciprocal
opportunities existed for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> satellites beaming to Canadian
customers -- which they don't.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg LP</ENAMEX>, the parent company of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
provides news and programming to subscribers of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DirecTV</ENAMEX>, another
direct broadcast satellite service, which is run by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GM Hughes
Electronics</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
