<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">JAPAN</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ROCKET</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">HUGHES</ENAMEX>-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">JAPAN</ENAMEX>'S <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ROCKET SYSTEMS</ENAMEX> TO LAUNCH MORE THAN 10 <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">HUGHES</ENAMEX> SATELLITES
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hanabusa Midori</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tokyo</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 4</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rocket Systems Corp.</ENAMEX> is
close to signing a deal worth about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$8 billion</NUMEX> to launch more than
10 satellites for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Space and Communications International</ENAMEX>, a
unit of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Electronics Corp.</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   Success of the deal will mark <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s entry into the commercial
satellite launch business around <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the turn of the century</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``We've reached agreement on basic conditions for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RSC</ENAMEX> launching
the satellites for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>. We expect to sign a formal contract by
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the end of August</TIMEX>,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hiroshi Imamura</ENAMEX>, executive vice president
overseeing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RSC</ENAMEX>'s commercial launch service.
<p>
   The basic conditions cover the number of satellites, cost,
options, penalties and insurance of the launches, he said, adding
there are still several details to be worked out.
<p>
   Under the agreement, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RSC</ENAMEX> will launch more than 10 satellites for
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> using the H2A rocket. It is being developed by Japanese
companies and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Space Development Agency</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>'s
version of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>, in a national effort to provide an inexpensive,
commercial version of the current H2 rockets.
<p>
   Each launch on the H2A will cost around <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">8.5 billion yen</NUMEX>,
bringing the total value of the deal to more than <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">850 billion yen</NUMEX>
(<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$7.73 billion</NUMEX>).
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RSC</ENAMEX> plans to launch two <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> satellites a year once initial
test launches of the H2A rockets are completed around the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2000">year
2000</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Imamura</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``Five other companies, including <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> and European ones, have
approached us'' since <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">RSC</ENAMEX> proposed developing the H2A to slash
launch costs by half that of the H2, he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rocket Systems Corp.</ENAMEX> is an unlisted company founded in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1990</TIMEX> by a
consortium of 73 Japanese companies. Its shareholders include
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy
Industries Co.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kawasaki Heavy Industries Ltd.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nissan Motor Co.</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NEC Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fujitsu Ltd.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mitsubishi Electric Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Mitsubishi
Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nissho Iwai Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sumitomo Corp.</ENAMEX>, as well as 19 non-life
insurers and 12 commercial banks.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Electronics Corp.</ENAMEX> is wholly-owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> automaker
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX>, and is represented by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GM</ENAMEX>'s class H stock.
</TEXT>
