<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A7416 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tth-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-LASER-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-08</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-LASER-SPI
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX> MAKES BID FOR LASER-ARMED 747 CONTRACT
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">T.M. SELL</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Seattle Post-Intelligencer</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">SEATTLE</ENAMEX>  &MD;  This could be the jet you won't want to mess with  &MD;  a
747 with a laser in its nose.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing Co.</ENAMEX> bid <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> for what could become a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5 billion</NUMEX>
contract to build seven such jets, which could detect and shoot
down hostile missiles in mid-flight.
<p>
   ``This a revolutionary weapons system,'' said Airborne Laser
Program Manager <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Paul Shennum</ENAMEX>. ``This could revolutionize
warfighting in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the 21st century</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> has teamed with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TRW</ENAMEX> to bid on the
project following more than <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">three years</TIMEX> of research and
development. A team including <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell International</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes
Aircraft</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">E Systems</ENAMEX> also is expected to bid by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>'s
deadline.
<p>
   Both teams will submit revised proposals in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX>, with final
award <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early next January</TIMEX>. A demonstration aircraft should be flying
by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2002</TIMEX>, with the first production models going into service by
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2006</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The project is an outgrowth of the Gulf War, where <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Raytheon</ENAMEX>'s
Patriot anti-missile system was pressed into service to shoot down
SCUD surface-to-surface missiles fired by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iraq</ENAMEX>. Despite early
reports of the Patriot's success, later evidence indicated that the
Patriot was too easily fooled by the missiles' breaking up on
re-entry into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">earth</ENAMEX>'s atmosphere.
<p>
   The Airborne Laser would use its own sensors and those aboard
satellites and reconnaissance craft to spot such missiles on their
way up, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shennum</ENAMEX> said. A powerful laser beam would hit the target at
around 40,000 feet from a distance of about 250 miles, while the
missile is still climbing and before it separates into distinct
warheads. Any fallout would land on the area that launched the
missile.
<p>
   ``With our sensors we are able to determine where the missile is
launched from and where it was going to land,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shennum</ENAMEX> said.
Launch-site location would be passed on to ground and air attack
forces, which would then have a much better chance of finding and
destroying the launching equipment.
<p>
   The teeth of the system is <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TRW</ENAMEX>'s chemically powered laser; an
electric laser would require more hardware than even a 747 could
carry, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shennum</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Randy Harrison</ENAMEX> said that because the laser uses
what are essentially household chemicals  &MD;  hydrogen peroxide,
chlorine and iodine  &MD;  the expected operating price will be around
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1,000</NUMEX> a shot. ``It will be able to fire repeatedly,'' he said. A
missile, by comparison, costs <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1-2 million</NUMEX> a copy.
<p>
   Of course, mixing those things together in a bowl at home won't
give you a laser. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX> had to develop an optical system
that would not only sight the target, but also focus the laser in
such a way that it could survive the vagaries of weather. A laser
is just an incredibly intense beam of light, and like a flashlight
at a distance, that light can dissipate and lose focus.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shennum</ENAMEX> said the problem seems to be solved.
<p>
   ``A lot of progress has been made in that area,'' he said.
Upper-atmosphere turbulence isn't as severe as first thought, and
they've gotten better at focusing.
<p>
   ``All our simulations, all the test experiments prove <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> that
we can deliver the lethal energy required to the distances
required,'' he said. ``Now we have to finalize our design concept
and build it and go up and prove it. We know of no show stoppers.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s task in the project is to develop the battle management
system and to integrate the whole thing into a 747-400, perhaps the
only aircraft large enough to carry everything required. The
competing bid, for example, also uses a 747 platform.
<p>
   The airborne platform's mobility also is a selling point.
``We're capable of self-deploying anywhere in the world within <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">13
hours</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shennum</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``It's a peaceful deterrent,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shennum</ENAMEX> said. ``It doesn't have
to be over hostile territory to be effective.''
</TEXT>
