<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-GALILEO-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">GANYMEDE</ENAMEX>-ART- </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-10</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0988 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-GALILEO-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">GANYMEDE</ENAMEX>-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">JUPITER</ENAMEX> PROBE FINDS SURPRISE ON A BIG MOON
(ART ADV: Graphic/photo is being sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX> graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JOHN NOBLE WILFORD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   On its first close encounter with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jupiter</ENAMEX>'s huge satellite
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX>, the Galileo spacecraft has found evidence that this
largest moon in the solar system behaves in many surprising ways
like a full-fledged planet.
<p>
   With its 3,269-mile diameter, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX> is larger than the planet
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mercury</ENAMEX> and about three-quarters the size of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX>. It is lifeless
and frozen, covered with ice and some dark, rocky debris, but the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX> revealed by Galileo's first pictures has a surface that is
deeply wrinkled with ridges, fissures and furrows, as well as other
signs that it experiences some of the same dynamic forces that move
continents and cause quakes on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Other instruments on the spacecraft detected an even bigger
surprise. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX> appears to generate its own magnetic field, a
planet-like characteristic that sets it apart from other moons.
<p>
   What this implies about <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX>'s interior structure is a
matter of puzzlement and debate for scientists, but it could mean
that despite its cold exterior, the large moon has a molten
metallic core generating the magnetic field, much as happens on
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But without doubt the first close-up photographs of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX>,
made public <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>, underscored the success of the
Galileo mission, which in itself is a surprise. Launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1989</TIMEX>,
the spacecraft has suffered one malfunction after another,
including the failure of its main antenna to deploy, which has
limited the number of pictures that can be transmitted.
<p>
   Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William J. O'Neil</ENAMEX>, the project manager at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jet Propulsion
Laboratory</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pasadena</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>, recalled <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> the heroic
efforts of engineers to keep the spacecraft going.
<p>
   ``You might say we had to perform a complete brain transplant,''
he said, referring to the reprogramming of Galileo's onboard
software to work around the malfunctions and meet about <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">70 percent</NUMEX>
of the original mission objectives.
<p>
   Galileo made it to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jupiter</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last December</TIMEX>, swinging into an orbit
of the planet and sending in an instrumented probe of the dense
Jovian atmosphere. On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 27</TIMEX>, it had its first of four planned
encounters with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ganymede</ENAMEX>. Over the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next two years</TIMEX>, the spacecraft
is expected to fly close to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jupiter</ENAMEX>'s three other major moons  &MD; 
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Callisto</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europa</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Io</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-10-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2003EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
