<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-10</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS
ROCKET PROBLEM COULD KEEP ASTRONAUT IN ORBIT UNTIL <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">SEPTEMBER</TIMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shannon Lucid</ENAMEX>, a guest aboard <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s
Mir space station <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="late March">since late March</TIMEX>, could spend an extra <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">six weeks</TIMEX>
orbiting the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> because of the shuttle's rocket booster
problems, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">53-year</TIMEX>-old biochemist will shatter the American
longevity record for spaceflight, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">115 days</TIMEX>, established <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a year ago</TIMEX>
by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Norm Thagard</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX>'s stay could be extended to <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">six months</TIMEX> under one scenario
described by officials of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX>. The agency is investigating the cause of charring
on insulation that protected O-ring joints on boosters used to
launch Columbia on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 20</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The discovery of the damage could delay <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s plans to launch
Atlantis on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 31</TIMEX> to replace <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX> with astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Blaha</ENAMEX>. If
the solid rocket boosters on Atlantis must be replaced, the
shuttle's launching would be postponed until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sept. 15</TIMEX>, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tommy
Holloway</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s shuttle program manager.
<p>
   ``She (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX>) has no problem with it,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Frank Culbertson</ENAMEX>,
who manages <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s cooperative activities with the Russians aboard
Mir. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Culbertson</ENAMEX>, an astronaut, said he briefed <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX> personally on
the issues <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``She wants to make sure people down here understand she's very
happy and comfortable. She understands the situation,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Culbertson</ENAMEX>
said. ``She also wants to make sure that people know she should not
be a factor in making the technical decision on whether to fly the
mission with the current booster configuration or to change it.''
<p>
   Experts have discovered some charring from rocket exhaust into
insulation protecting all six of the O-ring joints in both 15-story
solid rocket boosters used in Columbia's launch. The worst of the
damage was found in joints in the middle of the boosters.
<p>
   It was the leak of hot gases through a similar O-ring joint that
triggered the fatal Challenger accident of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1986</TIMEX>. However, none of
Columbia's O-rings were burned, officials said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Holloway</ENAMEX> said engineers continue to believe that a new adhesive
used to bond the insulation on Columbia or a new solvent used to
prepare the material for bonding is the most likely cause of
damage. However, he emphasized that managers will spend at least
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="week">another week</TIMEX> assessing launch forces and other possible factors.
<p>
   If the cause turns out to be the adhesive or solvent, Atlantis'
boosters would be removed and replaced with two new rockets
constructed of the glue and cleaning solution that have been used
in past launches.
<p>
   The space agency and its contractor switched supplies to comply
with environmental regulations. But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Holloway</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Utah</ENAMEX>-based
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Thiokol Corp.</ENAMEX>, the booster contractor, has enough of the old
materials to last 14 missions.
<p>
   Meanwhile, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> towed Atlantis from its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX>
launching pad to its assembly hangar on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> when it appeared
the complex might be hit by Hurricane Bertha.
</TEXT>
