<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A2996 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LUCID</ENAMEX>-STUCK-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-12</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LUCID</ENAMEX>-STUCK-HNS
MISSION TO RETRIEVE ASTRONAUT IS DELAYED <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">SIX WEEKS</TIMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARK CARREAU</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">HOUSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> announced it will delay by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">six weeks</TIMEX> a
mission to retrieve astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shannon Lucid</ENAMEX>, who is doing research
on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s Mir space station.
<p>
   The decision was prompted by the discovery that the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 20</TIMEX>
launching of the shuttle Columbia produced unexpected exhaust that
charred insulation which protects six O-ring joints.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX> therefore
wants to replace the solid rocket boosters on the shuttle Atlantis,
which has been assigned to return <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The repairs will push the planned launching of Atlantis <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">from
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 31</TIMEX> to <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sept. 15</TIMEX></TIMEX>, though it may be possible for the shuttle's
six-member crew to lift off a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">couple of days earlier</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Atlantis also will ferry several tons of supplies to the
Russians. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX> will be replaced by Atlantis astronaut <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Blaha</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> record-setting space voyage will be extended <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="four and a half to six months">from
four and a half to six months</TIMEX>. On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, she is slated to break
the record of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">115 days</TIMEX>, which was established by former astronaut
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Norm Thagard</ENAMEX> about a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``Everyone is in concurrence that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shannon</ENAMEX> is in good shape, and
she's prepared to go longer,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Frank Culbertson</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s
manager of joint <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-Russian space flights. ``These things tend to
happen and you learn to deal with them.''
<p>
   The space agency planned to inform <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lucid</ENAMEX> of its decision <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early
Saturday</TIMEX>. However, it has kept her apprised of the booster rocket
issue for more than a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">week</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Earlier this week</TIMEX>, she told American reporters she was taking
the delay in stride, though she was disappointed in not being able
to rejoin her family as soon as planned.
</TEXT>
