<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A5136 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-DEFENSE-CAMPAIGN-BLOO </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-23</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0875 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-DEFENSE-CAMPAIGN-BLOOM
MORE HIGH-TECH WEAPONS LIKELY UNDER <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DOLE</ENAMEX>: <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> CAMPAIGN ISSUES
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dina Temple-Raston</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (One in a series examining policies of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX>)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 23</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- Defense spending is on the
decline, when adjusted for inflation, and no matter who wins the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX> presidential election, that trend will continue. For all
the campaign rhetoric, the budgets backed by President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Clinton</ENAMEX>
and Republican challenger <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Dole</ENAMEX> differ on defense by less than
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 billion</NUMEX>.
<p>
   There are significant differences, however, on how the
candidates would spend defense money, and that could make all the
difference in the world to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> weapons producers like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed
Martin Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northrop Grumman Corp.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TRW Inc.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell
Douglas Corp.</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> is likely to cut personnel, relying more on reserves and
backing fewer humanitarian missions, thereby freeing funds for more
high-technology weapons such as bombers and fighter planes.
<p>
   ``Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> has emphasized one particular weapon system --that's
the ballistic missile defense,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lawrence Korb</ENAMEX>, a former
assistant secretary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">defense</ENAMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reagan</ENAMEX> administration. ``He
has also talked about adding more B-2 bombers . . . I also think
you will see him buying more F-22s.''
<p>
   If <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Korb</ENAMEX>'s scenario plays out, it would boost several defense
contractors, including <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX>, which makes the F-22,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northrop Grumman Corp.</ENAMEX>, which makes the B-2.
<p>
   The radar-evading, wing-shaped B-2 bomber has become a kind of
defense policy litmus test for <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> supports the B-2 and has said he wants money added to the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> budget for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">fiscal year starting Oct. 1</TIMEX> to fund
additional B-2s.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> opposes congressional efforts to push the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> in
that direction. He and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Perry</ENAMEX> say the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>'s long-term plans call for spending money on weapons that
are more important than the B-2.
<p>
   The two presidential candidates also have jockeyed over how fast
to develop the ballistic missile defense system. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> moved to set
himself apart from the president by backing a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">multibillion dollar</NUMEX>
revival of President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ronald Reagan</ENAMEX>'s ``star wars'' defense
initiative. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House</ENAMEX> Republicans postponed floor consideration of the
plan, though, after the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congressional Budget Office</ENAMEX> estimated it
would cost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">between $31 billion and $60 billion</NUMEX>. Republicans called
the estimate ``outlandish.''
<p>
   The delay in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> did not deter <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> from pushing the plan.
He told workers in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">California</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX> that if he were elected he
would make sure there would be major funding for the advanced
missile systems that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX> has been building <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="1968">since 1968</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Korb</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX> will likely push the plan if he is elected. ``The
ballistic missile defense for Republicans is sort of the foreign
policy equivalent of abortion,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Korb</ENAMEX> told the Bloomberg Forum.
``It's an article of faith (for Republicans) that we have to defend
this country against a ballistic missile attack.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> has his own missile defense plan, but it is smaller and
wouldn't be built as soon. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s plan would cost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$14 billion</NUMEX>
over <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the next five years</TIMEX>. The administration has said it isn't sure
when the system would be deployed. The Republicans want a deadline
and have suggested the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2003">year 2003</TIMEX>.
<p>
   While <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX>'s election would likely help the defense industry, no
one suggests he'll reverse the overall downward trend. ``Defense
spending is probably going to continue to decline, and companies
are going to have to change in response to that,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Fred
Johnson</ENAMEX>, chairman of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Mexico</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Santa Fe Technologies Inc.</ENAMEX>,
which develops missile defenses.
<p>
   For industry giants such as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX>,
and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northrop Grumman</ENAMEX>, the strategy for dealing with defense-budget
cuts has been to purchase other companies' business and slash
operating costs. The smaller component-suppliers companies have
been able to diversify their production to supply other industries,
as well as the defense business.
<p>
   There are a few exceptions. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp,</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" MIN="Hughes Electronics">Hughes
Electronics division</ENAMEX> makes missiles, radar systems, and one of the
best-selling consumer products -- the home DirecTV
satellite-broadcast system. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell International Corp.</ENAMEX>
manufactures bombs, and rocket engines, and is a leading maker of
computer modems. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Raytheon Co.</ENAMEX> makes defense electronics and missile
systems, provides construction services, and manufacturers Amana
refrigerators and ovens.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Raytheon</ENAMEX> is a good example of a company that isn't depending
just on government contracts, and more companies are going to have
to follow their lead,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Simple mathematics explains why: The portion of the defense
budget earmarked for purchases of new weapons has been slashed by
more than half to about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$40 billion</NUMEX>. Adjusted for inflation, the
weapons budget in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1986</TIMEX> was <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$124 billion</NUMEX>.
<p>
   As orders have dropped, companies have responded by
consolidating their operations, buying up their competitors'
product lines and pursuing technologies that have both military and
civilian use as a cushion against shrinking federal contracts.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-23-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1103EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
