<DOCID> nyt960723.0379 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A5472 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANESPACE</ENAMEX>-CRASH-UPD </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-23</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0947 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANESPACE</ENAMEX>-CRASH-UPDATE1-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ARIANE</ENAMEX> 5 ROCKET RELAUNCH FORECAST FOR <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">SPRING 1997</TIMEX> (UPDATE 1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christina Benischke</ENAMEX> through the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> newsroom 
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Adds comment throughout, detail to recommendations)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 23</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>, a pan-European
satellite launch group, hopes to launch the second <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 rocket
in ``<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the middle of the first half of 1997</TIMEX>,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jean-Marie Luton</ENAMEX>,
the director general of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Luton</ENAMEX>, who was presenting a report on the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 4</TIMEX> crash of the
first <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 launcher, said the proposed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">spring</TIMEX> date was
preliminary.
<p>
   He said the failed launch cost <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">between 2 percent and 4 percent</NUMEX>
of the total investment so far in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 development program,
or <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">between 800 million and 1.6 billion French francs</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$159 million
and $318 million</NUMEX>).
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 is an unmanned rocket, the most powerful built for
commercial payloads. It had been hoped a further prototype could be
launched as early as <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late October</TIMEX> or <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early November</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The report said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 failure was caused by ``the
complete loss of guidance and attitude information 37 seconds after
the start of the main engine ignition sequence (30 seconds after
lift-off).''
<p>
   The report blamed the loss of information on ``specification and
design errors in the software of the inertial reference system,''
part of the flight control system that measures the launcher's
movements in space and its position in relation to the horizon, or
attitude.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Luton</ENAMEX> stressed that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 program has ``not itself been
undermined by the report, which refers to specific errors.'' He
declined to comment where responsibility for those errors lies,
saying, ``We are all at fault.''
<p>
   The board that wrote the report presented a series of 14
recommendations to improve review procedures for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5
program that it said ``did not include adequate analysis and
testing of the inertial reference system or of the complete flight
control system, which could have detected the potential failure.''
<p>
   The report called for complete simulations before any mission
and recommended that the alignment function should be switched off
after lift-off. More generally, software functions should not run
during a flight unless needed.
<p>
   Among other recommendations, the board urged the inclusion in
the review procedures of participants from outside the project. The
board also called for ``more transparent cooperation among the
partners in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 program'' which it said should provide
``clear-cut authority and responsibility''.
<p>
   German Technology Minister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Juergen Ruettgers</ENAMEX> welcomed the
report, saying he would seek early agreement with his French
counterpart <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francois Fillon</ENAMEX> on how best to implement it. He agreed
with the recommendations to clarify lines of responsibility and
draw on independent experts, and urged <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX> to take a more active
role in overseeing the project.
<p>
   ``We must not allow ourselves to be put under time pressure in
this process,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ruettgers</ENAMEX> said. Only the result of a second test
flight will show whether a third flight is needed, he added. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX>
had earlier indicated that a third flight ``would contribute
towards the qualification'' of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 program.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ruettgers</ENAMEX> said participating governments should on no account
provide extra funds for any such flight. Instead, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX> should find
the money out of existing budgets, particularly those for follow-up
projects to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5, he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Luton</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">European Space Agency</ENAMEX> will study the report's
recommendations and present its own full proposals for future
action to the board in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Among elements that are likely to become clearer in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September</TIMEX> is
whether the second <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 launcher will have a commercial payload
on board. Further information is also expected at that time on the
financial implications for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 program as a whole. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ESA</ENAMEX>
said it would hold a further press conference in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-September</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> currently controls more than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">50%</NUMEX> of the global
satellite launch market and booked 14 orders in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the first half of
1996</TIMEX>. The order backlog as at <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 24</TIMEX> totalled 44 satellites worth
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">18.2 billion francs</NUMEX>. Further launches of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4 rocket are
scheduled, including that of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Telecom</ENAMEX> 2D satellite for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">France
Telecom</ENAMEX> ``within the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next few weeks</TIMEX>,'' according to a spokesman for
the state-owned group.
<p>
   More precise timing was not available. The spokesman would not
comment on whether <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">France Telecom</ENAMEX> would put satellites on a future
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 flight. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>'s other major clients include
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Eutelsat</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   A spokeswoman for French insurer <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Assurances Generales de France</ENAMEX>
(<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AGF</ENAMEX>) confirmed the group's insurance program was being maintained
on an unchanged basis for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4 flights. She added that the
delays to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 5 program ``inevitably changes the calendar
for the first launch, no doubt pushing it back to <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the end of 1997</TIMEX>
at the earliest.''
<p>
   The spokeswoman said it was too early to assess the impact on
insurance premiums. French insurers reportedly made a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">3 billion
franc</NUMEX> profit in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1995</TIMEX> on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ariane</ENAMEX> 4 insured launches because of the
high success rate.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX> is a group of more than 50 European aerospace and
defense companies that builds rockets to launch telecommunications
and scientific satellites.
<p>
   French companies, including <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aerospatiale</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">L'Air Liquide</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Societe de Propulsion</ENAMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SEP</ENAMEX>), hold a <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">55 percent</NUMEX> stake in
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Arianespace</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   German companies including <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Daimler Benz Aerospace</ENAMEX>, or <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DASA</ENAMEX>, own
a <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">19 percent</NUMEX> stake. A total of 12 European nations are represented
in the consortium.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-23-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1511EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
