<DOCID> nyt960802.0672 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A9921 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tth-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-SPACE-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-02</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-SPACE-SPI
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>'S NEXT CHALLENGE: MAKE MONEY IN SPACE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">T.M. SELL</ENAMEX> 
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Seattle Post-Intelligencer</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">SEATTLE</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s purchase of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell International</ENAMEX>'s defense
and space business may make it the world's biggest space company.
But the company's biggest challenge will be to make money at it.
<p>
   As it integrates the business units newly acquired from
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX>, analysts say <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> will have to pursue new frontiers and
refine existing programs. And with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ENAMEX> turning more and more responsibility over to
private business, space is no longer the final frontier. Making
money in space is.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s space-oriented divisions, much like its post-cold war
military programs, face tight markets with few customers, mostly
governments, and uncertain finances.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> and the analysts who follow the company say the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Seattle</ENAMEX>-based firm is well positioned to boldly go where few
businesses have gone before. By spreading its defense and space
business across a wide range of products, analysts say, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> will
find a way to make money.
<p>
   ``If they didn't think they could make money at it they wouldn't
do it,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Whitlow</ENAMEX>, research director at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pacific Crest
Securities</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Seattle</ENAMEX>. ``That's one of the changes in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s
philosophy in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the last decade</TIMEX>. They're not going to go after
business if it's not going to make money.''
<p>
   The most solid part of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s newly expanded space portfolio
could be the satellite business. Thousands of satellites will be
launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the next two decades</TIMEX>, experts say, because it's the
easiest, quickest way to transmit data. Launching them into orbit
is a significant cost component. The low-cost provider will get
plenty of business.
<p>
   ``The demand is obviously there,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Whitlow</ENAMEX> said. ``No matter how
you do it, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s got their foot in the door. They have better
skills at this (space systems) than anybody else, especially with
the addition of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX> component.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s satellite program now includes the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SeaLaunch</ENAMEX>
partnership, the Space Shuttle, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ukraine</ENAMEX> medium-payload
launch venture, and the EELV reusable rocket project for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air
Force</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> is playing both sides of the street,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Whitlow</ENAMEX> said.
``Not only are they <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s largest contractor, they're also
involved in the private launch business.''
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX> purchase includes a division that builds
satellites. That gives <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> the opportunity to offer customers
turn-key packages of satellite and launch, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Jacobs</ENAMEX>,
aerospace analyst at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ragen MacKenzie</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Seattle</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But satellites are just the tip of the rocket. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> is prime
contractor for the Space Station. Through <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> now is
jointly responsible with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> for operating the Space Shuttle,
and engine supplier for the X-33 reusable space launch vehicle.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> hopes to provide composites and operational expertise to
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed</ENAMEX> on that venture.
<p>
   ``They've got their fingers in enough of the future
developmental programs that they'll continue to be a player no
matter what happens,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jacobs</ENAMEX>. ``They're not going to live or
die by a single program.''
<p>
   That's good, because big programs such as the Space Station and
the X-33 reusable launch vehicle come with big risks.
<p>
   The Space Station, for example, is up against tight budgetary
constraints and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> is facing technological challenges in
developing its part of the package. The Russians reportedly are
behind schedule on their end of the program, including the
energy-generating FGB module scheduled to go into orbit in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November
1997</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> called in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two years ago</TIMEX> to act as a sort of
construction manager for the station, letting <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> apply the
system-integration skills that have become one the firm's core
competencies. But the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> space agency has made it clear that it
is rapidly moving to a role in which it will support research and
development, and leave the business of space launch and operation
to the private sector. Eventually, that could include the Space
Station.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> has experience turning big risk into profits, both in
commercial and defense ventures.
<p>
   At the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">beginning of the decade</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s defense group was
losing <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">hundreds of millions of dollars</NUMEX> a year. Now, it's solidly
profitable.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> achieved that by cutting costs, slashing payroll and
focusing on contracts that could make money, said spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dave
Suffia</ENAMEX>. Money-losing projects like the Peace Shield ground radar
and the A-6 aircraft re-wing were jettisoned, and employment
dropped from 53,000 to 31,000 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``We've made sure that the programs we have been involved with
are really sound financially,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Suffia</ENAMEX> said. ``And we're just a
heck of a lot more efficient at what we're doing.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s tally of big-ticket defense projects includes the V-22
Osprey tilt-rotor aircraft; military derivatives of the 767; RAH-66
Commanche attack helicopter; and the F-22 advanced tactical
fighter. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> also is bidding on potentially lucrative contracts
for an airborne laser system and the Joint Strike Fighter, and it's
working on unmanned aircraft and high-tech in-flight antenna
systems, both of which could provide big payoffs in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the next
century</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX> acquisitions bring in a number of mature programs
such as the B-1B bomber and the Space Shuttle, plus potentially
profitable ventures such as electro-optical and laser technology.
<p>
   The key to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s success in space and defense will be making
full use of its talents, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jacobs</ENAMEX> said, including those added from
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockwell</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``What <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> has to do to make this acquisition pay off in the
long term is create new business opportunities from this,'' he
said. ``You need one plus one to equal three.''
</TEXT>
