<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A4940 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttc-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MARS</ENAMEX>-EXPLORE-LADN </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-07</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0822 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MARS</ENAMEX>-EXPLORE-LADN
SCIENTIST ANXIOUS TO BEGIN SERIES OF MISSIONS TO <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MARS</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">KEITH STONE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Los Angeles Daily News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LOS ANGELES</ENAMEX>  &MD;  News that a Martian meteorite found in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Antarctica</ENAMEX>
might have contained life came as scientists at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jet
Propulsion Laboratory</ENAMEX> busily prepare to launch the first of 10
unmanned missions to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Red Planet</ENAMEX>, beginning in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``It certainly is an exciting day!'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Norm Haynes</ENAMEX>, director
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Exploration Program at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JPL</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pasadena</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   This cosmic coincidence in timing has led scientists at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JPL</ENAMEX> to
wonder whether they should accelerate their plans and retrieve a
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> rock in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2003">year 2003</TIMEX>  &MD;  <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="two years sooner">two years sooner than intended</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Global Surveyor will blast off in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX>, followed in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December</TIMEX> by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Pathfinder and then another launch <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">every 25 months
until the year 2005</TIMEX>, all to better understand the most <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>-like
of all planets in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Solar System</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Exactly when a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> rock is returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX> will hinge on
whether scientists worldwide agree with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ENAMEX> that the meteorite contains bacteria fossils  &MD; 
evidence that life existed on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s next-door neighbor.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JPL</ENAMEX> scientists had expected to retrieve a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> sample during a
mission to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Red Planet</ENAMEX> in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2005">year 2005</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``If analysis of the meteorite indicates that life is verified,
or at least if there is a consensus in the scientific community,
there will probably be some push to move up the sample return,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Haynes</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Further, the evidence of life will give scientists a better idea
of where to look for a sample, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Haynes</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``What we have to do is find the right place for the right
sample,'' he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Daniel S. Goldin</ENAMEX> said the meteorite discovery
might herald other changes in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> missions.
<p>
   ``In a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">few years</TIMEX>, we may want to consider some very bold
missions,'' he said, adding that some missions might dig into the
Martian surface in search of samples.
<p>
   ``We will have to ask, will robots do the task, or do we need
astronauts. But these are questions we will have to ask on a
systematic basis,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Golden</ENAMEX> added.
<p>
   Whatever changes are made are too late for Global Surveyor and
Pathfinder.
<p>
   As <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> announced its findings <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JPL</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> team made
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">last-minute</TIMEX> adjustments to Pathfinder and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Global Surveyor,
before taking them <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX> to the launch site in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cape Canaveral</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX> Pathfinder will be the first lander to visit <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> since the
Viking missions some <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">20 years ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Global Surveyor will explore <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> from space in the same way
that scientists had hoped <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JPL</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Observer would have, before it
was lost in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX> after firing its rockets.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Pathfinder's scheduled landing on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Independence Day 1997</TIMEX> is
expected to provide much information about the planet's composition
and climate, but probably not any more clues about the possibility
of life there.
<p>
   A key focus for scientists will be how <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> once supported
water, the root of life.
<p>
   ``It would be a long shot if we saw direct fossil evidence,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rob Manning</ENAMEX>, the flight system chief engineer. ``However, our
work could be complementary on the water question.''
<p>
   Also, Pathfinder's four-wheeled, 20-pound rover may help
researchers search the surface of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> for rocks that are made of
the same material as the meteorite found in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Antarctica</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1984</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``What we can do is see if there is the same general elemental
composition and mineralogy of those meteorites,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Donna
Shirley</ENAMEX>, program manager of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Explorer programs.
<p>
   ``And we will be getting close up pictures with the rover
camera. That may or may not tell us how they compare with the
meteorite,'' she said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> scientists said that chemical and microscopic tests of
minute pieces of the meteorite show there must have been life on
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> some <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">3.6 billion years ago</TIMEX>. The rock was found in an <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Antarctic</ENAMEX>
ice field <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="12 years ago">12 years ago, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="13,000 years">13,000 years after it is believed to have
landed there</TIMEX></TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``We know we have picked just the right spot to go with
Pathfinder, because Pathfinder is going to a place where we expect
there to be rocks from the ancient highlands,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shirley</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The Pathfinder spacecraft and the subsequent missions will not
be able to conduct the same sophisticated study of rocks that the
meteorite underwent on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> scientists used an extremely
large piece of equipment to peer inside particles a billionth the
size of a pinhead.
<p>
   ``Right now we don't have the technology. Certainly our
spacecraft was not designed to do that. We are on a geologic
mission,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Manning</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   One thing that the meteorite discovery affirms for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JPL</ENAMEX>
scientists is the need to make sure their spacecraft do not
contaminate <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>-spawned germs, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Manning</ENAMEX> said. ``It just
emphasizes the need to keep the spacecraft clean  &MD;  biologically
clean.''
</TEXT>
