<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A2003 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-AURORA-SATELLITE-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-24</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-AURORA-SATELLITE-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> LAUNCHES SATELLITE TO STUDY AURORA
(kd)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LOS ANGELES</ENAMEX>  &MD;  A satellite launched <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX> will monitor the
undulating curtains of the aurora light in the polar <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> sky in
an effort to explain its mysteries.
<p>
   The satellite, the Fast Auroral Snapshot, or FAST, is the second
of a new generation of smaller and cheaper spacecraft that
scientists say are the future of orbiter-based research. The
400-pound craft was launched on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> aboard a rocket from an
L-1011 jumbo jet, which was flying off the coast 150 miles
northwest of here.
<p>
   FAST will orbit as low as 220 miles above <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>, gathering
information and photographs of auroras on a scale of a few meters
rather than one kilometer, the scale of previous studies.
<p>
   In the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Northern Hemisphere</ENAMEX>, the multicolored veil is called the
aurora borealis, or northern lights. Auroras are most visible near
the magnetic <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">North and South Poles</ENAMEX> and can stretch across the
horizon for hundreds of miles at an altitude of 70 miles.
<p>
   ``Anyone who has seen the aurora borealis is impressed by the
colors,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles Carlson</ENAMEX>, the principal investigator for FAST
and a professor at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">University of California at Berkeley</ENAMEX>. ``But
we as scientists are interested in the physical properties that
cause these aurora displays.''
<p>
   A project scientist from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Goddard Space Flight Center</ENAMEX> in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenbelt</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Md.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Pfaff</ENAMEX>, said the research would help explain
similar phenomena on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jupiter</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Scientists also hope to gain insight into solar flares, which
add to the auroras' intensity. Those occasional explosions from the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sun</ENAMEX> disrupt the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s magnetic field and can make an aurora
visible as far south as <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Auroras are mainly powered by electrons, which are stripped by
solar winds from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sun</ENAMEX> and sent hurtling through space. FAST will
monitor the electrons in thousandths of a second as they are drawn
to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Earth</ENAMEX>'s magnetic poles and are accelerated by electrical
fields into the atmosphere, where they cast their hazy glow.
<p>
   Scientists expect FAST to be in use for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="two years">at least two years</TIMEX>,
before its orbit decays or radiation damages it. The instruments
are to be fully operational in a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">few months</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$72.2 million</NUMEX> project is part of a five-craft Small-Class
Explorer series of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ENAMEX>. The government intends the effort to make launching
a space satellite faster and cheaper than large-scale <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">multiyear</TIMEX>
endeavors like the Hubble Space Telescope. The other satellite in
the series was launched in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX>, to monitor solar winds.
<p>
   ``The scientific community is really thrilled by this program,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pfaff</ENAMEX> said. ``Projects in the past were really getting drawn out,
because large aircraft take longer to build.''
</TEXT>
