<PREAMBLE>
BC-SCIENCE-NOTES-COX
MARTIAN ODYSSEY AT STARTING GATE
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MIKE TONER</ENAMEX>
c. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The pair of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> spacecraft that will be launched to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
year</TIMEX> have arrived at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Space Center</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX> to be
readied for flights that have taken on new import since the report
that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> may once have supported primitive life.
<p>
   Neither spacecraft is designed to directly detect evidence of
life, past or present, but both are expected to expand
understanding of the planet.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Global Surveyor, a 1-ton spacecraft, will be launched
in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX>. After reaching <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September 1997</TIMEX>, it will circle
the planet for an <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="Martian year">entire Martian year  &MD;  <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">687 Earth days</TIMEX>  &MD;</TIMEX>  mapping
the surface of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">red planet</ENAMEX> in detail.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> Pathfinder, scheduled for launch in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December</TIMEX>, will
follow a faster track to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX>. The spacecraft is expected to land
on the surface on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 4, 1997</TIMEX>, releasing a small robot rover,
Sojourner, that will roam the surface of the planet.
<p>
     NEXT: LIVING TO 130  
<p>
   Get the birthday candles ready. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Duke University</ENAMEX> researchers say
changing human life spans make it likely that at least one person
currently alive in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> will live to the ripe, and
unprecedented, old age of 130 or 135.
<p>
   Although a number of people claim to be older, the oldest living
person whose age can be reliably documented <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> is a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">121-year</TIMEX>-old
woman in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">France</ENAMEX>. But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Duke</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Center for Demographic Studies</ENAMEX> says
conservative projections of population suggest that someone alive
will easily top that. With improving control of chronic diseases,
nutrition and overall health, they say, there is no ``biological
brick wall'' that sets an absolute limit on human life.
<p>
   The oldest old, in fact, are likely to have lots of company.
Within the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next 50 years</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> is expected to have
more than 1 million people over the age of 100  &MD;  and about 4
million or 5 million over the age of 95.
<p>
   A BRAIN FOR ROMANCE
<p>
   Birdbrain may not be the pejorative it's cracked up to be.
Researchers have discovered that songbirds' brains vary in size
according to the season.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">University of Washington</ENAMEX> zoology graduate <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Troy Smith</ENAMEX> says
seasonal changes in the size of certain parts of sparrows' brains
track the rise and fall of the hormone testosterone, which
increases 100-fold at the peak of the breeding season in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX>.
<p>
   It's not a case of birds needing a bigger brain specifically to
breed, though. It's all for the song. Rising levels of testosterone
triple the size of two portions of avian brains involved in
singing. And that may explain why some birds need <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">spring</TIMEX> tuneups
before going courting.
<p>
   ``Essentially the bird is making little mistakes, much like a
musician who is playing a song for the first time in a while and is
a little rusty,'' says <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX>, who did the research for his Ph.D.
<p>
   (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mike Toner</ENAMEX> writes for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Atlanta Journal-Constitution</ENAMEX>.) .
</TEXT>
