<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PANAMSAT</ENAMEX> SHARES RISE ON SPECULATION IT MAY BE ACQUIRED SOON
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karen Fessler</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenwich</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Connecticut</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Aug. 27</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat Corp.</ENAMEX>
shares rose as much as <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">8.2 percent</NUMEX> on speculation the satellite
company may soon reach an agreement to be acquired for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4 billion
to $5 billion</NUMEX>, analysts say.
<p>
   Shares rose 1 3/8 to 27 1/4 in late trading of 333,400, more
than double the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">three-month</TIMEX> daily average of 158,100. <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Earlier</TIMEX>, the
stock touched 28.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greenwich</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Connecticut</ENAMEX>-based company is attractive because
it has reserved several good orbital positions for new satellites.
The company already operates four satellites that broadcast video
and audio service in much of the world except the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   ``For anyone who buys it, it gives them an immediate worldwide
presence in the satellite industry,'' said analyst <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tom Watts</ENAMEX> of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   The likely buyers include <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors Corp.</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes
Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> unit, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Electric Co.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Space &AMP;
Communications Ltd.</ENAMEX>, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Watts</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX>, which has about <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 billion</NUMEX> in debt and 100 million
shares outstanding, would be valued at least <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$3.6 billion</NUMEX> and may
fetch <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4 billion to $5 billion</NUMEX> in an acquisition, analysts said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> declined to comment. A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> spokeswoman said the
company ``neither confirms nor denies'' acquisition speculation.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> said it was considering selling itself or
merging with another company to satisfy the needs of its largest
shareholders, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mexico</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Grupo Televisa SA</ENAMEX> and the family of its
founder, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rene Anselmo</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> hired <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co.</ENAMEX> to
explore the company's options.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> said in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX> it was interested in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX>'s network.
Three of the four <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> satellites were build by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>, and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX> contracted <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> to build satellites that it plans to
launch in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the next few years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The company would be a good fit with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GM</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> or <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral</ENAMEX> because
it's the ``only company, other than <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>, that has a global
fleet currently operating,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Watts</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> is an international telecommunications and broadcast
satellite operator owned by about 139 member countries. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>
operates nine domestic satellites, while <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">GE</ENAMEX> operates 12 domestic
satellites, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Watts</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PanAmSat</ENAMEX>'s four satellites service customers in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Latin America</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">East Asia</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">India</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>, and other areas. The company had
earnings of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$17.5 million</NUMEX> on revenue of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$116 million</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>.
