MISSILE STRIKE DRAWS MIXED REACTION FROM TEXANS IN <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CONGRESS</ENAMEX>
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CHRISTI HARLAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Texans in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that President
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> will have to demonstrate a clear <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> interest in the Iraqi
dispute to keep their support.
<p>
   ``At this point, I think what he's done is correct, and I'm very
hopeful he doesn't try to expand this mission,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kay
Bailey Hutchison</ENAMEX>, R-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Texas</ENAMEX>, a member of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate Armed Services
Committee</ENAMEX>. ``This is not like Desert Storm, and we do not have a
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> security interest there.''
<p>
   At least one Texan, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> Rep. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lamar Smith</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Antonio</ENAMEX>
Republican, was not prepared <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> to support the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> missile
strike.
<p>
   ``We would not be in this position <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> if over the course of
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the last six months</TIMEX> we had sent ge to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Saddam Hussein</ENAMEX> that we
opposed his military buildup,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX> said. ``Suddenly we lurch to
life and launch missiles.
<p>
   ``I have three questions I think need to be answered before the
administration will enjoy my support,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX> said. ``How did we
ever get to the point where we're launching the missiles? And what
happens next? <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Saddam Hussein</ENAMEX> is not known as a rational human being
. . . And why are our allies not supporting us? We've only got one,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Great Britain</ENAMEX>, that supported our action at the time the missiles
were launched.
<p>
   ``This isn't a time to cheer the administration on,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX>
said. ``It's a time to ask questions.''
<p>
   Opposite <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX> was a veteran of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Persian Gulf</ENAMEX> war  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> Rep.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Greg Laughlin</ENAMEX>, a Republican from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">West Columbia</ENAMEX>, a member of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Army Reserve</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Saddam Hussein</ENAMEX> is not to be trusted,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Laughlin</ENAMEX> said. ``The
only thing he understands is force. Certainly, the president did
the right thing in responding.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> did not consult with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> before ordering the
missile strike on Iraqi air defenses, but <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> Rep. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lloyd Doggett</ENAMEX>,
an <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Austin</ENAMEX> Democrat, said he would expect <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> to seek <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>'
OK before taking any further action.
<p>
   ``While this is what I view as a very measured response and
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Saddam</ENAMEX> is the kind of person who only understands force, any
lengthy involvement in a Kurdish civil war definitely requires
consultation with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Doggett</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Phil Gramm</ENAMEX>, R-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Texas</ENAMEX>, said in a statement on the floor
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> that he and others ``owe it to the president to give
him the benefit of the doubt on military matters.''
<p>
   ``Having said that,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gramm</ENAMEX> continued, ``if we look at the
fundamental conflict, it is a conflict between two warring Kurdish
factions, one backed by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iraq</ENAMEX> and one backed by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>, and we do not
have a dog in that fight . . . I think the president would be
poorly advised in becoming involved in that conflict, and I would
not and could not support such an involvement.''
<p>
   (Story Filed By <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The AMERICAN STATESMAN</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">AUSTIN</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TEXAS</ENAMEX>.)
