<PREAMBLE>
BC-MAKING-THE-PITCH-BLOOM
MAKING THE PITCH: SAMPLING PROGRAMS EXPLODING, BENEFITS MIXED
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bernice Kanner</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September 9</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">This summer</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Quaker Oats</ENAMEX>
handed out millions of free Snapple drinks in an effort to
rejuvenate the fruit-based soft drink brand and perhaps justify its
massive purchase price. Anyone living in a state beginning with a
consonant or a vowel qualified.
<p>
   That's just one of many current programs in a sampling industry
that's exploding. In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the past three years</TIMEX>, sampling has grown <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">15 to
20 percent</NUMEX> a year -- faster than any other element of promotion
spending by companies, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lafayette Jones</ENAMEX>, chairman of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Product Sampling Council</ENAMEX> unit of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" MIN="Promotion Marketing Association">Promotion Marketing
Association of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">America</ENAMEX></ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX> estimated that sampling accounts for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$600 million</NUMEX> in
marketing expenses, plus the cost of the products being given away.
And that doesn't include practices like the test drive to sell
cars, which has been on the increase.
<p>
   But there are no assurances that sampling will work and experts
say the best programs are for products with unique features.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX> said depending on what's being sampled, <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX> of
people who sample something actually buy it. Other industry
analysts said a successful sampling program typically converts <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10
percent to 15 percent</NUMEX> of consumers into regular customers.
<p>
   It partly depends on what's being sampled. Nine of every ten
sun-soakers may take a free soda pop at the beach on a hot day
while six to seven of ten women might try a fabric softener mailed
to their homes.
<p>
   One study found it cost more than four times to motivate a
``trier'' using discount coupons -- <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.30</NUMEX> compared with <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">50 cents</NUMEX> --
than with sampling. Converting them to loyalists cost on average
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$6.50</NUMEX>, compared with <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.50</NUMEX> via sampling.
<p>
   Sampling should grow. Some <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">56 percent</NUMEX> of manufacturers planned
to increase their overall sampling budgets <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>, according to
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Donnelley Marketing</ENAMEX>'s Survey of Promotional Practices. The average
company allocated <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10 percent</NUMEX> of its consumer promotion budget to
sampling. Industry executives estimate that <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">20 percent</NUMEX> more
companies are sampling their products <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> than a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">year ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   More than three of every four marketers (<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">78 percent</NUMEX>) consider
sampling an effective way to convince consumers to try established
products, up from <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">63 percent</NUMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Donnelley Marketing</ENAMEX> found.
About <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">75 percent</NUMEX> say it works stimulating trial of new products, up
from <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">60 percent</NUMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Donnelley Marketing</ENAMEX> found that <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">89 percent</NUMEX> of manufacturers use,
or have used, in-store sampling, where typically retailers grant
extra shelf space to products being demonstrated; that <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">53 percent</NUMEX>
attach samples to another product or put a sample inside; and <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">47
percent</NUMEX> have sampled at local events. Some <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">28 percent</NUMEX> distribute
product samples via direct mail and <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">22 percent</NUMEX> mail samples when
consumers request them. <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">Thirteen percent</NUMEX> use newspapers, magazines
and alternate delivery.
<p>
   The fastest growing areas of sampling, according to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">PMA</ENAMEX>, are
complementary packaging and venue-based sampling. ``They minimize
costs and maximize consumer feedback, and aim products at specific
audiences pre-disposed to try its products,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Malls are an ideal place to sample, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Hackett</ENAMEX>, vice
president at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Market Source</ENAMEX>, a marketing company in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cranbury</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
Jersey</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``At malls, <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">70 percent</NUMEX> of shoppers have neither a specific
purchase nor destination in mind,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hackett</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Despite the obvious up-front costs, marketers say sampling is
efficient. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Barbie Gumman</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lakewood</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colorado</ENAMEX>-based
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Promote It International</ENAMEX>, which distributed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jergens</ENAMEX> Shower-Active
moisturizer, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Helene Curtis</ENAMEX>'s Degree antiperspirant, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Quaker</ENAMEX> toasted
oatmeal, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Welch</ENAMEX>'s juice and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kellogg's</ENAMEX> low fat Granola Bars at its
network of 4,000 health clubs, said it costs about a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">nickel</NUMEX> a
sample. But, she said, on average <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">19 percent</NUMEX> of people later buy
the product.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rick Tanner</ENAMEX>, product manager for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">First Brands</ENAMEX>' Glad Bags,
samples of which were bagged with newspapers around <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">St.Louis</ENAMEX>, said
that as a result of that program, ``in a short time, an undeveloped
market became a developed one.'' And <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Taco Bell</ENAMEX> marketers credit its
8 million lunchtime Border Lights taco and burrito give-away at the
chain's 4,500 stores with overcoming perceptions that low fat means
lousy taste.
<p>
   Skeptics need only refer to the launch of the cat litter
category in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1947</TIMEX>, when sand was selling for a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY" MIN="penny">penny a pound</NUMEX> and no
one knew what <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY" MIN="65-cents">65-cents-a-pound</NUMEX> Kitty Litter was. But after inventor
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edward Lowe</ENAMEX> pressured retailers to give away the clay based odor
absorber, customers returned and asked for Kitty Litter by name. It
marked the birth of the brand -- and a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$700 million</NUMEX> category.
</TEXT>
