<DOCID> nyt960909.0500 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1157 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=sci-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MARS</ENAMEX>-MISSIONS-SCI-3RD </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">09-09</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0381 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MARS</ENAMEX>-MISSIONS-SCI-3RDTAKE-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">PASADENA</ENAMEX>: life question.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The committee of 30 government and university scientists and
engineers, led by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McCleese</ENAMEX>, was asked to recommend to the space
agency by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the end of this month</TIMEX> a rationale and strategy for
precursor flights and the sample-return missions.
<p>
   A fairly conservative strategy, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McCleese</ENAMEX> said, would be to
launch a sample-return flight in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2003</TIMEX> as the first of at least
three such missions <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="2011">through 2011</TIMEX>. This would permit sampling visits
to a variety of Martian landscapes, from the ancient highlands
(where the meteorite may have originated) to basins where water
once flowed or regions suspected of holding subsurface reservoirs
of water.
<p>
   If the decision is to launch a sample-return flight in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2003</TIMEX>, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> alone or with international partners would need to
use the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2001</TIMEX> opportunity to place one or two rovers on the surface,
to scoot about gathering rocks in caches for retrieval by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2003</TIMEX>
sample-return mission.
<p>
   A more aggressive strategy might open with two missions in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">2003</TIMEX>
and multiple flights at each subsequent opportunity for a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">decade</TIMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McCleese</ENAMEX> said, or at least send two rovers to collect rocks at
widely diverse sites at each opportunity. The rover that picked up
the most intriguing samples would be paid the visit by the next
return craft. And if one rover should fail, another would be left
to prospect the surface.
<p>
   Although an aggressive approach might be more stimulating,
promising swifter results in the quest for possible Martian life,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NASA</ENAMEX> officials and many scientists are not sure how much it would
cost. But they suspect it would be more than the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> or
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> would sit still for. They are also troubled by the shadow
of the two Viking spacecraft that went to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1976</TIMEX> with
elaborate biology experiments, at a cost of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.5 billion</NUMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX>
dollars, and failed to find unambiguous signs of life.
<p>
   ``We must be careful of walking into the Viking trap,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McCleese</ENAMEX>
mused. ``That mission cost a lot, expectations ran high and
everybody was let down by its failure to find definite signs of
life. It led to the shutting down of our <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mars</ENAMEX> program for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">20 years</TIMEX>.
If we try to go too fast now and promise too much, we could repeat
the Viking experience.''
</TEXT>
